<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cycling Wants Pre-Race Drug Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERONA, Italy (AP) -- Faced with growing costs of largely  
ineffective anti-drug tests, the International Cycling Union will 
place more emphasis on prerace medical controls, the governing 
body's president said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hein Verbruggen, speaking after an ICU congress at the World  
Championships, said the difficulty in catching drug cheats was ``a 
major problem'' for the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must reflect on the great number of cases undetected by  
anti-doping tests, which are very costly,'' Verbruggen said. ``In 
the future we must give more emphasis to medical controls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-drug tests, mainly from urine samples, cost the ICU $2.7  
million a year -- money he said would be better spent on blood tests 
that measure the red blood cell count. 
</P>
<P>
	A high count can occur naturally, but also signal the use of the  
banned growth hormone EPO. Under ICU rules, a cyclist can be kept 
out of competition for at least two weeks -- officially, in an 
effort to safeguard the athlete's health -- if the red blood cell 
level exceeds 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A cyclist from Moldova was banned from Wednesday's elite men's  
time trial at the championships following a prerace blood test. 
</P>
<P>
	The most prominent rider sidelined this year was 1998 Tour de  
France and Giro d'Italia champion Marco Pantani. He was kicked out 
of the Giro in June, hours before the start of the next-to-last 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Verbruggen said the ICU wants to standardize testing procedures  
around the world as of January, but it will not object if national 
Olympic committees or cycling federations choose to independently 
adopt more stringent testing policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Luckily the popularity of our sport continues to be very  
good,'' he said, ``and let's hope that the problem of doping is 
going to vanish in the coming years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On other issues, Verbruggen said:  
</P>
<P>
	-- The International Olympic Committee has authorized the ICU to  
administer blood tests on cyclists at next year's Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	-- ICU members are divided over whether to drop caffeine and  
other light stimulants from the list of banned substances. In the 
coming months, an ICU commission will discuss the possibility of 
handing offenders a warning rather than an immediate suspension for 
such substances. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want two extra cups of coffee to influence multistage  
races such as the Giro d'Italia, Tour of France or Vuelta,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By the end of January, the ICU will decide whether to erase  
all of the sport's standing world records to start the millennium 
with a clean slate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
