<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ramsey Grand Jury May Report Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- The grand jury investigating the death of  
JonBenet Ramsey was scheduled to meet today and Friday, and one 
adviser says he knows of no further meetings set for the group. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would not be surprised if there wasn't some kind of  
announcement next week, as opposed to waiting until the 20th or 
even the week of the 20th,'' Adams County District Attorney Bob 
Grant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, one of four metro-area prosecutors who have advised  
District Attorney Alex Hunter on the case, was referring to the 
legally mandated conclusion of the grand jury's term. It was 
originally set to end April 21, but a judge extended it at the 
prosecution's request to Oct. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-year-old JonBenet was found strangled, beaten and her wrists  
bound with cord in her home on Dec. 26, 1996. Her millionaire 
parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, have been identified as suspects 
but maintain they are innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the grand jurors were spotted at the Boulder County  
Justice Center on Wednesday, all appearing to leave by 
midafternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzanne Laurion, spokeswoman for Hunter's office, said, ``It  
would be my thinking that perhaps an explanation today is that a 
review session was scheduled.'' The grand jury has held several 
informal evidence review sessions since it began meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bipartisan Agreement on Tax Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats and Republicans on a key Senate  
committee largely agree that an expired business research tax 
credit should be made permanent, but they are far apart on how to 
pay for it. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, there is disagreement on the Senate Finance  
Committee about whether average taxpayers who claim personal 
credits should get permanent or temporary protection from the 
complex alternative minimum tax. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all a matter of money,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick  
Moynihan, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans want to use projected budget surpluses to offset  
most of the cost of a five-year, $28.7 billion proposal from 
Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del. In addition to the 
permanent AMT fix and research credit, Roth's bill would extend 
several other business credits by five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats are developing an alternative of up to $20 billion  
that raises the money through other tax increases. Aside from the 
permanent research credit, it renews most of the other credits for 
a shorter time and would only fix AMT temporarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither party's lawmakers want an estimated 1 million taxpayers  
to face higher alternative minimum taxes just for claiming breaks 
such as the $500 per child tax credit on their federal returns. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats, led by President Clinton, are resisting any tax  
package that would spend projected budget surpluses, as Roth's bill 
would in four of the five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going along with anything that isn't paid for,'' said  
Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats had identified $19.9 billion in offsets to pay for  
their bill, including closing corporate tax shelters, renewal of a 
Superfund environmental cleanup tax and a modification of foreign 
tax credits, said Finance Committee sources who spoke on condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth is proposing only to offset the fiscal 2000 cost of $1.7  
billion -- the GOP needs that money for spending on government 
programs -- by increasing estimated tax payment requirements for 
people earning $150,000 or more. In addition, companies would be 
prevented from claiming the research credit until Oct. 1, 2000, 
when the 2001 fiscal year begins. A House GOP version totaling 
$23.3 billion also would spend surplus money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has threatened to veto the bill if it  
spends the surplus before Social Security and Medicare are 
safeguarded for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the measure  
could prove too popular to kill. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the president wants to veto the R&AMP;D tax credit ... go right  
ahead. His days are numbered anyway,'' Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth's bill also includes five-year extensions for credits  
businesses can claim if they hire workers from certain 
disadvantaged or ethnic groups and those coming off welfare. The 
House version has 30-month extensions. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure includes a five-year extension of a credit for  
electricity produced by wind and certain kinds of biological 
material -- including a poultry waste provision sought by Roth for 
Delaware's chicken producers. These provisions are not in the House 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Both bills would extend an oil and gas investment deduction and  
an exemption for foreign corporate income from banking, insurance 
or finance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Roth bill also would make permanent a deduction for  
employers who pay education expenses for their workers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 06:10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scots Give U.S. Muted Reception  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Americans Tom Lehman, Payne Stewart  
and Mark O'Meara, playing for the first time in Europe since their 
controversial Ryder Cup win, got a muted but polite reception from 
Scottish golf fans as the Dunhill Cup began today. 
</P>
<P>
	Applause was light -- particularly for Lehman -- but there was no  
hint of fans trying to get even for the behavior of their American 
counterparts at the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the weather cooperated on a sunny fall day with light  
breezes wafting in off the Firth of Tay. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different kind of golf fan you've got here,'' said  
Chris Bell, applauding as Lehman rolled a long approach putt on No. 
3 at the Old Course to within inches. Lehman faced New Zealand's 
Michale Campbell in his match. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate our golf here, and we'll never forgive the  
supporters. The American fans were out of order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All three Americans were mobbed for autographs today at the  
practice green, mostly by excited teen-age boys. Only their accents 
belied they were Scottish. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they cheated, but I wanted a memento,'' said 14-year-old  
Paul Jensen, showing off autographs from Lehman and O'Meara. ``We 
got no problems with Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His friend, Stuart Adamson, 15, was hoping to see one more  
American. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish Tiger was playing, he's brilliant,'' Adamson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Almost two weeks after the Americans pulled off the greatest  
comeback in Ryder Cup history, they're still disparaged in Britain 
for the way they did it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lehman the monster asks for forgiveness as he enters the  
lion's den,'' The London Daily Mail said on Wednesday, describing 
the former British Open champion as the ``Ryder Cup bete noire'' 
and ripping the Americans for ``playing fast and loose'' with golf 
etiquette. 
</P>
<P>
	An openly religious man, Lehman wants forgiveness from the  
European fans and Ryder Cup players, 10 of whom are in the 
four-day, 16-nation Dunhill Cup. The British media has been rough 
on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``What better place to come and set things straight than St.  
Andrews,'' said Lehman, speaking just a wedge away from the famous 
stone clubhouse of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club -- the venerable 
custodian of the game's rules and etiquette. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's of concern to me that my reputation has been somewhat  
damaged,'' said Lehman, whose behavior was called ``disgusting'' by 
European assistant captain Sam Torrance when the American led a 
charge across the 17th green in a premature victory celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never walked on anybody's line,'' Lehman said. ``I'm not a  
monster. I'm not a rogue. I'm not a hooligan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman said he ``sent letters to the people I want to deal with  
directly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal of the letters that I wrote and the phone calls I  
made was that we can leave friends. I definitely don't think it's 
worth losing friendships over a golf tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to let you know the Americans and myself are very  
much aware of the honor and courtesy of golf, the history of 
golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torrance is playing for Scotland following the withdrawal of  
Colin Montgomerie with a dental problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The withdrawal of Europe's No. 1-ranked player wiped out any  
possible showdown with American golfers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans and Scots are two of the four seeded teams and  
could face each other in Sunday's semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart and O'Meara, lauded in the British press for being  
gracious in victory, blamed a handful of fans for problems that saw 
Jane James -- the wife of European captain Mark James -- spit on, and 
American caddie Jerry Higginbotham beat up for carrying the bag of 
a Spain's Sergio Garcia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably 80 to 100 of those 30,000 were not true golf fans ...  
and they treated the Ryder Cup as they would treat going to a 
football game, or a basketball game or a hockey game,'' Stewart 
said. ``They don't understand the etiquette that's involved in the 
game of golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it was horrible the way everybody was treated,'' O'Meara  
admitted. ``Because of eight or 20 or 12 fans, you don't label all 
Americans, the whole Ryder Cup as being a disgrace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman called some of the partisan cheering ``inevitable'' as  
the United States rallied on the final day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very sorry for running out on the 17th green, we're very  
sorry if ... you thought we haven't respected you (European 
players),'' Lehman said. ``It was never the intention to show any 
lack of respect or lack of courtesy. 
</P>
<P>
	``But in the excitement of the day, the excitement of the  
moment, things just spilled out. ... We can't do anything about it, 
we don't feel good about it, we just have to go on and get over 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Bonallack, the just-retired secretary of the Royal and  
Ancient who likened The Country Club in Brookline, Mass., to a 
``bearpit,'' said no extra security was planned on this ancient 
links guarded jealously by winds off the Firth of Tay. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman has already had problems off the course. Lost luggage  
forced him to play a practice round Tuesday in jeans, breaking the 
club's strict dress code. Royal and Ancient officials later said 
he'd been given dispensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman was also reportedly accused by golf broadcaster and  
former Ryder Cup player Peter Alliss of changing his character from 
unassuming to demanding since winning the British Open in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't comment on any of this until I have spoken to Peter  
and ask him if he made these comments,'' Lehman said. ``Anyone who 
knows me knows that I do not go around demanding this and that. 
It's a load of bunkum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is seeded No. 1 in the tournament, followed by  
No. 2 Spain -- with Ryder Cup stars Jose Maria Olazabal, Miguel 
Angel Jimenez and Sergio Garcia -- followed by two-time defending 
champion South Africa and Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	In other pairings today, it was Sweden vs. Italy, Scotland vs.  
Paraguay, Australia vs. Japan, South Africa vs. China, England vs. 
India, Spain vs. France and Ireland vs. Zimbabwe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
