<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Wrestler Gorilla Monsoon Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLINGBORO, N.J. (AP) -- Robert ``Gorilla Monsoon'' Marella, a  
true giant of professional wrestling who body-slammed Muhammad Ali 
and debated Jesse Ventura, has died of a heart ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	The 62-year-old former teacher, died Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6, 400-pound Marella turned to the pro wrestling game  
in 1960 when a promoter offered him $500 per week to don the 
tights. 
</P>
<P>
	As Gorilla Monsoon, Marella soon shared world tag-team titles  
with Walter ``Killer'' Kowalski and ``Cowboy'' Bill Watts. Playing 
a villain's role at the time, Marella gained notoriety for his feud 
with longtime champ Bruno Sammartino. 
</P>
<P>
	Marella's career in the ring lasted until the early 1980s, when  
he became one of the World Wrestling Federation's top ringside 
television announcers. He co-hosted WWF telecasts at a time when 
the high-flying entertainment genre was booming in popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	Marella frequently shared the microphone with former wrestler  
Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura, with whom he often argued over the 
importance of fair play in the ring. Ventura now is governor of 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger generation of wrestlers was honored to have the  
rotund Marella analyze their moves and holds, said fellow pro 
wrestler King Kong Bundy. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was somebody who knew the business,'' Bundy said. ``A great  
guy, a real class act all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marella also wrote a weekly pro wrestling column for the  
now-defunct Philadelphia Bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
	A son, Joey Marella, became a WWF referee in the 1980s. He died  
in an auto accident in Burlington in 1994. Thereafter, Robert 
Marella appeared on television less frequently. 
</P>
<P>
	``When his son got killed in a car accident, I think that took a  
lot out of him,'' King Kong Bundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marella did serve as interim president of the WWF in 1997 -- at a  
time when the industry admitted openly that the outcomes of its 
matches are scripted. 
</P>
<P>
	Heart problems forced Marella to scale back his work with the  
WWF. He also suffered from diabetes in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ali's Daughter Making Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERONA, N.Y. (AP) -- With a grin, Laila Ali predicted a win. In  
her mind, the bout will be a rout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to knock her out,'' Laila said Thursday on the eve  
of her first professional boxing match. ``I'm coming to knock 
somebody out, not just to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laila, the second-youngest of Muhammad Ali's nine children, will  
make her debut tonight at Turning Stone Casino against April 
Fowler, a veteran of one pro fight. Laila promised that her 
infectious smile, which lit up a room full of microphones and 
cameras, would soon disappear. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see me tomorrow, you're going to see a whole 'nother  
look,'' she promised. ``Right now, I have cameras in my face and 
I'm a very charming person. That other side of me is showing, but 
tomorrow is going to be a whole 'nother story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old Fowler was not impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't tell me it was her for two weeks,'' Fowler said.  
``When I accepted the fight, I did not know it was her. After I 
found out it was her, I freaked out. Then after they told me she's 
never even been in the ring, I kind of eased up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fowler, who lost her debut way back in March 1998, came dressed  
in black. If she was nervous, she easily hid any anxiety behind a 
pair of dark sunglasses. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just a name to me,'' said the 5-foot-6 native of  
Michigan City, Ind., who weighed in at just under 164 pounds. ``I'm 
not getting in the ring with her father, I'm getting in the ring 
with her. The pressure's not on me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laila was all too aware of that. Because of the hoopla, she has  
requested that the fight not be shown on television or videotaped. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's enough pressure on me as it is,'' said the 5-foot-10  
Laila, who weighed in at 168. ``I've said what I have to say. Now I 
have to deliver. I don't know exactly how I'm going to feel, but 
I'm comfortable in the ring. It will be a new feeling for me. I 
know what I'm capable of doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight will be staged in a 2,600-seat auditorium, and 600  
tickets were still available late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Providing room for the media promised to be more challenging  
than attaining a sellout. Promoter Mike Acri said about 90 
journalists from faraway places such as France, Germany, Italy, 
Sweden, Holland, Brazil and Japan will be there to record the 
moment. 
</P>
<P>
	The headliner of the seven-bout card understood all the fuss.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know you guys are not here for me,'' said 34-year-old  
Donovan ``Razor'' Ruddock, who will continue his comeback against 
journeyman Jose Ribalta in a 10-round bout. ``She's taking all my 
press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laila said her mother, Veronica, the third of Muhammad Ali's  
four wives, will be there, but she wasn't sure about her father. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like my father to be here, but it goes two ways,''  
said Laila, who operates a nail salon in Los Angeles in her spare 
time. ``Even though he's my dad and he's around me and my boxing 
career, it makes me nervous because he is the greatest and I feel 
like I can't do things wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That her parents weren't thrilled with her decision to box was  
not an issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm totally fine with the fact that he doesn't really want me  
to box,'' said Laila, 21, who was too young to see her father fight 
in person. ``He'd rather me just go to school like I was going to. 
He doesn't want me to get hurt, but he never once told me not to 
box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So box she will.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll feel better about this whole thing after I fight because  
there's so many questions, so many people wondering, so many 
expectations,'' said Laila, who was 7 when her parents divorced. 
``I'm the one you guys are going to be looking at. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, I don't feel like everyone's here for just me.  
It's the name. That is what puts the pressure on me. I'm always 
going to be recognized as Muhammad Ali's daughter. I can't say, `I 
want everyone just to see me for me' because that's not going to 
happen until I do what I need to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
