<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Diageo Getting New CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British food and beverages group Diageo PLC said  
today that the head of its Pillsbury subsidiary will become its 
next chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Pillsbury chief Paul Walsh, 44, will succeed Diageo's John  
McGrath, who is to retire at the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Diageo, which owns well-known brands such as Burger King and  
Johnnie Walker whiskies, said Walsh will become its chief operating 
officer at the beginning of next year. He will succeed McGrath in 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	John Lilly, president of Pillsbury North America, will succeed  
Walsh as Pillsbury's chief executive at the beginning of January. 
Lilly will also be appointed to Diageo's executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Diageo, which was formed by the merger of Grand Metropolitan and  
Guinness in 1997, has been selling assets and transforming into a 
more focused business ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	Diageo also confirmed that Lord Blyth of Rowington, the former  
chairman of the pharmacy chain Boots, will succeed Sir Anthony 
Greener as chairman of Diageo after Greener retires next June. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
