<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Helps Cover Immigrant Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government would reimburse state  
and local governments for $1.6 billion more in costs associated 
with illegal immigration under a Senate GOP plan introduced 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, sponsored by Arizona Republican Sens. Jon Kyl and John  
McCain, would spend the money over four years to pay for emergency 
medical care for illegal immigrants and processing illegal aliens 
who commit crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government already reimburses state and local  
governments for jailing criminal aliens, a $585 million program 
that Kyl said only provides 40 percent of the actual costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Border states such as Arizona ``are losing millions of dollars a  
year of expenses they incur because of the federal government's 
inability to control the borders,'' Kyl said. Getting Congress to 
approve the money ``won't be easy,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will not be enough money,'' Kyl said. ``We're just trying  
to reduce the burden on the states that are bearing the brunt of 
this illegal immigration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kyl-McCain proposal would make the money available to the 17  
states with the biggest illegal immigration problems. It would 
provide $200 million a year from 2001 through 2004 for processing 
criminal aliens and $200 million a year for medical care -- 
primarily emergency care -- to illegal aliens. 
</P>
<P>
	Border states and counties have complained for years that they  
are being overwhelmed by the costs of jailing, educating and 
providing medical care for illegal immigrants. California, Arizona, 
Texas, Florida, New York and New Jersey all sued the federal 
government to force it to reimburse some or all of those costs, but 
federal courts rejected those lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	In Santa Cruz County, Ariz., for example, a study found that  
34.4 cents of every dollar the county spends on law enforcement and 
the justice system goes to processing illegal immigrants. That 
includes about $1.1 million of the $2.7 million sheriff's budget 
and more than half of the county's court budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Those costs ``are a federal responsibility and should not be  
shirked by those in Washington who don't live with the problem of 
illegal immigration in their midst,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	An immigrant advocate also said he agreed with making the  
federal government pay more of those costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The federal government collects more taxes from immigrants  
than state and local governments do,'' said Thomas Saenz, a lawyer 
with the Mexican American Legal Defense Fund in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-sponsors of the plan include Sens. Kay Bailey Hutchison,  
R-Texas; Pete Domenici, R-N.M.; Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; and Dianne 
Feinstein, D-Calif. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
