<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 13:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Test Ban Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *BARRY SCHWEID   	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton urged the Senate on Thursday  
to ``do what's right for America'' and ratify an international ban 
on nuclear weapons tests. Facing potential rejection of the treaty, 
Clinton hoped for postponement of a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives the people who made early commitments, I think  
wrongly, but they did it, the chance to move to doing the Senate's 
business the way the Senate should do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Senate votes on and rejects the treaty next week, it  
would be the first time in modern history an arms control pact was 
turned down on Capitol Hill. It also could signal the collapse of 
bipartisan support for arms control in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, trying to reverse the tide, invoked a ``moral  
responsibility for future generations'' even as supporters conceded 
there seemed little chance to muster the two-thirds vote needed for 
Senate approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said the treaty ``gives us tools to strengthen our  
security'' and ``to throw away these tools will ensure more testing 
and more development of more sophisticated and more dangerous 
nuclear weapons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking before a political fund-raising trip to New York,  
Clinton said ``future generations won't forgive us if we fail that 
responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he was not trying to ``beat up'' Republican  
opponents but was asking that ``we do what is in the national 
interest. Let's just do what's right for America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is bigger than party politics,'' he said. ``This is  
bigger than personal politics. This is about America's future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright planned a pitch for the  
treaty before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., told the committee there was precedent  
for delaying the vote, citing the treaty to ban chemical weapons. 
Levin said a delay would give senators more time to propose changes 
in the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. of Delaware, the senior Democrat on  
the committee, said he was ready to vote now. ``The single-most 
important thing this committee can do is to attend to this 
treaty,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposing the treaty, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said the  
approval of 30 nations would be required to carry out an on-site 
inspection, thereby permitting opponents of the United States to 
block monitoring of suspicious activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, meanwhile, told the Senate  
Armed Services Committee that rejection of the 154-nation 
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty ``would announce that the United 
States refuses to lead on this issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Testing is not needed to make sure U.S. nuclear weapons would  
work, Richardson said. The nuclear stockpile is ``safe, secure and 
reliable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Republican and Democratic leaders sought ways to postpone  
a vote, a group of conservatives led by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., 
kept up pressure for proceeding. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has rejected their demand that Clinton put in  
writing any request to delay a vote on an international nuclear 
test ban treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservatives also want Clinton to promise -- in writing --  
not to seek to revive the treaty during the 2000 presidential 
election year, a condition the White House has also rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., served notice on  
Senate leaders that he planned to block any effort to postpone a 
vote, whether Clinton seeks it in writing or not. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has made the treaty a top priority ``and  
should live with the consequences,'' Inhofe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats acknowledged there seemed to be little way either to  
win ratification or persuade Republican leaders to postpone the 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to kill it, I guess they can do it,'' Biden told  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty has virtually no Republican support.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
