<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian shares ended higher Thursday on Wall  
Street's gains, while the region's biggest market, Tokyo, rose for 
the sixth straight session on growing optimism about Japan's 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
240.13 points, or 1.34 percent, to close at 18,136.55. The average 
had risen 0.63 percent on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is pretty strong. The outlook for the Japanese  
economy is bright,'' said Sachio Ishikawa of Chuo Securities in 
Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent positive signs -- such as two straight quarters of  
economic growth -- have fueled optimism that Japan may have 
weathered the worst of its downturn. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was trading at 107.92 yen  
on the Tokyo foreign exchange market late Thursday afternoon, up 
0.56 yen from late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing that a strong yen could hamper economic recovery,  
Japan's vice finance minister Haruhiko Kuroda said Thursday that 
the strengthening of the yen has eased slightly. A stronger yen 
makes Japanese goods less competitive abroad and could hurt 
corporate earnings if sales suffer as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares closed higher although prices were unable  
to hold onto big early gains that followed Wall Street's overnight 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index rose 95.22 points, or 0.7 percent, to close  
at 13,113.20. 
</P>
<P>
	The index had gained 0.1 percent on Wednesday and investors  
started a buying spree early Thursday that pushed the blue chips up 
1.8 percent by midday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders had taken their cue from the 1.8 percent gain of the Dow  
Jones industrial average in New York on Wednesday, but prices 
drifted lower in the afternoon in the absence of any domestic 
market-moving news. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose on gains on Wall Street and other regional  
markets. The SET index gained 2.55 points, or 0.65 percent, to end 
at 397.64. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell as investors cashed in on recent gains. The  
JSX Composite Index fell 3.404 points, or 0.6 percent, to 585.345. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose 2.9 percent on optimism over possible  
elections and Malaysia's bank merger plan. The Composite Index rose 
20.54 points to 734.73. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose on Wall Street's overnight gains. The PSE  
Index ended up 14.11 points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,071.64. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares climbed 1.5 percent as Wall Street's rally lured  
investors into the Taiwanese market. The Weighted Price Index rose 
110.37 points to 7,612.00. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on strong gains in the futures market. The  
All Ordinaries Index rose 15.2 points, or 0.5 percent, at 2,912. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares surged 1.9 percent on strong economic forecasts  
from the central bank. The Kospi index rose 15.84 points to 851.15. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on institutional buying of blue-chips.  
The Straits Times Index rose 19.26 points, or 0.92 percent, at 
2,119.97 points. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on hefty gains by market heavyweight  
Telecom Corp. of New Zealand. The NZSE-40 closed up 11.88 points, 
or 0.6 percent, at 2,041.35. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
