<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Playoffs Feature Tough Pitching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Same story.  
</P>
<P>
	Different ending.  
</P>
<P>
	As the results from baseball's postseason trickle in, this much  
is already apparent: Pitching still dominates, but it's just not 
the dominant pitchers we expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The name ``Cy Young'' turns up in Greg Maddux's trophy case  
almost as many times as his own. But who won the first real 
must-win game Atlanta faced this year? 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Millwood.  
</P>
<P>
	And while even casual fans should recognize the only member of  
the Braves' staff with an outside shot at the Cy Young award this 
season, it's hard to look past the Big Three of Maddux, Tom Glavine 
and John Smoltz and settle on Millwood's name. Not that pitching 
coach Leo Mazzone had trouble finding the youngster. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been our best starter all year,'' Mazzone said very  
matter-of-factly after Millwood threw a complete-game, one-hitter 
to even the division series with Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``And considering the company he keeps,'' Mazzone added,  
``that's saying something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It may say something about the Braves as well.  
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta is making an unprecedented eighth straight run into the  
postseason, but has only one World Series title to show for it. As 
much as the Big Three dominate the regular season -- they own seven 
Cy Youngs between them -- Smoltz is the only one who remains just as 
unbeatable in the postseason, 11-3 for his career. 
</P>
<P>
	After losing Game 1, Maddux, the best pitcher of his era, is a  
very average 9-9 in the postseason (with one save); Glavine, an 
even less-impressive 9-11. 
</P>
<P>
	But Atlanta isn't the only town where it pays dividends to pay  
attention to who's pitching once the regular season is done. 
</P>
<P>
	At $8.25 million, Roger Clemens is the most expensive pitcher on  
the Yankees' staff. But he won't get the ball until Game 3 for a 
very good reason. Clemens' postseason mark in nine starts is 1-2. 
Compare that with New York's Game 1 winner, Orlando Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	`El Duque'' cost the club $2.2 million last season, but that  
only hints at the bargain he's become. In three career postseason 
starts, he's 3-0 and has allowed just one run in 22 innings. But 
even he may not turn out to be the bargain of the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans in Cleveland like to call Bartolo Colon a younger version  
of Boston ace Pedro Martinez. But until they hooked up in the 
opener of the Red Sox-Indians division series, the comparisons were 
hardly flattering. 
</P>
<P>
	Colon, who makes just $625,000, had been matched up three times  
during the regular season against Martinez, who makes $12.5 
million. And when Colon departed Game 1 after allowing just five 
hits and two runs in eight innings, he still hadn't beaten Boston. 
But he left the Indians in much better shape than did Martinez, who 
strained his back while covering first base on a routine grounder 
to the right side. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk about a shift in momentum. There were two very unsettling  
jinxes colliding in the game. On one side was the Red Sox' 1-17 
postseason streak, dating back to Bill Buckner's miscue in the 1986 
World Series. The one win, coincidentally enough, belonged to 
Martinez and came against Cleveland in the opener of last year's 
series. On the other side was the Indians' streak of eight straight 
losses in playoff openers. 
</P>
<P>
	So relieved were the Indians fans to see Martinez go that they  
greeted Boston reliever Derek Lowe with an ovation. They must have 
known something, because Lowe was even tougher on the Indians' 
lineup than Martinez during the regular season, holding them to a 
1-for-30 performance. 
</P>
<P>
	But this being the postseason, Jim Thome hit a two-out, two-run,  
game-tying homer off Lowe in the next inning and the Indians 
eventually won on Travis Fryman's RBI in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	The momentum spilled into Thursday and threatened to become an  
avalanche when Boston announced Martinez wouldn't be available 
until Game 5 -- assuming the series stretches that far. 
</P>
<P>
	Few people intimidate hitters more than Martinez, but Randy  
Johnson, Arizona's 6-foot-10 left-hander, has to be one of them. 
Johnson is also one of the few NL pitchers to have a better season 
than Millwood -- they finished 1-2 in the ERA race, and could do the 
same in Cy Young balloting. But the postseason might turn out to be 
another story. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's loss in Game 1 of the Mets-Diamondbacks series was his  
sixth straight in the postseason, a major league record. The game 
wasn't decided until Johnson left after walking Melvin Mora in the 
ninth. Arizona manager Buck Showalter went to Bobby Chouinard, then 
played a hunch and let him face red-hot Edgar Alfonzo, instead of 
using closer Matt Mantei. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like he was best suited for the situation,'' Showalter  
said after Alfonzo hit a grand slam off Chouinard. ``He's done the 
job for us most of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe that should have been the tip-off.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
