<DOCNO> APW19991007.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 00:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Leaning Toward Reform Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan says  
he is likely to leave the GOP to seek the Reform Party's nomination 
-- a move he says has ``the Washington establishment in mortal 
terror.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting Wednesday morning with Reform Party chairman  
Russell Verney, Buchanan said he is ``leaning toward'' mounting a 
third-party presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real possibility,'' he said at a book-signing after the  
hourlong meeting. ``We are looking into it very hard right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan said political attacks on him and the Reform Party show  
that Democrats and Republicans fear a viable third-party candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a fear on the part of the establishment that maybe  
this time a third-party candidate who gets in the debates will walk 
away with the presidency of the United States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, who twice has sought the Republican nomination, plans  
to announce a decision by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney said that while Reform Party officials have not endorsed  
a candidate, Buchanan has enough grassroots support to petition to 
compete in the 30 state primaries in which the Reform Party is not 
automatically on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	The party will choose a nominee at a national convention next  
August. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker also is considering  
seeking the party's nomination. Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the 
highest elected Reform Party member, is cool to a Buchanan 
candidacy and has urged real estate tycoon Donald Trump to run. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump, interviewed Wednesday on ``Dateline NBC,'' said he feared  
that if Buchanan joined the Reform Party he would move the party to 
the fringes and make it less appealing to mainstream candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trump said he would not run simply to thwart Buchanan.  
</P>
<P>
	``That wouldn't be the reason I'd run,'' he said. ``I wouldn't  
run unless I really thought I had a chance to win the entire 
election. It wouldn't be worth it to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reform Party founder Ross Perot has not ruled out a third  
presidential race, although members of the splinter American Reform 
Party already have voiced opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Perot did not meet with Buchanan Wednesday and plans to stay  
silent throughout the nominating process, Verney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan said if he were to win the nomination, the party's  
rolls would grow as disenchanted Republicans and Democrats seek 
alternative candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Republican front-runner George W. Bush, Buchanan said the  
Texas governor is unprepared for the nation's highest office. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is his depth, his knowledge, his wisdom,''  
Buchanan said. ``The governor has not exhibited any depth on 
foreign policy whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the criticism Buchanan's book, ``A Republic, Not an  
Empire, has received for questioning U.S. involvement in World War 
II, hundreds of book buyers waited in line for hours to meet 
Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Sprouse, a 60-year-old telecommunications worker from  
Garland, said he traditionally has voted Republican but would 
change his party allegiance if Buchanan ran on the Reform Party 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd vote for the man, not the party,'' said Sprouse. ``America  
needs a choice.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
