<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rookie, Veteran Look To Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More Than Ready, a rookie, and Yagli, a veteran,  
will try to bounce back from defeat in two Grade I stakes Saturday 
at Belmont Park and re-establish their standing as major players in 
the Breeders' Cup races. 
</P>
<P>
	More Than Ready, who lost for the first time in six starts when  
he finished third, beaten only a half-length in the one-mile 
Futurity on Sept. 19 at Belmont, will oppose six other 2-year-old 
colts in the 1 1-16-mile Champagne. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory probably would make More Than Ready the favorite for  
the 1 1-16-mile Breeders' Cup Juvenile on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-year-old Yagli also will be looking to re-establish  
himself as the likely horse to beat in the 1 1/2-mile Breeders' Cup 
Turf by beating six rivals in the 1 1/2-mile Turf Classic 
Invitational. In his last start, he had a three-race winning streak 
snapped when he finished seventh in the Sword Dancer on Aug. 14 at 
Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The Champagne and Turf Classic are two of five Grade I weekend  
stakes at Belmont that will serve as Breeders' Cup preps. 
</P>
<P>
	Contested on Sunday will be the 1 1/4-mile Jockey Club Gold Cup,  
the 1 1/8-mile Beldame for fillies and mares and the 1 1-16-mile 
Frizette for 2-year-old fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid, the Belmont Stakes and Travers winner, will make  
his debut against older horses, including Behrens, the handicap 
division leader, in the weight-for-age Jockey Club Gold Cup. The 
sensational Silverbulletday also will make her debut against older 
fillies and mares in the Beldame. Entries for all three Sunday 
races were to be taken today. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's races will be part of an ESPN-2 telecast from 4  
p.m.-5:30 p.m. EDT. The three Sunday stakes will be televised by 
NBC from 2:30 p.m.-4 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best 2-year-old race of the year,'' said John Kimmel,  
trainer of Champagne starter Chief Seattle, who finished fourth in 
the 1-mile Futurity, in which More Than Ready was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Others entered Thursday in the $400,000 Champagne were High  
Yield, winner of the Hopeful at Saratoga; Bulling, third in the 
Sanford and fourth in the Saratoga Special; Greenwood Lake; 
Settlement, the Hopeful runnerup; and Traditionally, making his 
stakes debut. Each starter will carry 122 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``By far, he is the horse I'm most concerned about,'' Kimmel  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More Than Ready was supposed to start in the Hopeful, but got a  
fever and was taken out of training briefly. The Futurity was the 
first start in 52 days for the colt. Three of his five wins were in 
the six-furlong Sanford on July 29 and earlier in the Flash and 
Tremont at Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bill Mott-trained Yagli, being pointed to the Breeders' Cup  
Turf, won the Gulfstream Park Handicap, Manhattan Handicap at 
Belmont and the United Nations Handicap at Monmouth Park before 
finishing seventh in the Sword Dancer on Aug. 14 at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Yagli's rivals will be Val's Prince and Single Empire,  
1-2 in the 1 3/8-mile Man o'War on Sept. 11 at Belmont. Two others 
will be Dream Well, a stakes winner in France and third in the 
Irish Champion Stakes, and Sunshine Street, fourth in the Irish 
Champion, both of whom will be making their U.S. debuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing the field for the $600,000 Turf Classic are Fahris  
and Star Performance. Each starter will carry 126 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Others entered in the $600,000 Turf Classic are Fahris, Star  
Performance, Dream Well, Single Empire and Sunshine Street. Each 
starter will carry 126 pounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
