<HEADLINE> Air Force Launches Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The Air Force today launched a $42  
million navigation satellite aboard a Delta rocket that was 
supposed to carry up a different spacecraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boeing-built rocket should have lifted off earlier this year  
with another Global Positioning System satellite. But that 
satellite was damaged on the launch pad in May when rain leaked 
onto it. 
</P>
<P>
	A new GPS satellite was loaded onto the rocket, which soared at  
8:51 a.m. following multiple weather delays. The successful launch 
brought the number of operational GPS satellites in orbit to 28. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the Air Force's first launch from Cape Canaveral since  
a Titan rocket dumped a military communication satellite into the 
wrong orbit back in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force hopes to launch the rain-damaged satellite next  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Global Positioning System, originally designed for the  
military to pinpoint locations, is booming in the commercial 
market, too. Many luxury cars have GPS devices to help drivers find 
a route, and they are also used by aviators, boaters and even 
hikers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
