<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Wants To Aid Working Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PETERBOROUGH, N.H. (AP) -- Offering relief to parents juggling  
jobs and families, Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley 
today proposed a $26 billion program of education grants for 
parents and children and an expanded family and medical leave law. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a plan that looks ahead to our long-term interests in  
human terms not just economic ones,'' Bradley said in remarks 
prepared for a campaign speech today at New Hampshire's Contoocook 
Valley Regional High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Nostlagic for his boyhood family dinners at a reliable 6:30 p.m.  
sharp, Bradley painted a familiar modern-day American portrait -- 
Dad working late, Mom at a meeting, kids dashing to the microwave. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new global economy just doesn't care about the 6:30 dinner  
hour,'' Bradley said, adding a poke at the Clinton-Gore 
administration's boast of economic success. ``A prosperity that 
fails to bolster families is a hollow and unsustainable one,'' 
Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The $26 billion, 10-year cost of new grants for early childhood  
education and parent-friendly community colleges would be paid for 
-- like his $65 billion-per-year universal health plan -- from the 
federal budget surplus that is projected to reach about $1 trillion 
over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Also included in the package is an older-person's version of  
President Clinton's ``Americorps.'' With a goal of enlisting 
500,000 volunteers over three years, Bradley would offer a tax-free 
stipend of up to $200 a month to senior citizens who give at least 
15 hours per week to approved nonprofit youth programs such as the 
YMCA, Boys and Girls Clubs, school tutoring, or faith-based 
mentoring. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all in this together,'' said the former senator from  
New Jersey. ``And what individual families cannot build on their 
own, we can all build together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing a proposal voiced by Vice President Al Gore on Tuesday,  
Bradley said he would expand to workers in firms at least 25 
employees the popular Family and Medical Leave Act. The 1993 law, 
which currently applies only to businesses with 50 or more workers, 
guarantees them 12 weeks' unpaid leave to tend to a new child, a 
seriously ill family member or their own personal illness. 
</P>
<P>
	He said workers also should be given an additional 24 hours each  
year to meet other family obligations, such as attending 
parent-teacher conferences, taking a child to the dentist or 
helping an elderly relative with medical appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley aides appeared caught off guard when told late Wednesday  
that Gore, Bradley's rival for the Democratic presidential 
nomination next year, had articulated the same proposed changes to 
the family-leave law at a New York fund-raiser a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's plan would give $2 billion per year to state and local  
partnerships -- comprised of groups such as the Chamber of Commerce, 
Parent-Teacher Association, local child welfare agencies and 
churches -- to find new ways of tackling needs for child care, 
school readiness, parenting education and special services for 
children with disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty percent of the new money would be reserved to bolster  
existing programs, such as Head Start, with the balance intended to 
pay for new services. 
</P>
<P>
	The program, Bradley said, ``operates under the simple  
understanding that we all have a shared responsibility for our 
children. Government, acting as a catalyst, can provide the kind of 
supporting infrastructure that families need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley would offer $2 billion over five years in competitive  
grants to community colleges that do a better job of matching high 
school graduates' needs with demands in the local job market, 
providing flexible class schedules and on-site child care for 
working parents and improving students' technological skills. 
</P>
<P>
	The programs' remaining costs involve the proposal for a senior  
volunteer corps. 
</P>
<P>
	``My proposal focuses on four areas that are of vital concern to  
all families and is premised on a simple idea: That if you have 
health care coverage, good child care, educational opportunity and 
supportive work environments, you can be a better parent,'' Bradley 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
