<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NIH Head Leading NYC Cancer Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The director of the National Institutes of  
Health is resigning to become president of the Memorial 
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Harold Varmus said Thursday he will leave office Dec. 31 and  
assume his new job Jan. 1. He has directed the NIH since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It clearly seems to me that people who run large institutions  
should be moving on after a period of time,'' Varmus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Varmus, 59, has been involved in cancer research for 30 years,  
and shared the 1989 Nobel prize in medicine for discovering a 
family of genes that helped scientists understand how cancer 
develops. 
</P>
<P>
	As director of NIH he has been one of the most powerful men in  
science. The position also put him at the center of controversial 
matters ranging from the battle against AIDS to the use of embryos 
in research and freedom of information in scientific matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said Varmus  
``brought new energy, vision and excitement to the world's greatest 
scientific institution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Varmus said he urged President Clinton to appoint a new NIH  
director before Clinton's term is up, and to consider active 
scientists for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	At Sloan-Kettering, Varmus will succeed Dr. Paul Marks, a former  
teacher of his at Columbia University, where Varmus received his 
medical degree in 1966. Marks had announced his intention to step 
down late last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
