<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiators Agree on Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate negotiators completed work on  
a $268 billion defense spending bill that slows the Air Force's 
F-22 ``stealth'' fighter program but will keep the radar-evading 
jets flying. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to be business as usual'' at the Pentagon, Rep.  
Jerry Lewis, D-Calif., chairman of the Appropriations defense 
subcommittee, told reporters Thursday. ``If we're going to deal 
with fewer and fewer dollars, we have to deal with them wisely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The appropriations bill now goes back to the House and Senate  
for final approval. 
</P>
<P>
	It provides $4.5 billion more for the fiscal year that began  
Oct. 1 than President Clinton requested, and $17.3 billion over 
last year's levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The increases include money to help pay for a 4.8 percent  
across-the-board military pay raise also included in a defense 
authorization bill signed earlier this week by Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The final version of the bill retains a Senate-passed measure  
that would give the president permanent authority to waive all 
sanctions on India and Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic and military sanctions were imposed automatically after  
both nations conducted back-to-back nuclear tests in 1998. Congress 
temporarily waived a ban on the sale of agricultural goods. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense bill gives the president the authority to waive both  
economic and military sanctions. Sen. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., a 
sponsor of the waiver provision, called the action ``good news for 
farmers (and) for the aircraft industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a citizens group that opposes the F-22 criticized the  
decision to keep the fighter program alive. ``This fig leaf 
solution serves nothing. It just extends the F-22 debate into next 
year,'' the Council for a Livable World said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate negotiators finished their work at a  
closed-door session late Wednesday and released details Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, the final version included a compromise reached by  
negotiators last week on the F-22, the most expensive jet fighter 
ever built. 
</P>
<P>
	The House had voted to suspended the line entirely, while the  
Senate bill would have given the Air Force the full $1.8 billion 
requested by the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise recommends a year's delay in production and would  
give the Air Force $1 billion for the program instead of the $1.8 
billion, some of which could be used to buy test planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill sets aside $300 million to reimburse Lockheed Martin  
Corp., the prime contractor, in case the planes fail the testing 
and the program is terminated. Otherwise, the money could be spent 
to help build the planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force hopes to buy up to 339 of the jets. But Rep. John  
Murtha of Pennsylvania, the senior Democrat on the defense 
subcommittee, said Thursday it seemed unlikely the Air Force would 
be able to buy more than about 140 of the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're never going to build the numbers that are there,'' he  
said. ``They're going to become more expensive. The money just 
isn't there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would make a $375 million installment on a $1.5  
billion LHD-8 mini aircraft carrier to be built at a shipyard in 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's hometown of Pascagoula, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy did not want funds to start building the ship until  
fiscal 2005, but Lott persuaded the Senate to put $500 million in 
its version of the spending bill. The original House bill had 
provided nothing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
