<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The town of Gilbert just outside Phoenix is free  
to celebrate ``Bible Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union had sued  
Gilbert and Mayor Cynthia Dunham on the grounds that her 
proclamation of the week was unconstitutional. But U.S. District 
Judge Roslyn O. Silver ruled the suit invalid because the 
plaintiffs suffered no legal injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said whether Bible Week violates the doctrine of  
separation of church and state should be determined by ``political 
branches of government subject to majority rule,'' or at least 
should await a plaintiff who could prove legal standing to sue. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case never belonged in court,'' said Walter M. Weber, an  
attorney with the American Center for Law and Justice who helped 
represent Dunham. ``The mayor is once more free to proclaim Bible 
Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Bible Association in New York created Bible Week in  
1941 to bring communities together. Proponents say the week is 
meant to encourage people to read the Bible and to recognize its 
historical and cultural roots in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, the association asks one mayor and one governor to  
send letters urging other states and cities to proclaim Bible Week. 
Last year, Gov. Jane Hull and Dunham responded, proclaiming Nov. 
22-29 as Bible Week in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The celebration was put on hold after Silver issued a temporary  
restraining order. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Donkeys headed for Honduras are blessed    	
</P>
<P>
	PERRYVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Ten Mammoth Jack donkeys bound for  
Honduras to help in the Central American country's year-old 
hurricane recovery were blessed before their departure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Richard Davis blessed the animals in a ceremony at a  
ranch south of Perryville. The donkeys will be sent to Honduras in 
late October to stand at stud with horses to create work mules. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mammoth Jacks, the largest variety of donkeys, were  
collected by Heifer Project International, a Little Rock-based 
charity that sends food- or income-producing animals to developing 
countries. Religious services often are conducted before the 
animals are shipped. 
</P>
<P>
	``St. Francis called the animals, wild and tame, his brothers  
and sisters,'' said Davis, from St. Francis Roman Catholic Church. 
A donkey that had been across the field when Davis began the 
blessing walked over to the priest during the rite. 
</P>
<P>
	The blessing came on the eve of the day the church honors St.  
Francis, a 13th century monk who renounced his parents' fortune and 
became the patron saint of animals and nature. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Church 'haunts' youth with sins    	
</P>
<P>
	ARVADA, Colo. (AP) -- A gay wedding that ends in tragedy is this  
year's featured Halloween scenario at Hell House. 
</P>
<P>
	For five years, Abundant Life Christian Center has presented a  
kind of haunted house mixed with morality play to show young people 
how they will be punished for sinning. 
</P>
<P>
	The church is affiliated with Assemblies of God, a pentacostal  
denomination. It says worshippers number about 500 each Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the same-sex marriage, this year's Hell House,  
which runs 12 nights beginning Oct. 15, also features such sins as 
a teen-ager losing her virginity to a young man with HIV, a girl 
who takes drugs at a ``rave'' party, and an intoxicated driver who 
causes a fatality, associate pastor Keenan Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning from last year, he said, are an abortion scene and  
depictions of heaven and hell. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics, including liberal and moderate religious leaders, say  
Hell House concentrates too much on sin, hell and punishment, and 
not enough on God's love. 
</P>
<P>
	But Roberts said people ``need the hell scared out of them.''  
</P>
<P>
	In the gay wedding scenario, one of the partners will later die  
of AIDS as punishment, Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	But since the couple kisses, one of the men will be played by a  
woman, he said. ``I'm just not going to have two guys kissing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Anglican leader says diversity has limits    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The world leader of the Anglican Communion rejects  
the common view that diversity is ``the defining characteristic of 
Anglicanism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a major address, Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey said,  
``We do not live by the principle, 'Anything goes.' I, and I guess 
most of us, do not accept that there are no cardinal doctrines, 
beliefs or limits to orthodoxy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carey's comments, at the worldwide Anglican Consultative Council  
at Dundee, Scotland, were reported by the Anglican Communion News 
Service. The council includes clergy and lay delegates from each 
independent national branch of Anglicanism, including America's 
Episcopal Church. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting concluded without taking a position on the divisive  
homosexual issue, but the council did pass statements on 
disarmament, nuclear weapons, unrest in East Timor, Mideast peace, 
the Cuba trade embargo and international debt. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Not just homemakers    	
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The monthly gathering of Mormon women,  
long referred to as a ``homemaking meeting,'' is getting a name 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Jan. 1, Mormon women will follow a program of ``Home,  
Family and Personal Enrichment.'' Earlier in the century, they met 
monthly on a weekend afternoon, usually for quilting or other 
home-based activities. And in recent decades, the meetings have 
shifted to evenings as more women began working outside the home. 
</P>
<P>
	The change was announced during the annual meeting of the  
General Relief Society, the main women's group of The Church of 
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new program, women will get a 15-minute lesson on a  
spiritual topic, then spend 60 to 90 minutes learning practical 
skills associated with the topic, according to Virginia Jensen, 
first counselor to the presidency of the Relief Society. That could 
include home repairs, gardening, service, or the traditional 
quilting. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the group introduced a declaration for Relief  
Society members, which emphasizes support for the traditional 
family and an absolute authority of the church's all-male 
priesthood. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *A Lutheran guide to homosexuality    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America is  
offering members a short course on the morality of same-sex 
behavior. The textbook lays out conservative and liberal options 
but draws no conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	Current church policy welcomes homosexuals but forbids same-sex  
relationships for clergy and blessing ceremonies for gay and 
lesbian couples. Liberals among the 5.2 million members want to 
change that. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Paul Jersild, who teaches at the Evangelical Lutherans'  
seminary in Columbia, S.C., represents the liberal view in the 
text, ``Talking Together as Christians About Homosexuality.'' The 
conservative spokesman, the Rev. Gilbert Meilaender of Valparaiso 
(Ind.) University, is from the Lutheran Church -- Missouri Synod. 
</P>
<P>
	While Meilaender says the entire Christian tradition, and  
several Bible passages, prohibit same-sex relationships, Jersild 
argues that Christians' modern experiences compel a ``re-evaluation 
of what the Bible says.'' 
</P>
