<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Donald Eyes the White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Donald Trump is very, very rich. Which doesn't  
mean that his talk can't be cheap. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, The Donald announced that he'd formed an  
exploratory committee to determine his viability as a presidential 
candidate for the Reform Party. But in the past, the billionaire 
developer's done a lot of talking about a lot of things -- remember 
the United States Football League? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Trump has amassed a $1.6 billion fortune through savvy  
projects like the Grand Hyatt Hotel, Trump Tower and his Atlantic 
City casinos. But Trump occasionally has -- how to say this? -- made 
announcements that didn't amount to much. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many news-making projects exist only in his imagination,''  
read the headline on a November 1996 Trump article in the New York 
Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Take 1990, when Trump floated word that he might build a  
125-story tower -- the world's largest -- on the Los Angeles site of 
the old Ambassador Hotel. Simultaneously, city officials were 
knocking down Trump's plans for a similar edifice in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics howled that Trump was playing one city against the  
other. Trump was unmoved -- the massive building ``will only go to 
one,'' he promised. 
</P>
<P>
	It went to neither.  
</P>
<P>
	After a protracted legal battle, Trump sold his stake in the Los  
Angeles property without building anything. His Manhattan plans for 
a 150-story tower, announced in 1985, were wildly downscaled; 
construction on that West Side project continues today. Now absent 
the Television City office tower, the first of the apartment 
buildings in the complex are being occupied. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the Trump Organization announced plans for a possible  
Trump Tower Moscow. They're still waiting, comrade. Trump made 
similar comments about Trump Towers in Tokyo and Sao Paolo; none 
materialized. 
</P>
<P>
	Ditto an announced 1994 foray into Las Vegas. Five years later,  
Trump's casino holdings remain strictly in Atlantic City, N.J. 
Ditto a 1992 proposal for a high-tech theme park in the New Jersey 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics point to a common theme: publicity, spelled T-R-U-M-P.  
Trump creates headlines to feed a massive ego, they carp. And Trump 
certainly has enjoyed the attention. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1991, for example, Trump stood outside a Manhattan  
courthouse waving a $10 million check and announcing that his 
divorce from wife Ivana was final. He made all the papers, but the 
divorce wasn't finalized until more than two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1989, Trump made an unsolicited takeover offer of $7  
billion for AMR Corp., the parent of American Airlines. Eleven days 
after the bid created headlines, Trump withdrew it -- before it was 
ever formally presented to stockholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Publicity is always good, but candidate Trump would bring other  
things to the table. 
</P>
<P>
	He has experience with debt; hell, he wrote ``Trump: The Art of  
the Comeback,'' a whole book about his return from a $975 million 
financial black hole. 
</P>
<P>
	He's quite the spin doctor; when a jury awarded the USFL just $1  
in its $1.3 billion lawsuit against the NFL, New Jersey Generals 
owner Trump called it ``a great moral victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump also had predicted a USFL-NFL super-duper bowl by 1990,  
perhaps played in the modestly named Trump Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, well.  
</P>
<P>
	While politicians and unfulfilled promises are not strange  
bedfellows, Trump has at least one more political drawback: his 
germ-phobia keeps him from shaking hands, much less kissing babies. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the curses of American society is the simple act of  
shaking hands,'' the potential politico wrote in his ``Comeback'' 
book. ``I happen to be a clean-hands freak.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UPS Ending Some Gun Deliveries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service said today it will stop  
delivering handguns through its regular service, saying it was 
taking the step to help prevent thefts of weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Monday, Atlanta-based UPS -- which handles the vast  
majority of firearms shipments -- will ship handguns only through 
its Next Day Air service, which costs three to four times as much 
as ground service. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has become more than ever a tremendous issue of concern  
to our society,'' UPS spokesman Norman Black said. ``Society is 
concerned about these weapons falling into the wrong hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UPS' Next Day Air service is a separate, more controlled system  
where packages are handled by fewer people and stay in the system 
for only one night, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Chambers, executive director of the Sporting Arms and  
Ammunition Manufacturers' Institute, said overnight delivery costs 
about $25 more per gun, or about four times as much as ground 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we're trying to come to grips with. We're looking  
for alternative methods,'' Chambers told The Morning Call in 
Allentown, Pa., which reported the new UPS policy in a story 
published today. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will continue to ship long guns, rifles and shotguns  
by ground. Those guns are not as attractive to thieves as handguns, 
said another UPS spokesman, Robert Godlewski. 
</P>
<P>
	Godlewski acknowledged that shipping by air will be more  
expensive for gun manufacturers and dealers. But he said, ``We're 
going to err on the side of safety. If that costs more money, then 
that's the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each business day, Atlanta-based UPS delivers 12 million  
packages via its trademark brown trucks and brown-uniformed 
employees. UPS handles up to 75 percent of guns sent from 
manufacturers to distributors and nearly all firearms shipped from 
distributors to dealers, Chambers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Jannuzzo, vice president of Glock Inc., said the gun  
manufacturer will continue to ship with UPS, but the increase in 
cost will be passed on to dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too substantial to absorb,'' said Jannuzzo, who works at  
Glock's U.S. headquarters in Smyrna, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, federal investigators said 130 Glock guns being shipped  
via UPS were stolen from a series of shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it will cut out the theft problems, it will be a good  
thing,'' Jannuzzo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Black couldn't say how many guns have been stolen from the UPS  
ground system in the past. He knew of no cases where a gun stolen 
from UPS had been used in a crime and a lawsuit resulted. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, ``our attitude is that even one such instance is one too  
many, and we just had to find some way to improve the security 
around these shipments,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
