<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: N.Y. Senate Race Tightens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Rudolph Giuliani has been hurt by his battle  
with the Brooklyn Museum of Art, narrowing the gap between him and 
potential Senate rival Hillary Rodham Clinton, according to a poll 
released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the New York City mayor's standing improved among the  
state's largest voting group, white Catholics, in the wake of the 
museum showdown, according to the poll. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll from Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion  
found the mayor favored by 46 percent of the state's voters while 
42 percent backed Mrs. Clinton, a statistical dead heat based on 
the poll's margin of error of 4 percentage points. Other polls have 
also shown them about even. 
</P>
<P>
	A Marist poll last month had Giuliani, a Republican, leading the  
Democratic first lady, 49 percent to 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Mrs. Clinton's aides said she had filed a  
``statement of candidacy'' with the Federal Election Commission, 
another signal she intends to run for the seat being vacated by 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for her political committee, said  
the filing was not a formal declaration of candidacy, but simply a 
technical change allowing her to raise $2,000 from individual 
donors instead of the maximum $1,000 she has been raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has been operating under an FEC statement of candidacy  
since April, Wolfson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new poll found the mayor's unfavorable rating among New York  
voters had climbed to 39 percent, the same level as the first 
lady's. In last month's poll, the mayor's unfavorable rating was at 
30 percent while Mrs. Clinton's was at 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty percent of those polled this time around said their  
opinion of Giuliani has gotten worse since the flap over the 
Brooklyn museum's exhibit ``Sensation'' began. Twenty-one percent 
said their opinion of the mayor had improved because of the way he 
handled the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The show includes a black Virgin Mary surrounded by naked body  
parts and dried elephant dung. The mayor has said he wants to cut 
off city funding for the museum because of the exhibit, which he 
called ``sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has said that while she disapproves of the exhibit,  
she would not strip the museum's funding. 
</P>
<P>
	White Catholics traditionally make up 40 percent to 45 percent  
of the vote in statewide elections, and Giuliani -- himself a white 
Catholic -- saw his standing among that group improve. 
</P>
<P>
	In last month's poll, white Catholics favored Giuliani over Mrs.  
Clinton, 57 percent to 34 percent. In the latest poll, Giuliani 
topped Mrs. Clinton, 60 percent to 29 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton continued to have the edge among women, 46 percent  
to 41 percent, while Giuliani was tops among men, 52 percent to 37 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 702 registered voters was conducted Sunday  
and Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
