<HEADLINE> Devils' Goalie Ejected for Slashing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Martin Brodeur was kicked out of  
the New Jersey Devils' game with the Pittsburgh Penguins for 
slashing Matthew Barnaby early in the first period on Thursday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brodeur received a match penalty with attempt to injure from  
referee Paul Stewart after whacking the back of Barnaby's legs with 
his stick at 14:32. The penalty called for an automatic review by 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident in New Jersey's home opener happened just seconds  
after the Penguins' pesky player bumped Brodeur after the 
goaltender handled a loose puck in the corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Brodeur skated back into his crease and hit Barnaby, a move  
which might have reflected the goaltender's frustration after 
giving up three goals to Aleksey Morozov in the opening 12:39. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who was the trail official on the play, had a good view  
of the incident, but his major call seemed to surprise Brodeur. He 
was also called for a four-minute minor for roughing on Saturday 
night in New Jersey's season opener against Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnaby had to be helped off the ice, but he returned for the  
second period. 
</P>
<P>
	The ejection was the first of Brodeur's seven NHL seasons.  
Veteran Chris Terreri took over and stopped all seven Penguins 
shots on their five-minute powerplay. 
</P>
<P>
	Remarkably, Brodeur lasted longer than Penguins starter Tom  
Barrasso. He left after 8:22 and was replaced by Peter Skudra. No 
explanation was made, although Barrasso left shortly after becoming 
entangled with Randy McKay while trying to make a kick save on a 
shot by Devils defenseman Scott Niedermayer. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrasso had a knee injury coming into the game but it wasn't  
clear whether he had aggravated it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
