<HEADLINE> Accused N.J. Swindler Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Martin A. Armstrong Jr., the New Jersey  
financial adviser who prosecutors say swindled Japanese investors 
out of $950 million, pleaded innocent Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, 49, of Maple Shade, N.J., entered the plea during a  
routine appearance before Magistrate Judge Douglas F. Eaton in U.S. 
District Court in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who is free on $5 million bail, appeared in court in  
a business suit. When asked how he pleaded, he said, ``Innocent 
your honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton then picked from a wooden wheel the name of Judge Lawrence  
M. McKenna, who will preside over the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside court, Armstrong said: ``This case is far more  
complicated than anyone suspects. I'm innocent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to comment further as did his attorney, Marc Durant.  
</P>
<P>
	Durant has said prosecutors have grossly exaggerated the amount  
of money they allege his client lost for investors as the founder 
and chairman of Princeton Economics International Ltd. of a 
Princeton, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges Armstrong sold about $3 billion in  
securities to foreign investors through Princeton Global Management 
Ltd., an investment fund he controlled. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the promissory notes were described to  
investors as conservative investments before Armstrong squandered 
the funds on risky trading ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong has been charged with conspiracy to commit securities  
fraud, securities fraud and wire fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors allege Armstrong has significant assets in offshore  
bank accounts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
