<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sunscreen Maker Buys Rival's Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, N.J. (AP) -- Coppertone sunscreen maker Schering-Plough  
Corp. said Thursday it has bought the rights to sell the Bain de 
Soleil line of sun care products from rival drug maker Pfizer Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough, based here, and Pfizer, based in New York, did  
not disclose terms of the cash deal they concluded Wednesday. The 
Federal Trade Commission previously approved the purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough now has exclusive rights to sell Bain de Soleil  
products in the United States, Puerto Rico and a few other small 
markets. The company also acquired trademarks for the Bain de 
Soleil line, including Orange Gel+E, and the new Streakguard line 
of sunless tanning creams. 
</P>
<P>
	Coppertone products, the leading sun care brand in North  
America, are sold by the Schering-Plough HealthCare Products 
business, based in Liberty Corner. 
</P>
<P>
	``This allows us to reach a broader spectrum of the sun care  
market,'' said Schering-Plough spokesman Bob Consalvo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coppertone is sort of positioned as the traditional American  
sun care brand'' and has a strong line of sunblock products, 
Consalvo said. ``Bain de Soleil is positioned as a premium, upscale 
brand'' and is strong in sunless tanning products. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough, the maker of Claritin allergy medications and  
Dr. Scholl's foot care products, reported 1998 sales of $181 
million for its Coppertone line, which is sold in few markets 
outside North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Consalvo said Schering-Plough has an option to buy rights to  
sell Bain de Soleil products in Canada and probably will exercise 
that later. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are other companies that sell Bain de Soleil in other  
parts of the world,'' he added. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
