<DOCNO> APW19991007.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuits Over Star-Bulletin Closing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- The state and a group of residents are suing in  
an attempt to stop the closing of the Honolulu Star-Bulletin. They 
say shutting the newspaper down while it is still profitable 
deprives readers and advertisers of competition in violation of 
antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The separate lawsuits were filed Wednesday in U.S. District  
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett Co. Inc., which owns the competing morning Honolulu  
Advertiser, will pay Liberty Newspapers Ltd. Partnership more than 
$30 million to close the still-profitable Star-Bulletin, according 
to the lawsuit filed by Save Our Star-Bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
	The scheduled Oct. 30 closing of the 117-year-old afternoon  
paper would leave the Advertiser as Hawaii's only statewide daily 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our feeling is that as long as Liberty was making money and  
was profitable, there is no way we can justify the buying out of 
Liberty by Gannett,'' Gov. Ben Cayetano said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two newspapers have operated under a Joint Operating  
Agreement since 1962. It allows them to share production and 
distribution costs but maintain separate news gathering and 
editorial departments. The agreement was set to expire in 2012. 
</P>
<P>
	The private group's lawsuit accuses Gannett and Liberty  
Newspapers of using the Newspaper Preservation Act to create a 
one-newspaper monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most blatant example to date of a shutdown-for-pay  
agreement in the newspaper industry,'' said Donald Baker, one of 
two former federal attorneys representing SOS-Bulletin. ``The 
surviving paper ends up with a monopoly, the shutdown paper's owner 
gets a pile of money and the community suffers a big loss of 
independent news and editorial voices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael J. Fisch, president and publisher of The Honolulu  
Advertiser, wouldn't comment because he hasn't seen the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rupert Phillips, Liberty's chief executive officer, has refused  
to disclose the amount of Gannett's payment. 
</P>
<P>
	He announced last month he was closing the newspaper because it  
was no longer providing a sufficient return on his investment. 
Phillips also said investors were collecting a 12 percent return on 
the paper, whereas mainland papers were returning up to 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Those involved in Save Our Star-Bulletin include a University of  
Hawaii regent, two former lieutenant governors, a former Honolulu 
city council member, a former Star-Bulletin reporter and a real 
estate agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs are paying for the lawsuit with their own money  
with help from The Newspaper Guild-Communications Workers of 
America, said Richard Port, former head of the state Democratic 
Party and one of the seven plaintiffs. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
