<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Urges Patty Hearst Pardon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Former President Carter is urging President  
Clinton to pardon Patty Hearst, the newspaper heiress kidnapped by 
radicals in 1974 and convicted of joining them in a San Francisco 
bank heist. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19-year-old had claimed she was brainwashed by her  
Symbionese Liberation Army captors and forced to participate in the 
armed robbery. Carter commuted her 7-year sentence after she had 
served 21 months. 
</P>
<P>
	After her release from prison, Ms. Hearst married her bodyguard,  
Bernard Shaw, had two daughters, appeared in movies, wrote novels 
and has done charitable work. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter spoke with the Bush administration about a pardon and has  
spoken with Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Attorney General 
Janet Reno as well, Carter spokeswoman Carrie Harmon said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He ``has been her refuge in a sea of misunderstanding,'' Ms.  
Hearst Shaw's attorney, George Martinez, said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Wednesday he knew  
of no contact between Carter and Clinton about a pardon. 
</P>
<P>
	A former attorney who prosecuted Hearst, David Bancroft, has  
written a letter to the Justice Department opposing it. ``Simply 
staying out of trouble doesn't get you very much,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter's call for a pardon also caught the attention of  
attorneys for former SLA fugitive Kathleen Ann Soliah. 
</P>
<P>
	During 23 years on the run, Ms. Soliah married, took the name  
Sara Jane Olson, raised a family and became a community activist in 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	She was arrested in June and is scheduled to go on trial Jan. 10  
on allegations she conspired in a failed 1975 attempt to blow up 
two police cars, allegedly to avenge two SLA deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like Patricia Hearst, Sara Jane Olson has lived the life of a  
model citizen for over two decades,'' lawyers Susan Jordan and 
Stuart Hanlon said in a prepared statement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both women ``were caught up in the social turmoil of the late  
60s and early 70s,'' the lawyers said. Ms. Olson ``deserves the 
same consideration as Patty Hearst.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
