<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $4B Phen-Fen Drug Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American Home Products has agreed to pay more  
than $4 billion to settle thousands of lawsuits filed by patients 
claiming health problems due to the company's once popular phen-fen 
diet drug, an attorney close to the talks said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Becnel, a Louisiana plaintiffs' attorney, said the  
settlement will include money to pay patients who say they were 
injured by the drugs and for future medical monitoring for those 
who are still healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home was expected to announce the deal early this  
afternoon, said Becnel and a spokeswoman for another law firm 
representing plaintiffs, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of American Home rose $2.81, or 6 percent, to $47.94 on  
talk that a settlement was about to be annouced. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,100 suits, involving 8,000 people who took the diet  
drugs, have been filed against American Home, making it one of the 
largest product liability cases ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Becnel said the settlement totals approximately what American  
Home had offered several weeks ago. About $2.8 billion would go to 
to settle claims by people who say they developed heart valve 
injuries from taking fen-phen. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition the company offered to set up a $1.2 billion fund to  
provide medical monitoring of people who took the drug combination, 
but have no signs of injury, say lawyers familiar with the talks 
who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional $410,000 would be paid to cover plaintiffs'  
attorneys legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	About six million people took the drug combination.  
</P>
<P>
	Any settlement would need a federal judge's approval.  
</P>
<P>
	American Home made fenfluramine, the ``fen'' in the fen-phen  
combination and gave the drug a brand name of Pondimin. It also 
made Pondimin's chemical cousin Redux and marketed both until 
September 1997. That was when the U.S. Food and Drug Administration 
pushed for their withdrawal after a Mayo Clinic study linked the 
drugs to potentially fatal heart valve damage. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
