<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Courts-Martial Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed an executive order  
today increasing penalties for hate crimes and making other changes 
in the military justice code. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules ``make a number of desirable changes to modernize  
the rules of evidence that apply to court-martial proceedings and 
to take into account recent court decisions,'' Clinton said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The order allows a sentencing authority to hear evidence that a  
violent crime was based on hate, motivated by matters such as the 
victim's race, color or sexual orientation. 
</P>
<P>
	``As in the case of laws that apply in civilian courts, this  
rule sends a strong message that violence based on hatred will not 
be tolerated,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the order permits child abuse victims to testify  
away from their accuser, typically on closed-circuit television. It 
makes conversations between patients and psychotherapists 
privileged, unless the safety of military personnel is compromised 
and in other compelling cases. And it adds reckless endangerment to 
the list of crimes in the military code. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
