<DOCNO> APW19991007.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 11:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers: Nazi Workers Offered $3.3B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The German government and industries offered  
$3.3 billion today to compensate for World War II use of forced 
labor by the Nazis. Lawyers for victims labeled the offer ``an 
enormous disappointment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the German delegation they have done more harm to the  
German government and German people than they can ever imagine,'' 
said Mel Weiss, an attorney for survivors in class-action suits in 
U.S. courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Otto Lambsdorff, chief German envoy to two days of compensation  
talks hosted by the State Department, called the $3.3 billion offer 
``a considerable amount given the budget constraints in Germany.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfgang Gibowski, a spokesman for German corporations in the  
talks, said in a statement that he felt the offer shows German 
industry ``standing up to its moral responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	German officials said the offer would include payment of about  
$5,500 to each slave laborer. It was unclear what would be paid to 
other categories of victims, including those classified as forced 
laborers. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks continued into the afternoon. Attorneys said the next  
round of negotiations would be sometime in mid-November in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss first told reporters of the offer in front of the State  
Department after hearing the proposal made to a meeting of 
international negotiators by Lambsdorff. 
</P>
<P>
	``The offer amounts to about $300 million or less in 1940  
terms,'' Weiss said, charging that German industry has grown vastly 
wealthy in the years since it paid nearly nothing for the labor of 
prisoners of the Nazi regime during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is disgusting,'' Weiss said, adding that one-third of the  
money is supposed to come from the German government. He said that 
means industry came up with about $2.1 billion of the total after 
building up enormous wealth ``on the backs of these victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the proposed amount would cover payments to survivors of  
Nazi slave-labor camps as well as some compensation relating to 
unpaid World War II insurance claims, bank accounts and some other 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them that we are not going to walk away from the table  
... despite the fact that there is such enormous disappointment,'' 
Weiss said. Earlier this week, Weiss declined to say how much 
survivors demanded, but he said it far exceeds the $20 billion that 
had been recently reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Lambsdorff and other German negotiators were still in the  
meeting and not immediately available for comment. He had said in 
an AP interview Wednesday that he thought the offer would be 
``justified and dignified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offer was the first formal money proposal put on the table  
after months of negotiations on how to compensate an estimated 1 
million to 2.5 million people forced into labor for World War II 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only say that what I'm going to present ... is the  
result of very tough efforts in the German Republic to put this 
huge amount of money together,'' Lambsdorff said in an interview 
Wednesday with The Associated Press. ``And I would not have come 
here if I would not feel in a position to defend it as a justified, 
dignified offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the first day of a two-day session at the State Department,  
negotiators Wednesday made progress on such issues as how U.S. 
courts will handle any future lawsuits by forced laborers, 
Lambsdorff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of survivors, German companies that used forced  
labor and several governments have been meeting for months to 
negotiate a plan under which the German government and industry 
would set up two foundations to handle the compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks originally involved 16 German companies sued in U.S.  
courts, but about two dozen more are reported to be planning to 
contribute funds as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has said negotiations will get money to  
more people, and faster, than the lawsuits would. Part of the 
agreement would be some kind of U.S. government statement saying 
future claims should go through the foundations, discouraging the 
filing of further suits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been asked whether I have the authority to compromise.  
I have not,'' Lambsdorff said Wednesday. ``If we can make an offer, 
then the ball is in the court of the other side and they will, and 
have to, react.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he ``would be happy'' if agreement on all issues could  
be reached by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department says an estimated 12 million workers were  
forced to work in German industry and agriculture during World War 
II. Some produced materials for the war, and some took over jobs 
from German men, freeing them to fight.	   The largest number of surviving victims are Eastern European 
Christians from countries overrun early by Hitler's forces. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the United States and Germany, the other  
countries involved in the negotiations are Israel, Poland, Belarus, 
Ukraine, Russia and the Czech Republic, officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 10:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Rejects Modest HMO Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House members today rejected the most modest  
of four competing patient-protection bills as they confronted the 
politically charged issue of HMOs and whether injured Americans 
should be allowed to sue them. 
</P>
<P>
	Managed care has dominated the health debate on Capitol Hill all  
year, as Congress responds to voters' frustration over cost cutting 
and fears they may be denied needed care. 
</P>
<P>
	Casting their first votes on the politically hot topic, the  
House defeated, 284-145, a bill sponsored by Rep. John Boehner, 
R-Ohio, which would have given patients no new rights to file 
lawsuits. Federal law now effectively bans such suits for millions 
of Americans, even if they are injured or die because of an HMO's 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative Republicans and their allies in the business and  
insurance industries preferred this bill, but Democrats and many 
Republicans felt it didn't go far enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does not hold insurance companies accountable when they  
make medical decisions that harm people,'' said Rep. Sherrod Brown, 
D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, hoping to keep Democrats united, President Clinton  
today sent a letter to Capitol Hill restating his strong support 
for a broad bill that would give patients a host of new rights, 
including broad new rights to sue. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic leaders fear that concerns over how to pay for it may  
cost them votes, but Clinton sought to clarify that he still 
strongly supports the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I endorse this legislation without reservation,'' Clinton said  
in a letter to Minority leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. ``I cannot 
support a bill that is a patients' bill of rights in name only.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the House approved, largely along party lines, a  
GOP-written package of tax breaks and other provisions meant to 
help people without insurance obtain coverage. Democrats balked, 
saying the bill would cost the Treasury $48 billion over 10 years 
but help only a fraction of the uninsured. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was a prelude to the main event today, as the House  
took up four competing HMO bills. Each gives patients new power to 
demand care and take disputes to outside arbitrators, but there 
were major differences over details, notably whether patients 
should be given new rights to sue -- and, if so, whether to limit 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and some Republicans argued that the threat of a  
lawsuit is needed to force insurance companies to provide promised 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tell welfare mothers, we tell deadbeat dads ... you have to  
be responsible for yourself,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., 
the leading Republican backer of the right to sue. Health 
insurance, he said, is ``the only industry in America where we say 
you are absolutely protected from being responsible for your 
actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For two years, Democrats have put the GOP on the defensive over  
the politically popular HMO issue. House Republican leaders, 
struggling with a slim majority and a fractured caucus, did not 
endorse any bill until debate opened on the issue this week. 
</P>
<P>
	But they were working hard Wednesday to rally opposition to a  
sweeping bill backed by Norwood and virtually all the Democrats, 
including Clinton. That bill gives patients new power to see 
specialists, get emergency room care and take denials of care to an 
outside panel of experts. 
</P>
<P>
	Most controversially, it allows patients to sue HMOs in federal  
or state court and to collect whatever damages a jury might award. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to stop this bill, GOP leaders were trying to build  
support for an alternative by Reps. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and John 
Shadegg, R-Ariz. It would allow lawsuits only in federal courts and 
limit damages for pain and suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	The House also planned to vote on a fourth choice, backed by  
Reps. Amo Houghton Jr., R-N.Y., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C. It was 
quite similar to the Coburn-Shadegg bill, but offered in hopes of 
attracting more Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders saw the Coburn-Shadegg bill as their best hope of  
stopping the more sweeping Democratic measure, and they were 
appealing to interest groups to go easy on Republicans who vote 
``yes'' on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would rather we not vocally oppose it. After all, we  
share the same objective,'' said Neil Trautwein, a lobbyist for the 
National Association of Manufacturers, which opposes all new 
federal health mandates. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into this week's debate, Democrats appeared to have the  
votes they needed to pass their HMO bill. But they said Wednesday 
that they may lose the votes of some conservative Democrats because 
there was no way to pay for the HMO bill, estimated to cost the 
federal government some $7 billion in lost tax revenue over 10 
years. The bill, if it became law, likely would mean higher 
insurance premiums, which means businesses would be able to take 
higher tax deductions on their insurance costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP strategy has been to focus attention on the uninsured,  
as Republicans argue that new rights will drive up the cost of 
insurance and force employers to drop coverage. Hammering the point 
Wednesday, Republicans pushed through a bill, 227-205, aimed at 
reducing the ranks of the uninsured, which now stand at 44 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 14:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Falls on Output Worries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Concern that OPEC member nations were not holding to their  
production quotas sent crude oil futures prices plummeting Thursday 
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cattle and hog futures were higher, grain  
futures fell, and soybean futures prices were steady to 
fractionally higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Several analyst surveys concluded OPEC member nations were not  
complying with quotas set in March, indicating higher oil prices 
were encouraging some nations to increase production. 
</P>
<P>
	Various surveys estimated that September oil output ranged from  
26.17 million barrels a day to 26.41 million barrels a day, 
according to analyst Tim Evans of Pegasus Econometric Group. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC has a daily production target, excluding Iraq, of 22.97  
million barrels a day, Evans said. OPEC nations produced 23.5 
million barrels a day, with Iraq adding 2.7 million barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an emotional disappointment to the market,'' Evans said.  
``I don't think it shifts things to the point where (market) 
fundamentals are bearish. They are just less bullish than they were 
a week ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There also was concern that OPEC might back away from its  
commitment to current production levels, set to end in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The oil ministers for Mexico, Venezuela and Saudi Arabia are  
scheduled to meet next month. Mexican oil Minister Luis Tellez on 
Thursday indicated he would like to maintain current production 
levels into next year. 
</P>
<P>
	He is basically looking for negotiation on a new production  
agreement sooner, rather than later, Evans said. The market reads 
any potential change to be bearish rather than bullish. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline futures prices also were sharply lower, reflecting  
continued concern about a recent American Petroleum Institute 
report of an increase in gasoline stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Light sweet crude for November delivery was 82 cents lower at  
$22.45 a barrel; November heating oil was 1.97 cents lower at 57.46 
cents a gallon; November unleaded gasoline was 2.53 cents lower at 
62.76 a gallon; November natural gas was 4.1 cents higher at $2.641 
per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain futures prices fell and soybean futures prices were steady  
to fractionally higher in trading on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures were supported by higher than expected weekly  
export sales figures, released Thursday by the U.S. Agriculture 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean exports totaled 975,400, according to the USDA, beating  
the most optimistic analyst estimates by well over 100,000 metric 
tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Weighing on soybean futures was harvest weather in the Midwest,  
which continues to look good for producers. Positioning by traders 
ahead of Friday's USDA crop production report also affected the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures prices fell on expectation the USDA will raise the  
size of the 1999-2000 crop in its production report. Also 
pressuring corn futures was the rapid pace of the corn crop harvest 
and reports China's corn exports will increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were sharply lower on fears the government will  
report another increase in the size of wheat stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery was 5 1/2 cents lower at $2.58 3/4 a  
bushel; December corn was 1 1/2 cents lower at $2.03 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats were 2 cents lower at $1.09 3/4 a bushel; November 
soybeans were unchanged at $3.89 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and hog futures prices rose in trading on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle futures rallied due to higher cash prices and the  
likelihood strong demand will continue to the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog futures were higher on expectation of increased demand and  
on the possibility U.S. farm aid to Russia will result increased 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork belly futures were sharply higher due to rising cash  
prices. Increasing demand for bacon by fast-food restaurants also 
was a boost to prices. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle were .80 cent higher at 70 cents a pound;  
November feeder cattle were .65 cent higher at 83.02 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs were 1.05 cents higher at 45.75 cents a pound; 
February pork bellies were 3 cents higher at 64.22 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
