<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Outraged by Ventura Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying he was ``outraged'' by his governor's  
remarks, Sen. Paul Wellstone said Thursday that Minnesota Gov. 
Jesse Ventura should recognize that suicide is a form of mental 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in the November issue of Playboy, Ventura said  
he didn't read books by Ernest Hemingway because the writer killed 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen too many people fight for their lives. I have no  
respect for anyone who would kill himself,'' Ventura said. ``If 
you're a feeble, weak-minded person to begin with, I don't have 
time for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on the Senate floor, Wellstone, D-Minn., said Ventura  
``and all Americans need to understand that suicide is directly 
linked to mental illness. The form of mental illness we are talking 
about is severe depression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the governor of Minnesota to understand that this  
mental illness is not a moral failing,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Families that have lost members to suicide need support, said  
Wellstone, who has family members afflicted by mental illness. 
``They do not need ridicule,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wellstone made the remarks in offering an amendment, approved by  
the Senate, to increase federal block grants for mental health 
services by $48.8 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 06:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Expects 8.8 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Increasing investment and private  
consumption will help South Korea's economy grow 8.8 percent this 
year, the Bank of Korea said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's forecast is up sharply from its previous  
forecast of 6.8 percent growth. The new figure compares to South 
Korea's economic contraction of 5.8 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation is expected to post a surplus on its current account,  
the broadest measure of foreign trade, of $21 billion this year, 
the bank said. This is slightly up from a previous forecast of a 
$20 billion surplus, but sharply down from a $40.6 billion surplus 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account measures trade in merchandise, services,  
tourism and investment. It is calculated by determining the 
difference between South Korea's income from foreign sources 
against payments on foreign obligations. It excludes net capital 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, South Korea's trade surplus is expected to reach  
$25.8 billion this year, down from a $41.6 billion surplus last 
year, while the consumer price index, a measure of inflation, is 
expected to rise only 0.8 percent this year, sharply down from 7.5 
percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank also said the nation's economy would grow by 6.4  
percent next year, slightly up from its previous forecast of a 
growth between 5 and 6 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Health-Care Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, preparing for a series of showdown  
votes on patient protections, confronted the politically charged 
issue of HMOs and whether injured Americans should be allowed to 
sue them. 
</P>
<P>
	Managed care has dominated the health debate on Capitol Hill all  
year, as Congress responds to voter frustration over cost cutting 
and fears they may be denied needed care. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day I hear from my constituents who are enrolled in  
HMOs, crying out for help,'' Rep. Eliot Engel, D-N.Y., said in a 
typical speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening the debate over health care Wednesday, the House  
approved, largely along party lines, a GOP-crafted package of tax 
breaks and other provisions meant to help people without insurance 
obtain coverage. Democrats balked, saying the bill would cost the 
Treasury $48 billion over 10 years but help only a fraction of the 
uninsured. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was a prelude to the main event today, as the House  
takes up four competing HMO bills. Each gives patients new power to 
demand care and take disputes to outside arbitrators, but there 
were major differences over details, notably whether patients 
should be given new rights to sue -- and, if so, whether to limit 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and some Republicans argued that the threat of a  
lawsuit is needed to force insurance companies to provide promised 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tell welfare mothers, we tell deadbeat dads ... you have to  
be responsible for yourself,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., 
the leading Republican backer of the right to sue. Health 
insurance, he said, is ``the only industry in America where we say 
you are absolutely protected from being responsible for your 
actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For two years, Democrats have put the GOP on the defensive over  
the politically popular HMO issue. House Republican leaders, 
struggling with a slim majority and a fractured caucus, did not 
endorse any bill until debate opened on the issue this week. 
</P>
<P>
	But they were working hard Wednesday to rally opposition to a  
sweeping bill backed by Norwood and virtually all the Democrats, 
including President Clinton. That bill gives patients new power to 
see specialists, get emergency room care and take denials of care 
to an outside panel of experts. 
</P>
<P>
	Most controversially, it allows patients to sue HMOs in federal  
or state court and to collect whatever damages a jury might award. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to stop this bill, GOP leaders were trying to build  
support for an alternative crafted by Reps. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., 
and John Shadegg, R-Ariz. It would allow lawsuits only in federal 
courts and limit damages for pain and suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other alternatives were also being considered.  
</P>
<P>
	A bill sponsored by Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, was the most  
limited measure, providing no new rights to sue and limiting other 
protections as well. 
</P>
<P>
	And Reps. Amo Houghton Jr., R-N.Y., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.,  
had a measure quite similar to the Coburn-Shadegg bill, but crafted 
in hopes of attracting more Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders saw the Coburn-Shadegg bill as their best hope of  
stopping the more sweeping Democratic measure, and they were 
appealing to interest groups to go easy on Republicans who vote 
``yes'' on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would rather we not vocally oppose it. After all, we  
share the same objective,'' said Neil Trautwein, a lobbyist for the 
National Association of Manufacturers, which opposes all new 
federal health mandates. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into this week's debate, Democrats appeared to have the  
votes they needed to pass their HMO bill. But they said Wednesday 
that they may lose the votes of some conservative Democrats because 
there was no way to pay for the HMO bill, estimated to cost the 
federal government some $7 billion in lost tax revenue over 10 
years. The bill, if it became law, likely would mean higher 
insurance premiums, which means businesses would be able to take 
higher tax deductions on their insurance costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP strategy has been to focus attention on the uninsured,  
as Republicans argue that new rights will drive up the cost of 
insurance and force employers to drop coverage. Hammering the point 
Wednesday, Republicans pushed through a bill, 227-205, aimed at 
reducing the ranks of the uninsured, which now stand at 44 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill includes popular tax breaks for people buying health  
coverage on their own and for long-term care insurance. But it also 
includes a provision opposed by many Democrats that would allow 
more medical savings accounts, which let people opt out of the 
current health insurance market and buy high-deductible plans on 
their own. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation also would give small businesses the option to  
buy health insurance under federal rather than state regulation -- 
exempting them from state mandates that bigger self-insured 
companies already avoid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
