<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Macromedia To Acquire Andromedia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Macromedia Inc., a provider of tools for  
building Web sites, said Thursday it is acquiring Andromedia Inc., 
maker of electronic commerce software for the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made in New York at the Fall Internet World  
'99 convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Andromedia, based in San Francisco, makes software that analyzes  
data about Web site visitors. It also allows Web sites to be 
customized based on the data about the user. Terms of the deal were 
not announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase is part of Macromedia's strategy announced Thursday  
to integrate its Web authoring software with that of Andromedia's 
and several other companies. Macromedia said its ``ebusiness 
infrastructure'' strategy will include alliances with BroadVision 
Inc. and USWeb/CKS. 
</P>
<P>
	The new infrastructure delivers solutions for each step of the  
Web content lifecycle, Macromedia said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Macromedia, based in San Francisco, makes Dreamweaver, a Web  
site authoring software and the Shockwave player, a popular media 
playback device for Web content, including games, business 
presentations, and advertisements. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:30:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC OKs Ameritech-SBC Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fifteen years after the court-ordered breakup  
of the old Bell system, the pieces are coming back together. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger between SBC Communications and Ameritech Corp. to  
create the nation's largest local phone company -- a deal given 
clearance by federal regulators Wednesday -- leaves just four 
remaining regional Bells out of the seven created when American 
Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. was dismantled in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies like SBC and Ameritech assert that such consolidation  
is needed for them to compete and to provide packages of 
telecommunications services to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly going to increase competition,'' SBC's  
chairman, Edward Whitacre Jr., said of the $74 billion deal. The 
combined business, which will keep the SBC name, would control 57 
million, or one-third, of the nation's local phone lines spread 
across 13 states, primarily in the Southwest and Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre pledged that consumers would soon see the benefits of  
the union with packages of services and accelerated rollout of 
high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also is poised to seek federal permission to provide  
long-distance service to its local phone customers, after getting a 
signal Wednesday from Texas regulators that it had met a list of 
statutory requirements to do so, Whitacre said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the new SBC eventually wins FCC permission to provide  
long-distance service to its local customers, MCI WorldCom, Sprint 
and AT&AMP;T could face a formidable rival. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said the merger, which was approved  
with considerable conditions, could boost the likelihood that a new 
SBC would get into long-distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will speed the day when they can show their markets are  
open to competition in ways that allow them to compete in 
long-distance,'' Kennard said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger announced Tuesday between MCI WorldCom and Sprint is  
likely to make regulators more receptive to the new SBC's entering 
the long-distance market, said Rex Mitchell, a telecommunications 
analyst with Banc of America Securities in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC adopted 30 conditions to ensure the SBC-Ameritech deal  
would serve the public interest. The new SBC must enter 30 new 
markets within 30 months to compete with established local phone 
companies. The company is required to provide deep discounts on key 
pieces of their networks to rivals who want to lease them. 
</P>
<P>
	The business also must establish a separate subsidiary to  
provide advanced telecommunications services such as high-speed 
Internet access. At least 10 percent of its upgraded services would 
go toward low-income regions. 
</P>
<P>
	The conditions ``are unprecedented in their detail, their  
clarity and their enforceability and the vigor with which they 
inject competition in these monopoly markets,'' Kennard said. The 
conditions also are backed up with $2.2 billion in fines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't ever plan to pay a dollar,'' Whitacre said. ``I think  
we can certainly meet those standards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But consumer groups say that the deal will not do enough to help  
local residential customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commission has simply abandoned the average guy who  
worries about his phone bill,'' said Mark Cooper of the Consumer 
Federation of America. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI, which along with other major long-distance carriers had  
voiced opposition to the deal, expressed concern about enforcement 
of the conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The new SBC won't be the last word in Bell mergers. The FCC is  
still reviewing Bell Atlantic's proposed deal with GTE. If allowed 
to combine, those two companies would trump SBC as the nation's 
largest local phone company. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Begins No Gun Ri Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The South Korean government began a  
field investigation today that will look into allegations that 
hundreds of Korean refugees were killed by U.S. soldiers in the 
early days of the Korean War. 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the first time government investigators had formal  
interviews with people who have long contended that retreating 
American soldiers kept South Korean refugees under a railroad 
bridge at the hamlet of No Gun Ri and killed hundreds of them in 
July 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigators also visited the bullet-scarred railroad  
bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	``On behalf of the government, we offer a sincere apology for  
coming to this scene so late, nearly 50 years after the incident 
happened,'' said Park Chul-gon, leader of an eight-member 
investigation team. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, The Associated Press reported that American veterans  
confirmed the accounts by South Korean villagers who said they saw 
U.S. forces shoot civilians. South Korean survivors estimated 300 
civilians were shot to death and an additional 100 died in a 
preceding air attack. 
</P>
<P>
	After the AP report, the U.S. and South Korean governments  
promised thorough investigations. Until then, both Washington and 
Seoul had rejected the survivors' claims. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
