<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Buildings Need More Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal buildings have become safer, but some  
shortcomings continue to plague the government's efforts to improve 
building security, an investigator said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Service Administration's Public Building Service has  
made progress in installing security devices -- X-rays, metal 
detectors and surveillance equipment -- in public buildings 
nationwide, Eugene Waszily, a GSA assistant inspector general. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also has taken steps to use most of the $2 million in  
security equipment found in a Washington, D.C., warehouse, Waszily 
told members of the House Transportation Committee's oversight and 
investigations subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the most expensive equipment items, such as X-rays and  
magnetometers, have either been put in service or had a designated 
use planned,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he noted that more than 200 cameras, monitors and VCRs  
remained in storage. ``We have encouraged the federal Protective 
Service to survey all of its other regions to determine whether 
they have any use for this equipment,'' Waszily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Less progress has been made in ensuring that officials have  
accurate and reliable information about its security measures, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Waszily said there were record-keeping discrepancies in 104 of  
207 buildings visited during a 15-month review. 
</P>
<P>
	``These inaccuracies render the national database unreliable for  
program management and decision-making purposes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton launched an effort to increase security at  
federal buildings across the nation after the April 1995 bombing of 
the Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City that killed 168 
people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
