<DOCNO> APW19991007.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 14:30:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed Vs. Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar finished little changed against other  
leading currencies in New York trading Thursday after European 
central bankers decided against changing key lending rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0710, up  
from $1.0697 late Wednesday while the British pound fell to $1.6523 
from $1.6562. The dollar edged down to 107.49 Japanese yen from 
107.51 yen late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Central Bank held the line Thursday on short-term  
interest rates for the 11 nations that have adopted the euro. The 
Bank of England did the same for Britain, which is not part of the 
euro zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Wim Duisenberg, president of the European Central Bank, told a  
news conference following Thursday's meeting that inflationary 
risks are increasing, but not enough to warrant raising interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	He did signal an end, however, to the ECB's easy monetary  
policy. That stance has ``served its purpose'' over the past year 
and ``contributed to a resumption of growth in the climate of price 
stability,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillermo Estebanez, a senior currency strategist at Bank of  
America in San Francisco, described the remarks as ``a fairly 
hawkish speech warning the markets that he is on the bias toward 
tightening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be some doubt on when it happens ... but there is  
some fear that they are closer to raising them than not,'' 
Estebanez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, he said the dollar held its ground.  
</P>
<P>
	He noted that policy-makers at the Federal Reserve had also  
indicated they were leaning toward boosting U.S. lending rates in 
the future even as they left short-term rates unchanged earlier 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dollar has been holding onto the gains that it has had for  
a few days already,'' Estebanez said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of England was not expected to adjust its rates  
Thursday after raising them unexpectedly a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4872 Swiss francs on Thursday,  
down from 1.4891 Wednesday, and 1.4714 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4693. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8259  
German marks, down from 1.8282; 6.1239 French francs, down from 
6.1318; and 1,807.66 Italian lire, down from 1,809.94. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
