<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Sign Antitrust Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Japan signed an  
agreement Thursday to increase their cooperation in investigating 
corporate mergers and price-fixing that affect both countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing the agreement in her Justice Department conference room,  
Attorney General Janet Reno said it ``recognizes the increasing 
interrelations between ... the world's two largest national 
economies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the U.S. Federal Trade Commission,  
who also signed, said the agreement ``emerges out of an astonishing 
increase in global trade and global competition. Almost 50 percent 
of the mergers we investigate thoroughly affect consumers in two or 
more countries, sometimes consumers in 10 or 12 countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japan enacted its anti-monopoly law in 1947 and is now  
participating in the 21st annual antitrust consultation with U.S. 
counterparts. But Hideaki Kobayashi, charge d'affairs ad interim of 
Japan, said officials ``felt an increasing need for an agreement on 
anti-competitive policies so we can cooperate further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Certain differences do exist in the legal framework of our  
countries, which rendered our joint work a challenge,'' said 
Kobayashi, who signed for Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuchika Negoro, chairman of Japan's Fair Trade Commission,  
said it was appropriate that this was Japan's first antitrust 
cooperation agreement because ``our deepest relations are with the 
United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Modeled on pacts the United States reached in 1991 with the  
European Union and in 1995 with Canada, the agreement provides that 
each country will notify the other of enforcement actions that 
might affect it, that they will consider coordinating enforcement 
actions and that each will consider acting against domestic 
behavior that harms the other country. 
</P>
<P>
	While it calls for the exchange of information, the pact does  
not permit the sharing of nonpublic information or evidence 
gathered in a law enforcement investigation. Thus, it falls short 
of the full antitrust mutual legal assistance agreement the United 
States signed with Australia earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein said he  
believed it would increase the exchange of information and 
assistance in obtaining witnesses. ``I look forward to a full 
agreement ... several years in the future,'' said Klein, who heads 
the Justice Department's antitrust division. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States also has antitrust cooperation agreements with  
Germany and Israel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
