<DOCNO> APW19991007.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 09:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Climber Leaves Storied Legacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) -- A notebook left behind at a Montana  
mountaineering shop is part of Alex Lowe's legacy, a symbol of the 
humility typical of the celebrity climber now forever buried in a 
Himalayan avalanche. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe, regarded by some as the world's best climber, put the  
three-ring binder at the shop in 1995 and suggested any ice 
climbers who stopped in write about their adventures. Most of the 
entries, including many by him, detail ascents to nearby Hyalite 
Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	For Lowe, swapping stories with locals about climbs 25 miles  
from home was no less worthwhile than telling magazine writers and 
distant audiences about his experiences on the world's great peaks, 
said Joel Lee, manager of the store. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basketball fans don't get to play basketball with Michael  
Jordan,'' Lee said. ``With Alex, it was different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe, 40, and David Bridges, 29, of Aspen, Colo., a  
high-altitude cameraman, were killed by the avalanche Tuesday as 
they scouted routes on the upper slopes of Tibet's 26,291-foot 
Shishapangma, the world's 14th-highest peak. 
</P>
<P>
	Bridges was part of the film crew recording the expedition for  
American Adventure Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wilcox, president of the film company, said recovering  
bodies of the climbers would be too dangerous, and they will remain 
on the mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably an appropriate place for him,'' said Gordon  
Wiltsie of Bozeman, a National Geographic photographer who climbed 
with Lowe in Antarctica and on Baffin Island in the arctic. ``I 
think that moments before this happened, he was probably immensely 
excited and happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside magazine described Lowe in its March cover story as the  
best mountain climber in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	He climbed on five continents during his 25-year career and  
twice reached the summit of Mount Everest. At the time of his 
death, he was under sponsorship of The North Face equipment 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Expedition members were at about 19,000 feet when they saw the  
slab of snow break free some 6,000 feet above them. 
</P>
<P>
	``They looked up and saw it coming, and basically David and Alex  
were consumed by it,'' Wilcox said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew McLean, the expedition leader, estimated the avalanche  
was traveling at more than 100 mph when it struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's death stunned the community of high-altitude climbers,  
some of whom had believed that Lowe -- known as the ``Lungs with 
Legs'' for his incredible strength and stamina -- was invincible. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people go for the Seven Summits and all these chalk-it-up  
kind of climbs,'' said Gary Bocarde, a veteran guide on Mount 
McKinley in Alaska. ``He wasn't that kind of climber. He was more a 
climber's climber instead of a peak bagger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe was heroic in his efforts, too.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a year when six climbers died on Mount McKinley, Lowe  
was involved in several rescues, said J.D. Swed, chief 
mountaineering ranger for the National Park Service in Talkeetna, 
Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	``He literally, single-handedly saved several people. He picked  
one guy up who had frozen hands and feet and couldn't move and was 
literally inches from death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview with Outside, Lowe downplayed his heroics.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of those things you do because you have to do it,  
one of those Herculean things where you get a lot of adrenaline 
going and you just do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe was married to a Bozeman artist and fellow climber,  
Jennifer Leigh Lowe. They had three children -- Max, 10; Sam, 6; and 
Isaac, 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe reached the summit of the Grand Teton in Wyoming's Grand  
Teton National Park this summer with Max -- which he called one of 
his proudest accomplishments. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
