<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall on Profit-Taking / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices fell Friday morning on  
profit-taking following six consecutive sessions of gains. The 
dollar edged lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 148.95  
points, or 0.82 percent, to 17,987.60 at the end of the morning 
session. The average closed up 240.13 points, or 1.34 percent the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 107.43 yen at midday, down 0.49 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also below 107.49 yen late Thursday 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, share prices opened lower on profit-taking and  
a report in the Nihon Keizai economic daily that the three-party 
ruling coalition had agreed to call on the Bank of Japan to ease 
monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too much pressure on the BOJ is not necessarily good,'' said  
Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, strategist at Daiwa Securities in regard to the 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, International Monetary Fund deputy managing director  
Stanley Fischer urged the BOJ late Thursday to aggressively expand 
monetary policy to ensure Japan's economic recovery is sustained. 
</P>
<P>
	``With interest rates at zero, there is a question of what more  
the central bank can do. One answer is to continue to expand the 
money stock by injecting even more liquidity into the system,'' 
Fischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ has come under intense pressure for a monetary easing as  
the yen has surged against the dollar in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese currency has strengthened largely on increased  
optimism that the economy is recovering from its worst slump in 50 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese authorities fear, however, that too strong a yen could  
hurt that recovery by making Japanese products more expensive 
overseas, thus damaging the earnings of exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Players expected the market to remain cautious ahead of a  
central bank policy board meeting next Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down  
51.29, or 0.5 percent, at 10,537.05 on Thursday as investors took 
profits and awaited Friday's release of U.S. jobless figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 3.81 points, or 0.25 percent, to 1,521.23. The 
TOPIX closed up 12.51 points, or 0.83 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar was slightly lower against the  
yen as traders awaited the Bank of Japan policy meeting next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's decline followed comments by Japanese Prime  
Minister Keizo Obuchi and Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that an 
extra budget planned for later this fiscal year will likely exceed 
$92 billion, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government spending is expected to help support Japan's  
nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 115.08 yen at late morning,  
down from 115.38 yen late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7450 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its 
price fell 0.08 point to 99.61. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
