<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intuit Buys Online Mortgage Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Intuit Inc. will acquire Michigan-based  
Rock Financial Corp., a provider of online consumer mortgages, in a 
stock deal valued at about $370 million, the companies announced 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Rock Financial, which provides mortgages  
through RockLoans.com, would allow Intuit to offer home mortgages 
to consumers in all 50 states via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Intuit leaders said combining RockLoans.com with Intuit's  
QuickenMortgage online mortgage service will combine the speed and 
efficiency of online lending with an experienced mortgage team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The acquisition of Rock Financial advances Intuit's Web  
strategy by giving us the mortgage expertise, technology and 
marketing resources to truly revolutionize the mortgage process,'' 
said Bill Campbell, chairman and acting CEO of Intuit. 
</P>
<P>
	David Schehr of GartnerGroup Financial Services in Durham, N.C.,  
described the deal as ``just another brick in the wall'' for the 
online mortgage industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Online banking, brokerages and loans are still relatively  
narrow product offerings,'' he said. ``Only 10 percent of 
households are doing online banking, fewer are doing brokerage. 
It's still not the preferred method for most people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schehr said online mortgage services are like online car  
dealers: Many people use the sites simply gain information and 
negotiate a better deal offline. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. announced it will offer home  
equity loans over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Other sources of similar online information include LendingTree,  
a North Carolina-based Internet venture that allows consumers to 
browse for the best deals on mortgages, auto loans and credit 
cards. Other players include E-Loan, GetSmart, Microsoft's 
HomeAdvisor and iOwn. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's deal would give Intuit new features, including  
real-time credit checks and 24-hour loan updates. 
</P>
<P>
	Intuit, which has 11 million Quicken customers, launched its  
QuickenMortgage site in November 1997. RockLoans.com began in 
January. Together, the two companies have originated nearly $3.5 
billion in closed mortgage loans in the past 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Intuit also agreed to spend $6 million to buy Title Source Inc.,  
which provides title insurance and escrow services. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
