<DOCNO> APW19991007.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 03:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jesse Ventura Visits Harvard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- It was ``The Body'' and the minds.  
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura visited Harvard University on  
Wednesday, spending time with faculty members, dropping in on 
football practice and talking politics over pizza with about 70 
undergraduates. 
</P>
<P>
	He found himself defending comments made to Playboy magazine, an  
interview in which the former professional wrestler called religion 
a ``crutch for the weak-minded'' and said fat people are overweight 
because they ``can't push away from the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who later signed copies of the magazine, told students  
he doesn't worry about being politically incorrect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not afraid to speak my mind,'' he said. ``If I don't get  
re-elected that's fine. I'll go back to the private sector from 
whence I came.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, who himself only briefly attended North Hennepin  
Community College, said he was flattered by the invitation to speak 
at Harvard by an student advisory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you had asked me at any point in my life if I'd be at  
Harvard talking politics I would have laughed at you,'' Ventura 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some students said they found his openness refreshing.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was admirable that he could speak his mind freely  
without worrying what people think,'' said 18-year-old Brandon 
Fail. 
</P>
<P>
	While that candor has won Ventura fans, it has also ruffled  
feathers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura came under more fire Wednesday for telling Playboy that  
he didn't read books by Ernest Hemingway because the writer killed 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen too many people fight for their lives. I have no  
respect for anyone who would kill himself,'' he said. ``If you're a 
feeble, weak-minded person to begin with, I don't have time for 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota state Sen. Bob Lessard, whose daughter killed herself  
last month, said he was ``astounded and stunned'' and hoped Ventura 
would reconsider his remarks. ``I know my daughter wasn't 
weak-minded,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Harvard, Ventura said that he doesn't have sympathy for those  
who kill themselves and said ``if you're at the point of committing 
suicide it can only get better because you are the lowest you can 
possibly be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he offered a few words to Lessard: ``Losing a child is the  
hardest possible thing a family can endure,'' Ventura said. ``Terry 
(his wife) and I offer our deepest sympathies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura also dismissed results of a poll by the Star Tribune of  
Minneapolis following the Playboy interview showing that his 
approval rating has dropped from 73 percent in July to 54 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I believed in polls I wouldn't be the governor of  
Minnesota,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura also participated in a live town meeting with CNBC's  
Chris Matthews, in which he defended the right to bear arms and 
supported the theory that Lee Harvey Oswald did not act alone in 
the assassination of President John F. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura was scheduled to head today to New York, where he will  
appear on CBS's ``Late Show with David Letterman'' and tape an 
interview with ABC's Barbara Walters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 14:20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that have been moving substantially or  
trading heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq 
Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Airlines, up 1 1/4 at 18 1/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based airline said its planes were more crowded in  
September, and Deutsche Bank upgraded its earnings outlook on the 
company. 

</P>
