<HEADLINE> L.A. Robbery Suspect Tracked to Md. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALISBURY, Md. (AP) -- A college food manager is the missing  
member of a gang that donned masks of former U.S. presidents to 
undertake one of the biggest bank robberies in Los Angeles history, 
the FBI said. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agents said Derrick Anderson, director of dining services at  
the University of Maryland Eastern Shore, was one of four people 
who took $228,241 from the Family Savings and Loan in Los Angeles 
in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, 47, allegedly wore a Richard Nixon mask. He was  
missing when FBI agents arrived on campus Tuesday to arrest him 
after getting a tip from someone who saw a wanted poster at a post 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Police are monitoring Anderson's bank account and home but said  
he could have changed his look, FBI Special Agent Rosemary Vicini 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If (he) knew where to look and who to talk to, it wouldn't be  
difficult to change his identity,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson assumed his post at the school five years ago. He  
supervised a staff of five and was paid $70,000 per year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just so hard to believe, particularly for an individual  
who works so hard and has had such a positive effect on the entire 
campus,'' said Ronnie Holden, the university's vice president for 
administrative affairs who has known Stevens for nearly 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took us all by surprise. It's difficult to comprehend.''  
</P>
<P>
	One robber, Gregory Lewis, was convicted in 1985 of murder and  
sentenced to life in prison for shooting a man whose van was used 
as a getaway vehicle. Two other accomplices were sentenced to 15 
years in prison in 1984 for their roles in the heist. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
