<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Edmundo Freed From Brazilian Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Soccer star Edmundo walked out of  
jail Thursday, a day after his surrender. He will remain free until 
an appeal of his 4 1/2-year sentence for manslaughter is heard. 
</P>
<P>
	Globo News said Edmundo would go straight to Vasco da Gama's  
headquarters to meet with team officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The Superior Tribunal of Justice in the capital of Brasilia  
granted a request for Edmundo's release pending his latest appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old forward's appeal of his March 3 conviction in a  
1995 vehicular homicide case was rejected Tuesday, setting off a 
city-wide, 24-hour search. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was freed until the appeal of his 4 1-2-year  
``semi-open'' prison sentence was heard. His lawyers have asked 
that the sentence be commuted to community service. 
</P>
<P>
	After eluding police for a day, Edmundo surrendered late  
Wednesday. He spent the night in a common cell with six other 
prisoners, since he did not qualify for a special cell because he 
is not a college graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest stunned Brazil, where the rich and famous rarely go  
to jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``The group is sad,'' Vasco coach Antonio Lopes said when police  
arrived at training camp looking for Edmundo. ``Everyone was taken 
by surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it shouldn't have been so surprising, considering  
Edmundo's troubled history. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the remarkable talents that earned him a place on the  
Brazilian national team and numerous national titles, Edmundo is 
best known for insulting referees, cursing fans, and fighting with 
rivals and teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Roma fullback Antonio Carlos, a target of many run-ins when they  
played together on Palmeiras, summed up the problem: ``I was taught 
manners at home, and he wasn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Edmundo was expelled from Palmeiras for his constant  
fights with teammates. Coach Wanderley Luxemburgo relented after he 
apologized to the group, and Palmeiras went on to win the first of 
two straight national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Edmundo kicked a TV cameraman after missing a penalty  
kick and losing a first-round Copa Libertadores match in Ecuador. 
He was detained for three days in Guayaquil, and the Brazilian 
foreign ministry stepped in to avert a diplomatic incident. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 2, 1995, Edmundo was driving at night when his pickup  
truck collided with a car and flipped over. The car smashed into a 
pole, killing three passengers. The truck's airbag saved Edmundo, 
who received 10 stitches in his forehead. 
</P>
<P>
	At the trial, four witnesses testified that Edmundo was going at  
least 60 mph in a 40 mph zone. Witnesses at the nightclub where 
Edmundo had been prior to the accident said he had consumed a large 
amount of alcohol, although Edmundo claimed he only had two glasses 
of beer. 
</P>
<P>
	The court found him guilty of manslaughter and sentenced him to  
prison under a work release program, by which he would spend nights 
in prison but leave to work during the day. It wasn't clear whether 
he would be allowed to play night games or travel out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	Free pending trial, Edmundo led Vasco to the national  
championship in 1998 and set a single-season scoring record with 29 
goals. He was named to the Brazilian national team for the 1998 
World Cup, where teammates said he poisoned the atmosphere with 
constant complaining about not being among the starting 11. Brazil 
lost the final to France. 
</P>
<P>
	After a stormy season with Italy's Fiorentina, Edmundo returned  
to Vasco this year. The team is second in the standings and 
considered a favorite for the title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0131 </DOCNO>
