<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Terrorism Threat for Racing Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- This is the time of year that Dale Jarrett  
would like to be able to focus on his bid for the Winston Cup 
title. Instead, he's also thinking about the threat of terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	Security has been beefed up at Lowe's Motor Speedway in response  
to recent bombings at stores owned by the company that bought the 
track's naming rights, Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouses Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility of violence has prompted Jarrett, the series  
points leader, to change his routine as he prepares for Sunday's 
UAW-GM Quality 500 at the speedway. Jarrett had planned on spending 
the weekend in a motor home in the track's infield, but decided to 
instead commute about 70 minutes each way from his home in Hickory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm concerned,'' Jarrett said Thursday. ``They've done a good  
job here of getting more security, but you just don't know, and 
it's unfortunate that it has to be that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities are investigating the possibility that bombs found  
in three Lowe's stores were planted by someone who feels the 
company failed to do enough to help the victims of a May 1 crash at 
the speedway. Three spectators were killed and eight others injured 
when debris from a wreck flew into the stands during an Indy Racing 
League event. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb threat was called into the speedway last week, and even  
though no explosives were found, it has prompted federal, state and 
local authorities to increase their presence at the track. About 
250,000 people are expected at the speedway for Sunday's race and 
the various activities leading up to the event. 
</P>
<P>
	The added security is most noticeable in the 1 1/2-mile  
superspeedway's sprawling infield, where all incoming vehicles are 
stopped at well-staffed checkpoints. Inside the garage area, there 
are plenty of police officers, some toting guns. Speedway officials 
said the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms is using 
plainclothes agents to patrol the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most visible change, however, involves the drivers,  
who appear to be walking quickly to and from their cars during 
practice sessions, wasting little time to stop and chat or sign 
autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	It presents a stark contrast in a sport that has gained much of  
its popularity over the decades because of the drivers' willingness 
to mingle freely with fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a shame if we completely lost that, and it could  
happen,'' said Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's operations director. ``And 
it goes back to what your grandmother told you and you learned in 
first grade -- that one bad apple spoils the barrel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, who won the pole for Sunday's race, said the  
drivers need to be aware of the possibility they could become 
targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I go back to the Monica Seles stabbing,'' he said. ``That's  
scary. You just don't have any idea. You hope nothing like that 
ever happens. But with the sport growing like it is, you just never 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte said he and his team members attempt to control his  
exposure when he is out in public, especially when he's signing 
autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You try to make sure the crowd's in front of you and not  
behind you or surrounding you,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway usually hires a force of 400-450 people to provide  
security at races. That number has been increased this week, 
although track officials won't give exact numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The security guards hired by the track supplement the federal,  
state and local law enforcement officers who have been assigned to 
the speedway for the week. Triplett said NASCAR also has instituted 
special security measures in the garage area in response to the 
threat of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't be too much more specific other than saying we are  
doing some things here that we haven't done in recent weeks,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway usually stages elaborate prerace shows, complete  
with plenty of pyrotechnics. But all explosions that had been 
planned for Sunday's event have been canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	Any threat of violence doesn't appear to have deterred fans. A  
race-day crowd in excess of 150,000 is expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad and unfortunate that things of this nature don't  
create shock anymore,'' Triplett said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
