<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Major HMO Bill Provisions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Differences among the versions of health care legislation in the  
House Thursday: 
</P>
<P>
	Bill approved by House, 275-151:  
</P>
<P>
	Lead sponsors: Reps. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., and John Dingell,  
D-Mich.; backed by White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits: Lifts federal ban on lawsuits against many health  
insurance companies. Allows patients to sue in state courts if a 
benefit is denied or delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent reviews: Allows patients to take complaints to  
panels outside the health plan whose decisions are binding on the 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Access to care: Requires plans pay for needed specialists and  
for routine care associated with clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	First alternative, rejected 284-145:  
</P>
<P>
	Lead sponsor: Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio; preferred by insurance  
and business groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits: Does not allow any new rights to sue.  
</P>
<P>
	Independent reviews: Allows patients to go to outside panels but  
only if those services are part of the benefit package. Plans 
subject to fines of up to $5,000 per day if they do not follow the 
panels' recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	Access to care: Requires payments for clinical trials for cancer  
patients. No provision regarding access to specialists. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Second alternative, rejected 238-193:  
</P>
<P>
	Lead sponsors: Reps. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and John Shadegg,  
R-Ariz.; backed by many House GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits: Allows suits but only in federal court and with limits  
on financial damages. Patients must go through external appeal 
before taking their case to court. And they must bring their 
complaint to a second panel that would determine whether they have 
been injured. If the panel says they have not been injured, they 
can still go to court, but must pay court costs if they lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent reviews: Similar to Boehner's system, but with lower  
fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Access to care: Requires access to specialists and experimental  
cancer treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Third alternative, rejected 269-160:  
</P>
<P>
	Lead sponsors: Reps. Amo Houghton Jr., R-N.Y., and Lindsey  
Graham, R-S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar to the Coburn-Shadegg bill on lawsuits, but similar to  
Dingell-Norwood on other provisions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
