<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barnes &AMP; Noble Buys Babbage's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a bid to expand its computer software and  
video game offerings, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. will buy Babbage's Etc. 
for $189 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition, announced Wednesday, fits Barnes &AMP; Noble's  
strategy of investing in complementary, fast-growing businesses as 
it looks to broaden its array of entertainment products sold in its 
stores and on its Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately held Babbage's is owned by Leonard Riggio, who is  
chairman and chief executive of New York-based Barnes &AMP; Noble. 
Barnes &AMP; Noble formed a special committee of independent directors 
to evaluate the feasibility and fairness of the deal, given 
Riggio's connection to both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbage's, based in Grapevine, Texas, operates 495 stores under  
the Babbage's, Software Etc. and GameStop names. Most of the stores 
are in malls and offer popular video games and computer software 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbage's also operates an Internet site, gamestop.com.  
</P>
<P>
	The purchase gives Barnes &AMP; Noble, the nation's largest  
bookseller, a piece of the video game and software business, which 
continues to grow rapidly. Barnes &AMP; Noble currently sells some 
software in its stores and online. A very small selection of video 
games is available online but not at its stores. 
</P>
<P>
	According to The NPD Group, a Port Washington, N.Y., market  
research firm, video game and entertainment software sales are 
expected to grow from $8.4 billion in 1998 to $10 billion in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``This acquisition is ... important to the positioning of our  
online affiliate, barnesandnoble.com, where the penetration of the 
fast-growing video-game market is not only complementary, but can 
be considered essential,'' said Alan Kahn, chief financial officer 
at Barnes &AMP; Noble. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Barnes &AMP; Noble will take responsibility for  
$26 million in Babbage's debt. The bookseller expects the 
acquisition to add 10 cents a share to earnings in its 
fourth-quarter ending in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The current version of Babbage's got its start as two separate  
retailers in the 1980s. Two former Harvard Business School 
classmates established Babbage's in 1983, while Riggio and Dutch 
retailer Vendex founded Software Etc. in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the two companies merged, creating NeoStar Retail  
Group. But it ran into financial trouble almost immediately as 
mass-marketers and discount stores stole away business. 
</P>
<P>
	NeoStar filed for bankruptcy court protection in 1996. It was  
then bought by Riggio and renamed Babbage's Etc. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 05:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Play Showcases Unsatisfied Writers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A writer's lot is not a happy one.  
</P>
<P>
	So sighs Irish playwright Brian Friel in ``Give Me Your Answer,  
Do!'', his uneasy domestic drama that contrasts two artists, one 
full of integrity but debt-ridden and stymied by writers' block for 
the past 20 years; the other a prolific popular success but equally 
unsatisfied. They are friends and rivals, each wishing for a piece 
of the other's life. 
</P>
<P>
	Friel's play, which the Roundabout Theater Company opened  
Tuesday, may not be at the level of ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' or 
``Translations.'' It talks itself into corners. Yet the work has 
its haunting moments, particularly in this beautifully acted 
production directed with care by Kyle Donnelly. 
</P>
<P>
	Friel focuses on Tom Connolly, a struggling author who had a  
burst of glory in his 20s. Now, more than two decades later, he 
finds himself in growing financial difficulty and unable to write. 
Tom lives in increasing isolation in Ballybeg, County Donegal, in a 
crumbling structure remarkably similar to the old manse in 
``Aristocrats,'' another Friel family play. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom spends time visiting his autistic daughter, who has been  
committed to an institution. As the lost writer, John Glover 
perfectly captures the man's bitterness and sorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Kate Burton underplays his alcoholic wife with great effect.  
Tom's helpmate is a sardonic woman who grudgingly helps her husband 
but resents everything that didn't happen to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom stands in forlorn contrast to Garret Fitzmaurice, a  
prosperous novelist portrayed with zest by Gawn Grainger. This 
robust man arrives with his equally jocular wife (Helen Carey) for 
a visit. Behind their gaiety, there is a desperate sniping not 
unlike the little wars being fought by Tom and his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Friel's slight story spins on a question of money. An American  
university has offered Garret a sizable amount of cash for his 
collected papers. Now, it may do the same for Tom, depending on 
what an appraiser -- presented here as a nervous, insecure man (the 
wonderful Michael Emerson) -- thinks of the work. 
</P>
<P>
	Fluttering around the edges of this drama are Tom's in-laws: the  
wife, a retired doctor, whose crippling arthritis will soon doom 
her to a wheelchair, and the husband, a spright of a fellow given 
to bouts of kleptomania. Lois Smith invests the elderly woman with 
a commonsense that eludes most of the other characters, while Joel 
Grey exudes considerable charm as her hubby, who plays the piano in 
local hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Tom's considerable flaws, Friel clearly favors the man  
over Garret. Tom lives life on the edge, emotionally, financially, 
creatively. He may not be successful, but he is not any more 
unhappy than his seemingly satisfied counterpart. 
</P>
<P>
	Friel frames the play with Tom's visits to his mentally  
disturbed daughter, a haunting performance by Woodwyn Koons. These 
meetings are where Tom's imagination really soars -- making up 
fanciful stories for an offspring, who, perhaps, will never hear, 
much less understand, them. Then again, she might. Friel seems to 
be saying it is a chance every writer must take. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 03:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Hurts Southeast Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- For more than two decades, Paul Shirley  
and his son David have operated businesses side by side in this Tar 
River community, founded by freed slaves after the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	But the filthy water that swamped the area after Hurricane Floyd  
has put the future of the businesses in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Shirley's S&AMP;J Grocery was swamped by 16 feet of murky,  
contaminated water. Dozens of cars at David Shirley's S&AMP;J Auto were 
ruined. Both face huge obstacles before they can reopen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard there's a possibility the federal government might  
buy out some businesses and homes in flooded areas and demolish 
them,'' Paul Shirley said. ``I'm hoping for that. I'm 80 years old, 
and I don't want to start over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Commerce Secretary Rick Carlisle estimated Wednesday that  
more than 1,000 North Carolina businesses sustained damage severe 
enough to warrant Small Business Administration claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's the worst ever in terms of business  
disruptions,'' he said. ``(Hurricane) Fran caused some problems, 
but businesses were able to get back in business once the trees 
were cleared and power was restored for the most part. 
</P>
<P>
	``This time it's taking much longer for them to get back on  
their feet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd, which came ashore near Wilmington on Sept. 16, drove more  
than 10,000 people into shelters, destroyed 3,680 homes and damaged 
more than 12,000 others. Floyd is blamed for at least 48 deaths and 
causing severe damage in at least 27 counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jim Hunt is seeking $5.3 billion in federal aid for the  
flooded region. Including insurance claims and money local 
governments will spend on recovery, the disaster will likely exceed 
Hurricane Fran's record $6 billion in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd flooded the downtown areas of 30 eastern North Carolina  
towns, including Princeville, dashing the dreams of many business 
owners and damaging economic development efforts in places like 
Edgecombe County. 
</P>
<P>
	Here, it was ``a blow after a real turnaround for a county that  
went from double-digit unemployment to around 7 percent,'' Carlisle 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Waite of the SBA said owners now are trying to clean up  
and reopen for business and the anticipated flood of loan 
applications hasn't begun yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody has a handle right now on what they think the damage  
might be to businesses, both the physical damage and the economic 
loss,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Shirley, who has run his grocery since 1963, is also  
worried about his customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran an old-style grocery store with charge accounts and  
delivery service,'' he said. ``I've had hundreds of customers tell 
me, `Mr. Paul, we don't know what we would do without you.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	They will have to learn to make do without him because the  
floods transformed the interior of his once-tidy store near the 
railroad tracks into a mess of decaying meat and cheese and 
stinking debris. 
</P>
<P>
	His son's used-car and car-rental business also sustained  
massive damage. More than 50 vehicles were flooded along with the 
business office, putting 20 people out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	David Shirley, 50, opened the business after finishing college  
in 1972. He said he has applied for assistance from FEMA and the 
SBA, but isn't waiting for help. He's using some of the insurance 
money from his flooded vehicles to try to resurrect the car-rental 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to depend on myself and not the government,'' he said.  
``I appreciate any help we can get, but we're not sitting back and 
waiting for them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
