<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coelho Wall Free of Donors' Names </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's campaign chairman,  
Tony Coelho, has yet to keep his promise that contributors to a 
Portuguese-American memorial wall in Lisbon would have their names 
engraved on the monument. 
</P>
<P>
	The only names now on the 8-foot-by-60-foot sculpture, ``The  
Wave,'' are those of the artists, according to a check by The 
Associated Press in Lisbon. 
</P>
<P>
	While commissioner general for the U.S. pavilion at Expo 98 in  
Lisbon, Coelho took out a $300,000 personal loan to get the 
sculpture built, and formed the Luso-American Wave Foundation to 
help repay the costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The pavilion books carried the costs of the sculpture as a  
liability, and a State Department inspector general's report said 
taxpayers could be responsible for any unpaid bills. The report 
also cited mismanagement of the pavilion by Coelho and his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho's attorney, Stanley Brand, said Thursday that the names  
would be engraved on the wall, but he did not know when. He said 
Coelho this week repaid the outstanding balance of more than 
$119,000 on the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand said he did not have precise figures on how much of the  
loan was raised from donors other than Coelho, but estimated the 
figure was $150,000 to $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The sculpture, in the shape of a wave, commemorates the  
contributions of Portuguese who emigrated to the United States. 
Coelho is a Portuguese-American. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expo's Internet site said, ``Contribute to The Wave and have  
your name engraved on the monument.'' The notice also said a family 
name could be included. 
</P>
<P>
	The Luso-American Wave Foundation's certificate to operate and  
its articles of incorporation were revoked Sept. 7 by the District 
of Columbia government ``for having failed and/or refused to file 
reports and pay all fees due and owing on or before April 15, 1999, 
and 1998.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
