<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 15:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Stars Roster Selected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The five leading scorers from the 1999 Women's  
World Cup were selected for the World Stars roster that will play 
the champion Americans in the Victory Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The team, announced Thursday, will face all but one of the U.S.  
women who captured the World Cup in July. The only American who 
won't participate is Lorrie Fair, who is attending North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour kicks off on Oct. 22, in Pittsburgh, and will conclude  
Dec. 15 in Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the World Stars will be FIFA World All-Star Game MVP  
Charmaine Hooper of Canada, who has scored four goals in her last 
two games against the Americans. She will be joined by Japan's 
all-time leading scorer Homare Sawa; Ulrika Karlsson of Sweden, one 
of the world's top goalkeepers; three-time collegiate All-American 
Laurie Hill of Mexico; and Australia captain Julie Murray. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway's Ann Kristin Aarones, the top scorer of the 1995 World  
Cup, and teammate Hege Riise, the MVP of the '95 tournament, scored 
four and three goals, respectively, in the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Other potent scorers on the World Stars are Brazil's forward  
tandem of Pretinha and Roseli, one of the world's top forwards who 
was injured for the World Cup; Patience Avre of Nigeria; China's 
sensational Sun Wen and Brazil's Sissi, who tied for the World Cup 
goals lead with seven. Sun and Siss are planning to join the tour 
team in mid-tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``This World Stars team will give fans a taste of what they saw  
during the World Cup,'' said U.S. co-captain Julie Foudy. ``We know 
from experience that great players, no matter how long they've 
played together as a team, can beat you, and these guys are as 
competitive as they come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Victory Tour, sponsored by Toys 'R Us, is a series of indoor  
soccer exhibitions that will also make stops in Detroit (Oct. 24), 
Cleveland (Oct. 29), Chicago (Oct. 31), Philadelphia (Nov. 13), 
East Rutherford, N.J. (Nov. 14), Washington (Nov. 20), Raleigh, 
N.C. (Nov. 21), Anaheim, Calif. (Dec. 9), San Jose, Calif. (Dec. 
11), and Tacoma, Wash. (Dec. 12). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Maneuvers for Soc. Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans want voters to know that  
they would rather cut federal programs across the board than tap 
Social Security's surpluses to pay for more spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to spend it for anything, other than paying down  
the national debt,'' Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., 
said Wednesday. ``Period. We're drawing the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nickles' remarks came as the Senate approved a nonbinding GOP  
resolution by 54-46 advocating unspecified, across-the-board cuts 
in all 13 annual spending bills for the new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the Senate rejected, 54-46, a Democratic alternative.  
That nonbinding measure said that instead of across-the-board cuts, 
Congress should close tax loopholes and find other unspecified 
savings to pay for spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Both votes were mostly along party lines.  
</P>
<P>
	Neither vote advanced Congress' overdue spending bills for  
fiscal 2000, which began Oct. 1. Rather, a battle for political 
positioning was under way, with Republicans casting themselves as 
champions of Social Security and Democrats accusing the GOP of 
seeking dangerous cuts in popular programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., answered Nickles by asking, ``Do  
my colleagues really want to go on record cutting education,'' 
anti-crime, health research and other programs no politician wants 
to be seen as slashing? 
</P>
<P>
	Amid some internal grumbling, congressional Republicans --  
especially in the House -- are considering across-the-board 
reductions to keep from eating into Social Security funds. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans have been considering a 2.7 percent cut to  
achieve that. The White House budget office said that would really 
require a 9 percent reduction, and produced a five-page memo 
asserting that such cuts would have a ``severe impact'' on defense, 
education and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, President Clinton has signed only four of the 13 bills  
for fiscal 2000, vetoed one and threatened to veto five others. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, House-Senate bargainers working on one of the most  
contentious spending bills were ready to roll back some 
House-approved cuts in the National Aeronautics and Space 
Administration and housing -- if Clinton administration officials 
could provide savings to pay for them, said congressional 
participants who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	White House budget chief Jack Lew was talking to lawmakers about  
finding the savings. But the two sides had not yet agreed on dollar 
amounts to be restored or how the extra spending would be paid for, 
an administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity, 
said Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional officials said if an agreement on savings was  
reached, lawmakers would provide 50,000 new rental housing vouchers 
for low-income families that Clinton has requested, the $13.6 
billion he sought for the space program and restore the national 
service AmeriCorps program. 
</P>
<P>
	The House had approved none of the housing vouchers, voted to  
kill AmeriCorps, and pared $900 million from Clinton's NASA 
request. White House officials have cited those cuts in threatening 
a veto of a $97 billion measure financing housing, veterans, 
environment and space programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were other disputes surrounding the bill that leave  
its fate uncertain. House-Senate negotiators were hoping to meet 
formally today. 
</P>
<P>
	In other action, Congress sent Clinton its sixth spending bill  
as the Senate voted 51-49 to approve a $12.6 billion foreign aid 
measure. Clinton has threatened to veto it because it provides $1.9 
billion less than he wants, including none of the $500 million he 
requested for Israel and the Palestinians to implement the Wye 
River peace pact. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Stewart Haas    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Stewart Haas, an award-winning  
journalist and retired professor, died Wednesday after a brief 
illness. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Haas retired in December from his position as associate  
professor of mass communication at Winthrop University in Rock 
Hill, a position he had held since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent most of his professional career working at newspapers  
in Iowa. After graduating from Kansas State University, Haas was 
hired in 1957 as a city reporter for The Courier in Waterloo, Iowa. 
He later worked for The Courier as farm editor, assistant state 
editor, state editor and associate editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Haas served as editor of the Cedar Falls (Iowa) Record in the  
late 1960s after it was purchased by The Courier. He then returned 
to The Courier in 1975 as managing editor, becoming editor in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	At Winthrop, Haas was selected for an American Press Institute  
fellowship at The Seattle Times and conducted journalism workshops 
in Botswana and Zimbabwe. He often spent his summers as a writing 
coach for members of the South Carolina Press Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Haas worked on the editorial staff of the  
International Herald Tribune in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Haas is survived by his wife, Sally Willson Haas; two daughters;  
his sister; four stepchildren; and four grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                           *John Hope Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Andrew John Hope Jr., a prominent tribal  
leader in Alaska, died in a car crash Wednesday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope served as director of community development with the state  
Department of Community and Regional Affairs, president of the 
Central Council of Tlingit and Haida Indians of Alaska, and Grand 
Camp president of the Alaska Native Brotherhood in 1962 and 1963. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert Monsoon    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLINGBORO, N.J. (AP) -- Robert ``Gorilla Monsoon'' Marella, a  
rotund professional wrestler who became a television announcer and 
later president of the World Wrestling Federation, died Wednesday 
of complications from a recent heart attack. He was 62. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6, 400-pounder's wrestling career began in the 1960s  
and ran until the early 1980s. Marella once shared a world tag-team 
title with ``Killer'' Kowalski. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially a villain who feuded with pro wrestling legend Bruno  
Samartino, Marella later became beloved among fans of the 
ever-growing entertainment genre. 
</P>
<P>
	As a ringside analyst on WWF telecasts, Marella was known for  
his on-air banter with fellow announcer Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura. 
A former professional wrestler himself, Ventura now is governor of 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Marella served as WWF president in the mid-1990s.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Paul Petzoldt    	
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Wyo. (AP) -- Paul Petzoldt, a mountaineer who founded  
the National Outdoor Leadership School that has trained thousands 
worldwide in outdoor safety and ethics, died Wednesday of prostate 
cancer. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Petzoldt, who climbed ranges around the world, is credited with  
establishing many guiding and climbing protocols in North America. 
For example, some signals that climbers shout to one another as 
they ascend cliffs were developed by him. 
</P>
<P>
	A sturdy figure with bushy, trademark eyebrows, Petzoldt made an  
early ascent of the 13,772-foot-high Grand Teton in 1924 when he 
was only 16. He made his last ascent of the Grand Teton 60 years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965 he established the National Outdoor Leadership School in  
Lander, about 120 miles southeast of Jackson. It has branch 
campuses in Alaska and eight other locations around the world. 
Nearly 50,000 students have attended the school in 35 years. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Howard C. Raether    	
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Howard C. Raether, known to colleagues as ``Mr.  
Funeral Service'' during his years as executive director of the 
National Funeral Directors Association, died Wednesday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Raether frequently appeared on radio and television in the 1960s  
to defend the industry from criticism leveled by British author 
Jessica Mitford in the 1963 book ``The American Way of Death,'' 
which portrayed funeral directors as using questionable practices 
and taking unfair advantage of grieving survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	He also represented the industry during hearings and debate in  
the early 1980s when the Federal Trade Commission developed rules 
governing price disclosures of funeral goods and services. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Shmuel Schnitzer    	
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Shmuel Schnitzer, the founder and former editor  
of the daily Maariv, died Wednesday at his desk in the newspaper 
office after finishing an article. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnitzer was among a group of journalists who started Maariv,  
an afternoon newspaper, in 1948. He served as the paper's editor 
from 1980-82 and was known for his sharply worded editorials and 
commentaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The article he finished just before his death was meant for  
Friday's weekend edition. The paper printed it Thursday instead. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Schnitzer argued against allowing the  
publication of the memoirs of Adolf Eichmann, who, as Hitler's 
deputy directed the murder of six million Jews during World War II. 
Eichmann, who wrote the document while in an Israeli prison, was 
executed after being convicted of war crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Eichmann's survivors have demanded that Israel turn over the  
memoirs, held under lock and key by Israeli officials. Schnitzer 
argued that if they are made public, the memoirs could be used by 
neo-Nazis to justify or excuse the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnitzer is survived by his wife, and two sons.  

</P>
<P>
                         *Dimitri Tsafendas    	
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Dimitri Tsafendas, who  
assassinated South African Prime Minister Hendrik Verwoerd in 1966, 
died Thursday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsafendas was a parliamentary messenger when he stabbed Verwoerd  
to death in parliament in Cape Town on Sept. 6, 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	The assassin claimed that a giant ``tapeworm'' in his stomach  
had forced him to kill Verwoerd, who was widely considered the 
architect of apartheid. Ruled insane, Tsafendas was imprisoned and 
later sent to a mental institution. 
</P>
<P>
	It was never clearly established if Tsafendas, the son of a  
Greek father and Mozambican mother, targeted Verwoerd for 
institutionalizing the system of white rule in South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	During the decades that Tsafendas was incarcerated, apartheid  
was strengthened, with the country's white rulers crushing attempts 
by the African National Congress and other groups to overthrow it. 
The system finally collapsed with the nation's first all-race 
elections in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Dave Whitsell    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Dave Whitsell, a defensive back on the  
Chicago Bears' 1963 NFL championship team, died Thursday after 
battling prostate cancer. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitsell played collegiately at Indiana. He was with the Bears  
from 1961-66 and was a member of the 1963 team that beat the New 
York Giants 14-10 for the title. He later played with the New 
Orleans Saints from 1967-69. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Tomoki Hitomi    	
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tomoki Hitomi, a Japanese painter who learned his  
trade while on the run from police, died of liver cancer Tuesday. 
He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	He was imprisoned for his involvement in a series of art thefts  
in 1972. Hitomi, whose real name was Yasuo Hitomi, fled to Hong 
Kong in 1973 after police began searching for him in connection 
with the robberies. He later went to Greece, where he learned to 
paint. 
</P>
<P>
	He surrendered to police in 1986 at the Japanese Embassy in  
Athens and was sent to prison in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	After his release four years later, he opened a studio in  
central Japan and held private exhibitions of his artwork both at 
home and abroad. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Alex Lowe    	
</P>
<P>
	BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) -- Alex Lowe, regarded by some as the world's  
best mountain climber, was killed by an avalanche Tuesday as he 
scouted routes on the upper slopes of Tibet's 26,291-foot 
Shishapangma, the world's 14th-highest peak. He was 40. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bridges, 29, of Aspen, Colo., a high-altitude cameraman,  
was also killed. Bridges was part of the film crew recording the 
expedition for American Adventure Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe climbed on five continents during his 25-year career and  
twice reached the summit of Mount Everest. At the time of his 
death, he was under sponsorship of The North Face equipment 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Expedition members were at about 19,000 feet when they saw the  
slab of snow break free some 6,000 feet above them. Andrew McLean, 
the expedition leader, estimated the avalanche was traveling at 
more than 100 mph when it struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's death stunned the community of high-altitude climbers,  
some of whom had believed that Lowe -- known as the ``Lungs with 
Legs'' for his incredible strength and stamina -- was invincible. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a year when six climbers died on Mount McKinley, Lowe  
was involved in several rescues. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe reached the summit of the Grand Teton in Wyoming's Grand  
Teton National Park this summer with Max -- which he called one of 
his proudest accomplishments. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert Monsoon    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLINGBORO, N.J. (AP) -- Robert ``Gorilla Monsoon'' Marella, the  
rotund professional wrestler who became a television announcer and 
later president of the World Wrestling Federation, died Wednesday 
of complications from a recent heart attack. He was 62. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6, 400-pounder's wrestling career began in the 1960s  
and ran until the early 1980s. Marella once shared a world tag-team 
title with ``Killer'' Kowalski. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially a villain who feuded with pro wrestling legend Bruno  
Samartino, Marella later became beloved among fans of the 
ever-growing entertainment genre. 
</P>
<P>
	As a ringside analyst on WWF telecasts, Marella was known for  
his on-air banter with fellow announcer Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura. 
A former professional wrestler himself, Ventura now is governor of 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Marella served as WWF president in the mid-1990s.  

</P>
<P>
                            *A.L. Owens    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A.L. ``Doodle'' Owens, who wrote dozens  
of country music hits for stars like Charley Pride, George Jones 
and Moe Bandy, died Monday from a heart attack. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens' hits include ``Wine Colored Roses'' for Jones, ``Johnny  
One Time'' for Brenda Lee and ``Hank and Lefty Raised My Country 
Soul'' for Stoney Edwards. Owens got the nickname ``Doodle'' as a 
child because he crawled backwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens, a native of Waco, Texas, moved to Nashville in 1965,  
after being encouraged by singer Ray Price. With Frazier, he 
co-wrote two No. 1 hits for Pride in 1969, ``(I'm So) Afraid of 
Losing You Again'' and ``All I Have to Offer You (Is Me).'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Frank Richardson    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Retired state Supreme Court Justice Frank  
Richardson, a conservative dissenting voice on the liberal court of 
the 1970s and early 1980s, died Tuesday at age 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was appointed to the court in 1974 by Gov. Ronald  
Reagan, who had named him to a state appellate court in Sacramento 
three years earlier. He retired in 1983 and spent the next two 
years as chief lawyer for the U.S. Interior Department, then headed 
by William Clark, a former state Supreme Court colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Clark, also a Reagan appointee, regularly dissented from  
rulings by the court under Chief Justices Donald Wright and Rose 
Bird that increased protections for criminal defendants, expanded 
consumer rights and strengthened environmental restrictions against 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote the majority rulings that upheld Proposition 13, the  
1978 tax-cut initiative, and Proposition 8, a prosecution-sponsored 
1982 initiative that restricted some criminal defenses. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Amalia Rodrigues    	
</P>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Amalia Rodrigues, the Portuguese singer  
whose passionate performances of the country's brooding ``fado'' 
music took her from Lisbon taverns to worldwide fame, died 
Wednesday at her home. She was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodrigues' personal secretary, Leonel Henriques, told the news  
agency Lusa that she was found dead in her bed, adding she had felt 
unwell in previous days. The singer had suffered two heart attacks, 
in 1979 and 1980, and increasing health problems caused her to 
retreat from public life in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Antonio Guterres announced three days of national  
mourning. 
</P>
<P>
	Amalia da Piedade Rebordao Rodrigues, known popularly as Amalia,  
became known at home as the ``Ambassador of Fado'' for taking 
Portugal's sad and haunting traditional music out of Lisbon taverns 
and placing it on a world stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Her interpretations of ``fado'' -- which means ``fate'' or  
``destiny'' -- gave the world a glimpse into the depths of the 
Portuguese character. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fado'' lyrics are sentimental and melancholic, centering on  
longing, sadness and fatalism, while the guitar accompaniment 
combines the influences of Arab, African and Portuguese cultures. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Dr. Sydney Salmon    	
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Dr. Sydney Salmon, a nationally recognized  
cancer scientist, clinician and founding director of the Arizona 
Cancer Center, died Wednesday of complications from pancreatic 
cancer. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	He was considered one of the most nation's most influential  
cancer researchers. His successor, Dr. Daniel Von Hoff, called him 
``a remarkable cancer visionary and great leader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon made a number of early influential findings, including  
the first reproducible human tumor cloning and the use of 
chemotherapy following tumor removal, said Dr. David Alberts, 
associate dean for research at the cancer center and a protege of 
Salmon's. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, he was named to the National Cancer Advisory Board.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
