<HEADLINE> Holdout McCarty Signs With Red Wings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Holdout Darren McCarty has signed a contract to  
remain with the Detroit Red Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Wings spokeswoman Sue Gjerset confirmed the signing, saying  
details would be released later today. 
</P>
<P>
	Booth Newspapers and radio station WWJ-AM said McCarty and the  
team agreed on a $5.4 million, three-year contract. McCarty 
originally had asked for $6 million over three years and the Red 
Wings had offered $5 million, the station said. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit television station WDIV and the Detroit Free Press  
reported McCarty signed the deal late Wednesday night and was on 
his way to join the team in Atlanta. The Red Wings play the 
expansion Thrashers tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	A message left today with McCarty's agent, Patrick Morris, was  
not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-1, 215-pound power forward, who missed 13 of the last  
16 games with a groin injury, scored 14 goals and added 26 assists 
last season for the Red Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty, 27, has been a part of two Stanley Cup-winning Red  
Wings teams, scoring the game-winning goal against Philadelphia in 
the final game of the 1997 championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	Both McCarty and the team had reasons to break the deadlock  
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Since players start being paid with the beginning of the regular  
season, McCarty potentially lost income with each game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings only had 12 healthy forwards since right wing Kirk  
Maltby, who had taken McCarty's spot, irritated a lower-abdominal 
hernia in Tuesday's 3-2 loss to the Dallas Stars. He could be 
sidelined as long as a month, Booth reported. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty has stayed in shape by working out with the junior  
Windsor Spitfires of the Ontario Hockey League. 
  	   	
</P>
