<HEADLINE> German Outfit Plans Magnetic Rail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Despite strong signals that the government will  
pull the plug on a magnetic high-speed rail link, a consortium 
backing the project moved forward with plans today to build a 
single line between Hamburg and Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after meeting with industry and rail officials, Transport  
Minister Reinhard Klimmt said a decision on the project would be 
made by Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional talks were needed to determine whether a single-track  
alternative is technically feasible and whether companies would be 
able to finish the project without long-term subsidies, he told ZDF 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	A consortium of firms, however, said it would continue working  
on plans for a cheaper, single-track model, and present full data 
on the alternative before the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has made clear it will spend only the $3.3  
billion pledged by the previous conservative government, and the 
project's backers are proposing the single-rail version as a way to 
stay within budget. 
</P>
<P>
	An environmentalist group criticized the alternative, saying it  
would run above the price tag. Environmentalists also contend that 
the line's electromagnetic field would be a health hazard. 
</P>
<P>
	The gliding train, driven by electrically generated magnetic  
forces on a cushion of air, would cut travel time between Berlin 
and Hamburg by two-thirds, covering the 185 miles in just under an 
hour. 
</P>
<P>
	The first intercity link of its kind, it would carry as many as  
6 million passengers a year on the single rail version, or 8.5 
million on a double rail. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
