<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Poll Shows McCain Behind Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain has moved into  
sole possession of second place behind George W. Bush in a new poll 
of likely voters in New Hampshire's Republican presidential 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls suggested that Democrats Bill Bradley and Al Gore remained  
in a tight battle in the state with the nation's first presidential 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, the former New Jersey senator, had a slight lead over  
the vice president in one poll out Thursday, and the two were 
locked in a statistical dead heat in another. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was favored by 42 percent of likely Democratic primary  
voters, while Gore was picked by 35 percent in the poll done by 
Franklin Pierce College for WNDS-TV. Because the error margin was 
plus or minus 6 percentage points, Bradley appeared to have a 
slight lead, his first in a New Hampshire poll. Bradley and Gore 
were in a statistical dead heat in a poll done for the Boston 
Herald and WCVB-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley led Bush among New Hampshire voters by 51 percent to 36  
percent in the Franklin Pierce poll, while Gore and Bush were in a 
statistical dead heat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key to Bradley's success is attracting independents to the  
Democratic primary'' and the Democratic ticket, said Franklin 
Pierce pollster Robin Marra. ``In the head-to-head with Bush, 
independents favor Bradley by a 55 to 30 percent margin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among likely voters in the Republican primary, Bush had 43  
percent and McCain 23 percent, according to the Pierce poll. Former 
American Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole had 8 percent, and 
magazine publisher Steve Forbes had 6 percent. No one else had more 
than 4 percent, while 10 percent of likely Republican voters were 
undecided in the Pierce poll. The Herald-WCVB poll only looked at 
Democratic candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pierce poll taken a month ago showed Bradley slightly behind  
Gore and in a dead heat with Bush. It also showed Bush leading the 
Republican field with 48 percent of the Republican vote, and 
McCain, Dole and Forbes with 10 percent each. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pierce survey of 564 registered New Hampshire voters was  
conducted Sunday through Wednesday, with 258 saying they would vote 
in the Democratic primary and 252 planning to vote in the 
Republican primary. Independents can vote in either primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Herald-WCVB poll, also released Thursday, found  
Bradley and Gore in a statistical tie, a finding that has been 
reflected in several recent polls. Four months ago, that poll gave 
Gore a 12-point lead over Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	But R. Kelly Myers of RKM Research and Communications said his  
poll for the Herald and WCVB also found Bradley's support was 
unsettled. Nearly two-thirds of those who said they would vote for 
him also said they might change their minds before the February 
primary. Only 45 percent of Gore supporters said they might switch, 
while more than half were firmly committed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Herald-WCVB telephone survey of 403 likely voters was  
conducted Tuesday and Wednesday and had a margin of error of 5 
percentage points. The WNDS poll of 564 registered voters had an 
error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage points for the entire 
sample, larger for subgroups. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
