<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Close Race is 'Liberating' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, trying to put  
his best spin on his tight Democratic presidential primary race 
with Bill Bradley, says the contest is ``liberating'' him for a 
personal and political campaign makeover. 
</P>
<P>
	After cutting the ceremonial ribbon Wednesday for his new  
national campaign headquarters in Nashville, Gore acknowledged 
there was truth to the perception that he becomes wooden and stiff 
whenever TV cameras begin rolling. 
</P>
<P>
	He tried for years to change a style learned from his father,  
the late Albert Gore Sr., but decided to have another go at it 
after Bradley's campaign began to surge. 
</P>
<P>
	``The closeness of the battle for the nomination has been an  
opportunity for me to let 'er rip, and I think that's been healthy 
and liberating,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	'' ... You know, Janis Joplin sang 'freedom's just another word  
for nothing left to lose.''' 
</P>
<P>
	As poll numbers and fund-raising totals began increasing for  
Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New Jersey, Gore tossed the 
prepared speeches and began trying to better connect with his 
audiences. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, he abruptly announced he was moving his campaign out  
of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	At the ribbon-cutting, he wore cowboy boots, khakis and a  
blue-knit sports, and shunned the stage to walk among some 200 
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very powerful moment in this campaign,'' Gore said.  
``Powerful because of what home means. ... Home is where we start 
from. Home is where we learn our values. It's where we return to 
remember ourselves in the best sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though born and raised in Washington, Gore considers Tennessee  
his home. As a boy, he spent summers working on the family farm in 
Carthage, about 50 miles east of Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	As a young man, he studied at Vanderbilt University and was a  
reporter at The Tennessean in Nashville before being elected to the 
U.S. House in 1976. He was re-elected three times, and won the 
first of two U.S. Senate races in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers say Gore's decision to relocate to Tennessee is not  
only an effort to revitalize a stagnant campaign, but to help 
distance him from President Clinton, lose the Beltway insider image 
and trim a staff viewed as top heavy. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Gore announced a new campaign manager Wednesday,  
Donna Brazile, who brings a reputation as one of the Democrats' 
best grassroots organizers. The appointment of Brazile, a black 
woman, also helps diversify a Gore inner circle that has been 
criticized for being dominated by white males. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
