<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Parents Appeal Busing Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Two black parents filed notice Thursday  
that they will appeal a judge's decision ending the 
Charlotte-Mecklenburg school district's policy of busing students 
to achieve racial balance. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Belk and Dwayne Collins' filing in the U.S. Circuit Court  
of Appeals in Richmond, Va., came a day after the school board 
voted to appeal the ruling as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte was one of the first large urban school districts to  
bus students to achieve racial balance. A Supreme Court ruling in 
the case prompted other school districts to follow. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice was dismantled in Charlotte last month by U.S.  
District Judge Robert Potter, who ruled in favor of seven white 
parents who had challenged the 30-year-old policy. Potter said the 
Charlotte school system, which is 40 percent black, fixed its 
segregation problems ``quite some time ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some black parents worry that the decision will result in  
predominantly black schools that receive fewer resources than 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are appealing Judge Potter's ruling because we know it is  
unfair to black kids and poor kids,'' Belk said. ``We will not go 
back to where we were 30 years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The parents' attorney, James Ferguson II, said the judge had  
ignored evidence, misinterpreted the law and exceeded his 
authority. Ferguson will seek a stay of Potter's ruling until the 
appeal is heard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Expects 8.8 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Increasing investment and private  
consumption will help South Korea's economy grow 8.8 percent this 
year, the Bank of Korea said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's forecast is up sharply from its previous  
forecast of 6.8 percent growth. The new figure compares to South 
Korea's economic contraction of 5.8 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation is expected to post a surplus on its current account,  
the broadest measure of foreign trade, of $21 billion this year, 
the bank said. This is slightly up from a previous forecast of a 
$20 billion surplus, but sharply down from a $40.6 billion surplus 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account measures trade in merchandise, services,  
tourism and investment. It is calculated by determining the 
difference between South Korea's income from foreign sources 
against payments on foreign obligations. It excludes net capital 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, South Korea's trade surplus is expected to reach  
$25.8 billion this year, down from a $41.6 billion surplus last 
year, while the consumer price index, a measure of inflation, is 
expected to rise only 0.8 percent this year, sharply down from 7.5 
percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank also said the nation's economy would grow by 6.4  
percent next year, slightly up from its previous forecast of a 
growth between 5 and 6 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
