<DOCNO> APW19991007.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wins Dunhill Golf Opener  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- The top-seeded Americans, playing  
for the first time in Europe since their controversial Ryder Cup 
victory, got a muted but polite reception today, then beat New 
Zealand in the opening round of the Dunhill Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia and Scotland also won their first-round matches 2-1.  
Sweden wiped out Italy 3-0. In late matches today, it was South 
Africa vs. China, England vs. India, Spain vs. France and Ireland 
vs. Zimbabwe. 
</P>
<P>
	American Mark O'Meara defeated Greg Turner 73-74 when Turner  
bogeyed the final hole. Tom Lehman won over Michael Campbell 71-74, 
and Michael Long defeated Payne Stewart 76-72. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, the Americans were criticized for their  
celebrative actions after beating the European team in Brookline, 
Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were great, not one negative thing,'' said Lehman, one of  
the most widely criticized American players in the Ryder Cup. 
``They were very appreciative of good golf and very warm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've made my apologies sincerely, they're not hollow and now  
you go on. It's up to somebody else to accept the apology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman did stumble once. He overslept and missed the opening  
ceremony, which didn't create an international incident on a 
perfect fall day on the Old Course. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no idea there was one,'' Lehman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Scotland's Sam Torrance, who called the behavior of American  
fans and players ``disgraceful'' serving as Europe's assistant 
captain at the Ryder Cup, said that chapter was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans were subdued, quite quiet,'' he said. ``Let them do  
what they do best, which is appreciate good golf. It (Ryder Cup) is 
well over and done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many fans shared that sentiment.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different kind of golf fan you've got here,'' said  
Chris Bell, applauding as Lehman rolled a long approach putt on No. 
3 at the Old Course to within inches. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate our golf here, and we'll never forgive the  
supporters. The American fans were out of order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All three Americans were mobbed for autographs Thursday at  
putting green, mostly but excited teen-age boys. Only their accents 
belied they were Scottish. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they cheated, but I wanted a memento,'' said Paul  
Jensen, 14, showing off autographs from Lehman and O'Meara. ``We 
got no problems with Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish Tiger was playing, he's brilliant,'' added his friend  
Stuart Adamson, 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's Craig Parry kept his side from being upset when he  
holed a 58-yard wedge on 18 for an eagle-2, shooting 3-under 69 to 
beat Japan's Tsuyoshi Yoneyama by one shot and give Australia a 2-1 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never done that sort of thing before,'' Parry said. ``In  
'98 in the Presidents Cup I chipped in on 18 against Tiger Woods. 
That got a bigger roar but this was really special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Leaney also shot 69 to win Australia's other match,  
beating Japan's Katsuyoshi Tomori who had a 70. Japan's lone winner 
was Isao Aoki, who beat Peter O'Malley 72-74. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Dunhill Cup format, the 16 nations play in four,  
four-team groups with the top team in each going to the semifinals 
on Sunday. Stroke-play rules are used with each match counting one 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	Scotland defeated Paraguay despite a 7-under 65 for Carlos  
Franco of Paraguay, who swamped Gary Orr with a 73. Torrance, 
called in as a late replacement for Colin Montgomerie -- he has a 
dental problem -- defeated Raul Fretes 75-77, and British Open 
champion Paul Lawrie defeated Angel Franco 71-73. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden swept by Italy as Gabriel Hjertstedt defeated Costantino  
Rocca 71-75, Jarmo Sandelin beat Massimo Scarpa 79-72, and Patrick 
Sjoland won over Emanuele Canonica 68-74. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
