<HEADLINE> DuPont To Acquire CombiChem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Chemical maker DuPont Co. is paying $95 million  
in cash to acquire CombiChem, which creates computer models 
designed to predict whether an experimental drug will work. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont will add the company to its pharmaceutical division,  
keeping the smaller firm's main operations in San Diego and its 
software programmers in Palo Alto, Vince Anido, the chief executive 
of CombiChem, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be some layoffs as a result of the acquisition among  
the 93 employees of CombiChem, which was founded in 1994 in San 
Diego, but Anido did not specify how many. 
</P>
<P>
	The smaller firm had been exploring merger possibility with  
several companies. 
</P>
<P>
	CombiChem uses a process it calls computational drug discovery  
to help lab researchers predict the outcome of chemical reactions, 
which can save time and money in the pharmaceutical development 
process. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
