<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The leading presidential candidates have  
agreed to participate in a series of debates sponsored by The Des 
Moines Register in the weeks before the Iowa caucuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats Bill Bradley and Al Gore will debate Jan. 8, their  
aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of Pat Buchanan, the Republican contenders  
have agreed to participate in a Jan. 15 debate. They include 
front-runner George W. Bush, Gary Bauer, Elizabeth Dole, Steve 
Forbes, Orrin Hatch, Alan Keyes and John McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, who is considering leaving the GOP for the Reform  
Party, was invited to participate but has not yet responded, the 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both debates will be held at 1 p.m. at Iowa Public Television  
studios. IPTV will air the events statewide. C-SPAN will televise 
the debates nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa caucuses are scheduled for Jan. 31.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Campaign for Working Families, the  
political action committee run by Gary Bauer before he left to seek 
the Republican presidential nomination, has agreed to pay $12,000 
to the Federal Election Commission for violating election laws in 
connection with two 1998 congressional primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer was the head of the organization at the time. The FEC  
announced the penalty Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Campaign for Working Families spent tens of thousands of  
dollars on direct mail and radio commercials in support of two 
Republican congressional candidates, Peter Roskam in Illinois and 
Perry Atkinson in Oregon, but failed to disclose its spending 
within 24 hours, as required by law. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Roskam and Atkinson lost their respective primaries.  
</P>
<P>
	``The mistakes were ones of timely filing but there was no  
intent to hide our participation,'' said Bauer's campaign manager, 
Frank Cannon, who was treasurer of the Campaign for Working 
Families when the violations occurred. ``In fact, from the moment 
we entered the races, we were talking about our participation in 
the press. It was a technical violation in terms of timing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Gov. Jeanne Shaheen and legislative leaders  
said Thursday they would back Secretary of State Bill Gardner's 
decision to hold the state's first-in-the-nation presidential 
primaries Feb. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa officials, who had already set their caucuses for Jan. 31,  
have brought considerable pressure on New Hampshire officials to 
move the date back to Feb. 8 and maintain the traditional eight-day 
window between the nation's first caucuses and firm primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaheen, key lawmakers and officials from both major parties met  
behind closed doors Wednesday to talk about passing a law to 
override Gardner's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	However, on Thursday they said they did not have enough support  
from rank-and-file legislators for such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should be working together with Iowa, as we have in the  
past, to protect the status and relevance of the 
first-in-the-nation caucus and the first-in-the-nation primary,'' 
Shaheen said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, under New Hampshire law, Secretary Gardner has the  
authority to set the date of the primary. Secretary Gardner's 
decision will stand, and we must now focus our efforts on 
protecting our primary,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- It's all in the family.  
</P>
<P>
	Florida Gov. Jeb Bush has agreed to serve as Florida chairman  
for his brother's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am honored to have my brother Jeb at the helm of my Florida  
team,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush said in a statement Wednesday. 
``I know Jeb will pull together a strong leadership team and an 
impressive grassroots organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush, 53, will be in Orlando on Friday, speaking to  
the delegates of the Florida Victory 2000 Convention at a ``Bush 
for President'' reception. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe George has a plan to move this country forward,''  
Jeb Bush said. ``He has been an outstanding governor of Texas and I 
am excited to help my brother by serving as state chairman of his 
campaign.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
