<HEADLINE> UPS Settles Sex Harassment Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service has settled a federal  
lawsuit filed by a woman who said her boss tried to get her two 
daughters to become his mistresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Diane Latone filed suit against Sandy Springs-based UPS, two  
subsidiaries and former UPS Logistics president and CEO Ray 
Thurston last year, claiming he made sexually offensive, 
intimidating and hostile comments about Latone's two daughters, 
both of whom were in their 20s. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit said he proposed that the women be his ``mistress'' in  
exchange for gifts, cash payments and the use of Thurston's jet, 
and that he invited them to live in one of his condominiums at his 
expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the settlement are confidential, Ms. Latone's lawyer,  
Stephen Land, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS spokesman Norman Black confirmed that the case had been  
settled but had no comment. When Latone filed a complaint last year 
before the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, UPS denied 
Latone's complaints. 
  	   	
</P>
