<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Curbs Cellular Phone Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- BP Amoco is warning customers not to use  
cellular phones near gasoline pumps, out of concern that electronic 
impulses could start a fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the risk is slight, the company doesn't want to take  
any chances, BP Amoco spokeswoman Linda McCray said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other oil companies have plans for similar warnings, and  
London-based BP Amoco has already put warning signs on gas pumps in 
the United Kingdom and Australia. The signs will be placed at BP 
and Amoco stations in the United States by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a ban -- this is a precautionary warning,'' Ms.  
McCray said. She said the warning does not apply to customers who 
are in their cars or in convenience stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The signs have a picture of a cell phone enclosed in a red  
circle with a slash through it, resembling signs warning against 
smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	Cell phone manufacturers have included warnings against such use  
in owner's manuals for years because they say that under certain 
conditions, cell phones could help generate sparks. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tom Wheeler, president of the Cellular Telecommunications  
Industry Association, said the warnings at gas stations are 
groundless. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no evidence whatsoever that a wireless phone has ever  
caused ignition or explosion at a gas station anywhere in the 
world,'' Wheeler said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Kelley, a spokesman for the National Petroleum Institute,  
said that while the institute has heard reports of fires sparked by 
cell phones, none have been verified. ``But prudence is probably 
the best policy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman said Chevron will place warning decals on gas pumps  
later this year. Exxon recently started placing similar stickers on 
its pumps. 
</P>
<P>
	And the city of Cicero, Ill., outside Chicago, recently passed a  
law believed to be the first in the nation banning cell phone use 
at gas stations. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
