<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Blocks a Type of Timber Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTON, Ill. (AP) -- In a decision that could affect logging  
nationwide, a federal judge has ordered the federal government to 
stop certain timber sales that were exempted from environmental 
impact reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the second key courtroom ruling since August involving  
logging on the nation's forests. It was also a blow against the 
timber industry, which has seen logging on federal lands steadily 
drop over the past decade as steps to protect fish and wildlife 
habitat increase. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge J. Phil Gilbert's injunction, filed Sept. 28  
in a lawsuit brought by an environmental group called Heartwood and 
two of its Illinois members, affects timber sales under what is 
known as a ``categorical exclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exclusion is used frequently by the U.S. Forest Service to  
allow timber companies to log up to 250,000 board-feet of live 
timber or up to 1 million board-feet of dead timber without the 
agency first completing various environmental impact assessments. 
</P>
<P>
	The exclusion was designed to allow the Forest Service to skip  
costly assessments for projects that were not expected to have 
significant effects, such as removing debris from trails. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, the agency -- over the objection of its own advisory  
task force -- changed the exclusion and increased the size of the 
allowable timber sales by up to a factor of 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists say the agency changed the exemption in an  
effort to avoid costly and time-consuming environmental studies and 
after losing numerous lawsuits over various forms of logging. 
</P>
<P>
	Judi Brawer, an attorney with American Wildlands in Bozeman,  
Mont., said the Forest Service has allowed timber sales under the 
rule in grizzly bear habitat and areas inhabited by endangered fish 
and birds, as well as in particularly fragile ecosystems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have found a number of egregious timber sales under this  
program,'' added Kim Davitt, also of American Wildlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Forest Service spokesman Pete Pierce said Wednesday that the  
agency has not tried to circumvent environmental laws. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the agency Forest Service not decided how it will  
respond to the injunction but has stopped work in affected areas. 
He did not immediately know how many timber sales are affected by 
the injunction. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Gilbert said the Forest Service failed to explain its  
reasoning for the 1992 change. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing continued use of the exemption could pose ``possibly  
irreparable'' harm to the environment if further review shows sales 
should be much more limited, Gilbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Donham, one of two Illinois environmentalists who filed the  
lawsuit, said the ruling could force the Forest Service to perform 
potentially lengthy environmental reviews on all land exempted 
under its policy since Sept. 16, 1998, the date the suit was filed. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, U.S. District Judge William Dwyer ruled in Seattle  
that the Forest Service had violated the Clinton administration's 
Northwest Forest Plan by failing to carry out plant and wildlife 
surveys prior to putting timber up for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ruling, the Forest Service put more than 400 million  
board feet of proposed sales on hold. An earlier injunction blocked 
sales totaling 100 million board feet -- enough to build 7,000 homes 
-- in national forests in Washington, Oregon and Northern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	The landmark plan was adopted in 1994 to balance demand for  
timber from public lands against the need for habitat for dwindling 
populations of fish and wildlife. It reduced logging by 80 percent 
from levels during the 1980s, resulting in the loss of more than 
10,000 jobs in Oregon and Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0198 </DOCNO>
