<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh Welcomes 4-Team Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh Steelers president Dan Rooney has  
long wanted the NFL to return to the days when only four teams 
played in a division. 
</P>
<P>
	With Houston coming back to the NFL as the league's 32nd team,  
Rooney is about to get his wish: eight divisions of four teams 
each. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney has been assured by the NFL that the rival Cleveland  
Browns will remain in the Steelers' division, which probably will 
retain the name of AFC Central. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely needed to expand to 32 teams so we could get a  
better schedule,'' Rooney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFC Central currently is the only division with six teams:  
Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Cincinnati, Jacksonville, Baltimore and 
Tennessee. For years, the AFC Central was comprised of Pittsburgh, 
Cleveland, Houston and Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the only division with six; everyone else has five,''  
Rooney said. ``That's incongruous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The owners still have not decided which teams will go into which  
divisions. Because Houston will play in the AFC, as the Oilers did 
before moving to Tennessee, one AFC team must move to the NFC. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney prefers that Cincinnati and Baltimore join the Steelers  
and Browns in the realigned AFC Central. 
</P>
<P>
	All have rivalries with each other; the Browns and Bengals have  
been in the Steelers' division since 1970, except for 1996-98, when 
Cleveland didn't have a team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ravens, as the former Browns, of course have a natural  
rivalry with Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney prefers each team to play six games in its division, four  
in its conference, four from one division in the other conference 
and, as a switch, two wild-card games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those two wild-card games can be an excellent thing,'' he  
said. ``You could have strong vs. strong games. It could be great 
TV matchups. We can do things that are different than what we 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney is glad Houston will remain in the AFC. In the late  
1970s, the Steelers and Oilers were rivals who met in the AFC 
championship game in consecutive seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have great fans,'' said Steelers offensive coordinator  
Kevin Gilbride, who once had the same job in Houston. ``The times I 
was there we sold out all the time. That old Astrodome used to 
rock. It was a great place to be. They love football. It very much 
reminds me of Pittsburgh.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
