<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Oct. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	House Approves HMO Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today approved a sweeping bill  
backed by President Clinton that aims to give patients a stronger 
hand in dealing with their health insurance companies. ``It is time 
we asked the insurance industry to be responsible for its 
actions,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., one of the 29 
Republicans who crossed party lines. Federal law now effectively 
bans lawsuits against HMOs, even if a patient is injured or dies 
because of the insurer's decision. The House bill allows patients 
to sue in federal or state court and collect damages assigned by a 
jury. But the bill must be reconciled with a Senate health-care 
plan that offers no new rights to sue. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Floods, Mudslides Kill 131  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico -- With dozens of people believed buried alive  
in mudslides, rescue workers struggled to reach remote towns in 
southern and central Mexico, where flooding has killed at least 131 
people. Government officials said the death toll was certain to 
rise as reports come in from towns now cut off from the outside 
world. More than 157,000 people have been forced from their homes. 
Some parts of southeastern Mexico had received 2 1/2 feet of rainfall 
in two days -- a total greater than the average annual rainfall for 
the Mexico City area. 

</P>
<P>
	The Donald Eyes the White House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Real estate tycoon Donald Trump announced that  
he was forming an exploratory committee to help him determine if he 
could win a presidential race as a Reform Party candidate. He said 
his first choice for vice president would be Oprah Winfrey. Trump 
planned a dinner tonight night with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura -- 
the Reform Party's leading elected official. Pat Buchanan is also 
expected to seek the Reform nomination. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Financier Indicted on 36 Counts  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A federal grand jury has indicted rogue  
financier Martin R. Frankel on 36 counts of fraud and 
money-laundering, the U.S. attorney's office said. Frankel, under 
arrest in Germany, is accused of absconding with more than $200 
million in insurance company assets he was supposed to be 
investing. If convicted of all charges, he faces a maximum of 410 
years in prison. Frankel disappeared in early May, shortly before 
firefighters found smoldering documents in a safe in his 
Connecticut mansion. 

</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati Gun Lawsuit Dismissed  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A judge's dismissal of Cincinnati's lawsuit  
against the firearms industry will be used to try and defeat 
similar lawsuits across the country, according to a lawyer for the 
gun makers. In the first dismissal of such a case, Hamilton County 
Common Pleas Judge Robert Ruehlman said the city's claims were 
vague and unsupported by legal precedent. Cincinnati's suit 
demanded reimbursement for the costs of providing police, 
emergency, court and prison services in connection with shootings 
in the city, whether those shootings were homicidal, suicidal or 
accidental. Cincinnati intends to appeal the decision within a few 
days. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Delays Prisoner Release  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A group of 151 Palestinian prisoners who were  
supposed to be freed Friday will remain locked up for now after a 
dispute between Israel and the Palestinians over which people to 
release. Internal Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said Thursday 
that the decision about which prisoners to release is Israel's 
alone, though the Palestinians should be consulted. Under the terms 
of an interim peace agreement signed last month, Israel was to 
release the prisoners on Oct. 8, which the Palestinians observe as 
an annual day in solidarity with the prisoners. 

</P>
<P>
	$3.75B Fen-Phen Drug Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- American Home Products Corp. resolved one of  
the largest product liability cases ever by agreeing to pay $3.75 
billion to settle claims that its fen-phen diet drug combination 
caused dangerous heart valve problems. The settlement covers 
thousands of lawsuits filed nationwide, along with any of the 
roughly six million people who took the drugs even if they didn't 
sue. Pending a judge's approval, initial payments will begin later 
this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Industrials Close Down 51.29  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mostly lower today as investors  
took some profits. The Dow industrials were down 51.29 at 
10,537.05. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,714-1,244. The Nasdaq 
rose 3.52 to 2,860.73. 

</P>
<P>
	Heisman Hopeful Warrick Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Heisman Trophy hopeful Peter Warrick  
was indefinitely suspended following his arrest today on charges he 
and a Florida State teammate were allowed to underpay for clothes 
at a department store by about $391. Warrick and Laveranues Coles, 
both Seminoles receivers, were charged with grand theft along with 
a Dillard's clerk. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  



  	   	
</P>
