<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Oct. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	House Rejects GOP-Backed HMO Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today rejected a GOP-backed patient  
protection bill and set the stage for a showdown vote on a White 
House-endorsed plan giving Americans broad new rights to file 
lawsuits against their health insurance plans. Republican leaders 
had worked fiercely in recent days to rally support for their 
version, which offered patients a limited right to file lawsuits, 
with restrictions on jurisdiction and awards. Democrats and some 
Republicans argued that the threat of a lawsuit is needed to force 
insurance companies to provide promised care. The GOP measure was 
defeated 238-193. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Cancels Prisoner Release  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A Palestinian prisoner release scheduled for  
tomorrow has been canceled, an Israeli official said, complaining 
that the Palestinians had raised demands that were not part of the 
latest peace agreement. Internal Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami 
said a Palestinian official raised objections to the list of 151 
prisoners that would be freed. Ben-Ami said the decision over which 
prisoners to release is Israel's alone, though the Palestinians are 
to be consulted. 

</P>
<P>
	Germans Offer Nazi Workers $3.3B  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The offer by German government and industries  
of $3.3 billion to compensate laborers forced to work for the Nazis 
during World War II is ``an enormous disappointment,'' according to 
lawyers for the victims. ``The offer amounts to about $300 million 
or less in 1940 terms,'' said Mel Weiss, an attorney for survivors 
in class-action suits in U.S. courts. He charged that German 
industry has grown vastly wealthy in the years since it paid nearly 
nothing for the labor of prisoners during the war. German officials 
said the offer would include payment of about $5,500 to each slave 
laborer. 

</P>
<P>
	Trump Forms Exploratory Committee  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New York tycoon Donald Trump said today that  
he has formed an exploratory committee to help him determine 
whether he can win the White House as a Reform Party candidate. He 
is meeting tonight with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura -- the Reform 
Party's leading elected official. In the topsy-turvy world of 
Reform Party politics Trump -- with his vast personal wealth -- would 
stand as good a chance as anybody of seizing the nomination. Pat 
Buchanan is also expected to seek a Reform Party nomination. 

</P>
<P>
	N.H. Poll Shows McCain Behind Bush  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain has moved into  
sole possession of second place behind George W. Bush in a new poll 
of likely voters in New Hampshire's Republican presidential 
primary. Elizabeth Dole was next, and magazine publisher Steve 
Forbes followed. Polls suggested that Democrats Bill Bradley and Al 
Gore remained in a tight battle in the state with the nation's 
first presidential primary. 

</P>
<P>
	$3.75B Phen-Fen Settlement Announced  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American Home Products has agreed to pay $3.75  
billion to settle thousands of lawsuits filed by patients claiming 
health problems due to the company's once popular fen-phen diet 
drug. The settlement will include money to pay patients who say 
they were injured by the drugs and for future medical monitoring 
for those who are still healthy. Pending a judge's approval, 
initial payments will begin later this year. 

</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco Curbs Cellular Phone Use  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- BP Amoco plans to warn customers against using  
cellular telephones at its gasoline pumps in the United States amid 
concern that electronic impulses could start a fire. The risk is 
slight, but BP Amoco doesn't want to take any chances, said company 
spokeswoman Linda McCray. The Chevron Corp. also plans to warn 
against using cell phones. 

</P>
<P>
	Powerbeads Attract the Masses  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Millions of Americans who are buying into the  
latest New Age craze -- powerbead bracelets, which promise to do 
everything from boost intelligence to offer relief from PMS. 
Modeled after Buddhist prayer beads, powerbeads were originally 
marketed last year by Zoe Metro, a New York designer. The beads are 
semi-precious stones that are thought to have certain powers 
depending on color. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Fall; Dow Down 65.85  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as investors took some  
profits. Just before the 4 p.m. EDT close, the Dow industrials were 
down 65.85 at 10,522.49. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 
1,796-1,152. The Nasdaq was down 5.56 at 2,851.65. 

</P>
<P>
	Orioles Fire Manager Ray Miller  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles today fired manager Ray  
Miller after two straight losing seasons with one of the 
highest-paid teams in the majors. Baltimore finished 79-83 last 
year and was never in contention this season after stumbling to a 
4-14 start. Owner Peter Angelos would not say whether general 
manager Frank Wren would remain with the team. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  









  	   	
</P>
