<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Oct. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	S. Korea Begins No Gun Ri Inquiry  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The South Korean government began a  
field investigation today that will look into allegations that 
hundreds of Korean refugees were killed by U.S. soldiers in the 
early days of the Korean War. It marked the first time government 
investigators had formal interviews with people who have long 
contended that retreating American soldiers kept South Korean 
refugees under a railroad bridge at the hamlet of No Gun Ri and 
killed hundreds of them in July 1950. The investigators also 
visited the bullet-scarred railroad bridge. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Wants To Aid Working Parents  
</P>
<P>
	PETERBOROUGH, N.H. (AP) -- Offering relief to parents juggling  
jobs and families, Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley 
today will propose a $26 billion program of education grants for 
parents and children and an expanded family and medical leave law. 
``This is a plan that looks ahead to our long-term interests in 
human terms not just economic ones,'' Bradley said in remarks 
prepared for a speech today at New Hampshire's Contoocook Valley 
Regional High School. ``The new global economy just doesn't care 
about the 6:30 dinner hour,'' Bradley said, adding a poke at the 
Clinton-Gore administration's boast of economic success. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Up in September  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's biggest retailers reported today  
that sales rose modestly in September as the robust U.S. economy 
continued to encourage shoppers to spend despite volatility in the 
stock market, stormy weather and rising interest rates. The winners 
in September were the discount chains, such as Wal-Mart and Target, 
which continue to draw consumers with their wide selection and 
affordable prices. Kmart, however, reported disappointing sales due 
to aggressive price-cutting by competitors on back-to-school 
merchandise. Specialty stores, such as the Limited, also reported 
healthy sales. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan May Close Nuclear Reactor  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese nuclear reactor may be shut down because  
last week's accident at a reprocessing facility means there is no 
place to store its spent fuel, officials said today. The Fugen 
thermal reactor in Tsuruga, 200 miles west of Tokyo, has been 
storing spent fuel on-site since a fire and explosion closed 
another fuel reprocessing plant north of the capital in 1997. The 
Sept. 30 accident 70 miles northeast of Tokyo exposed at least 49 
people to radiation and heightened fears about safety procedures at 
facilities handling nuclear material. 

</P>
<P>
	NIH Director Varmus Leaving  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Harold Varmus, director of the National  
Institutes of Health, is leaving to take a post at Sloan-Kettering 
Cancer Center in New York. Varmus told the NIH staff today that he 
will take the new job at the end of the year. Co-winner of the 1989 
Nobel Prize for discovering a family of genes that helped 
scientists understand how cancer develops, he has headed NIH for 
six years. 

</P>
<P>
	Hindu Alliance Wins in India  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A 22-party alliance led by the Hindu  
nationalists won India's parliamentary elections, unofficial 
results showed today, giving the nation its first chance at a 
stable government in several years. With winners declared for 536 
seats, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's alliance had won 286 
while the main Congress party and its allies trailed at 129. 
Congress, led by Italian-born Sonia Gandhi, suffered its worst 
showing ever, with a projected 113 of the 543 elected seats in the 
lower house. 

</P>
<P>
	Former SS Officer Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- An 81-year-old former SS officer has  
been arrested on new evidence for the shooting deaths of seven 
Jewish concentration camp prisoners in 1945, prosecutors said 
today. Julius Viel is accused of killing the seven inmates at the 
former Theresienstadt concentration camp, in the present-day Czech 
Republic, as they were digging anti-tank trenches near the Czech 
town of Leitmeritz. Viel was awarded the federal medal of honor in 
1983 for encouraging hiking through his newspaper columns. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 4; Nasdaq Rises 15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was up 4.43 points at 10,592.77. Decliners on 
the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,355-1,024. The Nasdaq 
Composite Index was up 15.29 at 2,872.50 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Golfers Get Polite Reception  
</P>
<P>
	ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- Americans Tom Lehman, Payne Stewart  
and Mark O'Meara, playing for the first time in Europe since their 
Ryder Cup win, got a polite reception from Scottish golf fans as 
the Dunhill Cup began today. Applause was light, but there was no 
hint of fans trying to get even with their American counterparts at 
the Ryder Cup. Stewart and O'Meara blame a handful of fans for 
problems at the Ryder Cup that saw the wife of European captain 
Mark James spit on, and an American caddie beat up for carrying the 
bag of a Spain's Sergio Garcia. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
