<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Courts Labor in NYC Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton's third trip to New York in as  
many weeks Thursday was an exercise in Democratic fence-tending, if 
not fence-mending, with carefully planned overtures to organized 
labor and politically active gays. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats traditionally fare well with both constituencies. But  
Clinton, whose 1992 election marked the end of a 12-year Democratic 
drought in the White House, has periodically disappointed each 
camp. Both constituencies could greatly help, or hurt, the 
candidacies of Clinton's chosen successor, Vice President Al Gore, 
and of his wife, the presumed Democratic candidate for Senate in 
New York next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said union endorsement of Gore barely came up during a  
private meeting with Jim Hoffa, head of the powerful Teamsters 
union and a frequent critic of Clinton-Gore policies, especially on 
trade matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said they discussed Teamster trade and economic concerns  
during the 25-minute meeting, as well as other subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a good talk about golf,'' Clinton told reporters  
afterward. ``We didn't talk too much about other politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also appeared at the 24th annual Labor Research  
Association dinner, which honored Hoffa in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Gore, campaigning in Louisville, Ky., made his  
position on unions clear Thursday night. Gore told a union hall 
full of Teamsters members that Clinton has vetoed every anti-union 
bill that has crossed his desk and that he would follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	In a third labor-related event, Clinton combined an appearance  
with a prominent New York labor leader with an evening reception 
intended to raise $500,000 to elect Democrats to the Senate. First 
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton may be among the beneficiaries, but she 
is traveling overseas and did not attend the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton mentioned both Gore and Mrs. Clinton at the labor think  
tank dinner, where he studded his standard fund-raising speech with 
references to union concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so sick and tired of more than a decade of people trying  
to make unions the whipping boy of whatever it was that was wrong 
in America that they wanted to make right,'' Clinton said of the 
time before he took office. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Clinton addressed a gathering of gay activists called  
the Empire State Pride Agenda Dinner, his second speech to gays 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a reason the president of the United States is here,  
besides my heart,'' he told the crowd of about 1,800. ``It is the 
right thing to do, and you have been heard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many gays still resent Clinton's ``don't ask, don't tell''  
policy on homosexuals in the military. He promised much broader 
protection against discrimination when he ran in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also signed legislation in 1996 that took a stand  
against same-sex marriages. 
</P>
<P>
	During his campaign for the union presidency, Hoffa backers  
accused the Clinton administration of meddling in union politics in 
1996 to support incumbent Ron Carey. But Clinton said Thursday's 
visit was not a peace mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not mending any fences,'' Clinton said. ``I have actually  
enjoyed a fairly constructive relationship with the Teamsters for 
the last 6 1/2 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa has argued against early support for Gore, who also was in  
New York on Thursday to seek backing from union members, and 
Democrats generally, in this crucial early primary state. 
</P>
<P>
	Some union leaders have flirted with Democratic challenger Bill  
Bradley, and Gore is eager to line up as many labor leaders as he 
can. Gore appears likely to capture the coveted AFL-CIO endorsement 
despite differences with unions over the North American Free Trade 
Agreement and other Clinton administration policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton-Hoffa meeting was several months in the making and  
recognizes Hoffa's efforts to rid the Teamsters of corruption, 
White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said. Presidents have 
avoided the Teamsters in recent years because of its history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
