<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 50.97 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as investors took some profits  
from Wednesday's hefty jump in prices and looked nervously toward 
the government's employment report on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In late afternoon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 50.97 at 10,537.35. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 8.52 at 1,316.88, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
off 4.62 at 2,852.59. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taking profits is part of the story today after a big runup on  
Wednesday and the other part is waiting for tomorrow to see what 
September's employment numbers look like,'' said Hugh Johnson, 
chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow climbed 187.75 to 10,588.34 on Wednesday as investors  
temporarily set aside worries about rising interest rates and 
focused on corporate earnings. But with the market's volatile 
performance over the month amid nervousness over interest rates, 
many investors decided to take a prudent approach today and collect 
profits before Friday's employment report from the Labor 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The market -- and the Federal Reserve -- will be scrutinizing the  
report to see if there are signs of inflation that could prompt the 
Fed to push rates higher at its next policy meeting next month. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if the jobs creation and wage figures contained in the  
report signal that inflation is under control, analysts expect a 
continuation of the volatility that Wall Street has seen over the 
past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Wachtel, a market analyst for Prudential Securities, said  
upcoming third-quarter earnings reports, which traders have been 
optimistically awaiting, will help some stock sectors, but not the 
overall market. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of the averages, you're not going to get a clear-cut  
bull market going,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the technology-dominated Nasdaq index gave up early  
gains, some high-profile Internet stocks were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! soared 12 1/4 to 188 after the Internet search company  
reported quarterly earnings results late Wednesday that were 
stronger than analysts expected. EToys rose 2 3/8 to 81 3/8; Amazon.com 
was up 4 5/16 at 86 3/4 and Priceline.com rose 1 3/16 to 73 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Internet stocks have turned a corner,'' Johnson said.  
``But I've said that before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, reflecting more nerves about interest rates,  
were mostly lower. Chase Manhattan fell 1 7/8 to 74 1/16, and Bank of 
America was off 1 15/16 at 56 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 643.76 million 
shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index was down 2.54 at 427.22  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
