<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Congress Back Pension Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and lawmakers from both  
parties joined forces Thursday to push legislation that would give 
millions of workers the right to more information when employers 
change pension plans. 
</P>
<P>
	In a written statement, Clinton said the trend among companies  
to convert traditional pensions to ``cash balance'' plans has 
raised concern that workers frequently are unaware they may get 
lower benefits, particularly if they are older. 
</P>
<P>
	``This legislation would ensure that all Americans have the  
necessary information to plan for retirement,'' the president said. 
``It would shine sunlight on changes in retirement benefits. And it 
would do this without unduly burdening employers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, to be jointly introduced in the House and Senate by  
Democrats and Republicans, would require basic notice of pension 
changes at least 45 days before they take effect. For pension plans 
with 100 or more participants, the notice would have to detail the 
new benefit formulas and illustrate how benefit accrual rates might 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, participants in the larger plans could obtain an  
individual benefit statement describing in plain language the 
changes affecting that person. These statements could be requested 
90 days after the change's effective date and would have to be 
provided within a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Employers now must provide notice when they make pension changes  
that would reduce the rate at which employees earn future benefits. 
But such notices do not have to be ``clear and complete,'' as the 
legislation would require. 
</P>
<P>
	``Employees have a right to know and understand the personal  
impact of any changes to their personal pension,'' said Rep. Jerry 
Weller, R-Ill., one of the prime House co-sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 300 companies have converted to cash-balance pension  
plans in recent years. Such plans are popular among younger workers 
because they often can be shifted from job to job and frequently 
permit lump-sum payouts. 
</P>
<P>
	But because the accrual rate of benefits is changed, older  
employees often find that their peak earning years no longer 
translate into higher retirement payments -- and sometimes into cuts 
of 20 percent to 50 percent from what they had expected. This has 
led to claims of age discrimination and investigations by the 
Internal Revenue Service, Equal Employment Opportunity Commission 
and Labor Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Several groups of employees that have opposed pension changes at  
their companies, including IBM and Bell Atlantic, said the 
disclosure bill does not go far enough. They want employees given a 
choice between the new and old plans and some redress for lost 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, employees across the country should have a right to  
meaningful disclosure, but they must also be given the right to 
choose which pension plan works best for them,'' said Janet Krueger 
of the IBM Employee Benefits Action Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Employers also were less than thrilled with the bill. Jim Klein,  
president of the Association of Private Pension and Welfare Plans, 
said requiring detailed individual disclosure statements would be 
``complex and cumbersome'' and might persuade more and more 
employers to drop pension plans altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we want companies to stay within the defined benefit  
system, we cannot make it more onerous for them to do so,'' Klein 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional leaders said they hoped to get the bill to Clinton  
before the year is out, although that may prove difficult with time 
running short. 











  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
