<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Networks' Studios Clog NYC Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Overcome with excitement, Claudia Debro screamed  
at the top of her lungs on a Times Square sidewalk, waving a sign 
addressed to her favorite MTV veejay, trying desperately to get the 
attention of a television camera. She has waited for this moment 
for -- well, weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind her, a man was simply trying to get by. He stepped to the  
left. Unwittingly, she stepped into his path. Back to the right. 
Same thing. Finally, he lifted the 14-year-old by the shoulders and 
moved her aside. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crossroads of the World has never been particularly easy to  
maneuver, but some New Yorkers are objecting to what they say is 
the transformation of Times Square and other areas of midtown into 
de facto sound stages for TV networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The networks have discovered that turning the camera back at the  
viewer during some of its programs yields high ratings -- and crowds 
of people trying to get into the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent trend started in 1994 with NBC's ``Today Show'' at  
its Rockefeller Center studios. MTV and ABC's ``Good Morning 
America'' have since followed with their own glass-walled studios 
in Times Square, and the Fox News Channel has also broadcast 
programs out of its ground-floor facility in Rockefeller Center. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS plans to unveil its own $30 million storefront studio in the  
General Motors building across from Central Park on Nov. 1 for the 
debut of its new morning program, the ``Early Show.'' Bryant Gumbel 
will be the host. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the owners of a swank hotel up Fifth Avenue have gone  
to court to stop CBS. Also, some Times Square-area merchants and 
residents are peeved at ABC for allegedly filming on the sidewalk 
outside its studio on 44th Street and Broadway, causing more than 
the normal congestion. Others unhappy about the trend simply mutter 
and shove -- a traditional New York way of dealing with crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look, this area is crowded anyway, but when MTV goes live and  
these irritating screaming kids come in, the sidewalk is 
impassible,'' growled 66-year-old Manhattan resident Gina Reynolds 
as she pushed through a passel of teen-agers blocking a sidewalk 
outside the music channel's studio at Broadway and 45th Street 
earlier this week. ``Makes me miss the old Times Square. It was 
quieter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The networks, which have invested millions in the studios, say  
they are doing their best to avoid disruptions. Police use 
barricades to keep fans from spilling into the streets, and some of 
the networks also employ their own security personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed earlier this month, the owners of the  
Sherry-Netherland Hotel objected to CBS's indoor-outdoor studio 25 
blocks north in the General Motors building across the street from 
Central Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The network, the hotel says, plans to use the building's plaza  
and ground-floor studio ``as a `tourist destination' where crowds 
(will be) able to gawk through glass at the goings on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People will be waving and shouting and creating that fake  
Beatlemania-like sensation,'' and ``CBS will be able to stage 
everything from concerts to cooking demonstrations,'' according to 
the hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the programs or networks that now broadcast from a  
glass-walled studio has seen its ratings swell, including ``Good 
Morning America,'' where viewership has gone from 3.8 million to 
4.5 million since the debut of its studio in September. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting this week with midtown residents, ABC officials  
promised to try to avoid inconveniencing the public while using its 
``Good Morning America'' studio. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their studio is fabulous, wonderful,'' said Lola Finkelstein,  
head of the local community board. ``But they've got to know that 
they shouldn't block the sidewalk.'' 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
