<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Down; Soybeans Mostly.Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures prices were lower and soybean  
futures prices were mostly higher in early trading today on the 
Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Large stocks of wheat continue to weigh down wheat prices, which  
opened lower. In addition, the market is anticipating the U.S. 
Agriculture Department's crop estimate to be released Friday will 
show another increase in wheat stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn future prices were lower as traders positioned themselves  
ahead of tomorrow's crop production and supply and demand reports, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices were steady to mostly higher in reaction  
to better than expected weekly export sales figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA reports soybean exports for the week ending Sept. 30  
totaled 975,000 metric tons. Gains were limited as harvest weather 
in the Midwest continues to benefit farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery was 1 3/4 cents lower at $2.62 1/2 a  
bushel; December corn was 1 1/2 cents higher at $2.03 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats were 3/4 cent lower at $1.11 a bushel; November 
soybeans were 1 1/4 cents lower at $4.88 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and hog futures prices were higher in early trading on  
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle futures were boosted by higher cash prices stemming from  
strong consumer demand. The strength of cattle lifted hog futures 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork belly futures were higher as demand for bacon continues to  
strengthen, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle were .37 cent higher at 69.45 cents a  
pound; November feeder cattle were .33 cent higher at 82.70 cents a 
pound; December lean hogs were .70 cent higher at 45.40 cents a 
pound; February pork bellies were 1.58 cents higher at 62.80 cents 
a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
