<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 49.07 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower today as investors took  
profit from yesterday's hefty jump in prices and worried about a 
spike in unemployment claims. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 49.07 at 10,587.71. Broader stock 
indicators also dropped. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 
4.03 at 1321.37, and the Nasdaq composite index was off 1.93 at 
2,855.28. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that the number of Americans  
filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose last week to the 
highest level in more than two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists fear a tight job market will push employers to offer  
higher wages and benefits to attract qualified workers. Those costs 
could drive up prices and spark inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Federal Reserve opted against raising interest  
rates for a third time this year. But the central bank, expressing 
concerns that a tight labor market could lead to inflation down the 
road, held open the door to another bump up in rates before year's 
end. Higher interest rates hurt stocks because they can hurt 
corporate earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists believe Fed policymakers may raise rates at  
their next meeting on Nov. 16 . 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Yahoo! rose 8 to 184, after the Internet portal  
reported quarterly earnings results late Thursday that proved much 
stronger than analysts expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, General Electric, slipped 3/8 to 123 1/2 after the Dow  
component posted third-quarter profits that beat Wall Street 
forecasts by a penny. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow on Wednesday climbed 187.75 to 10,588.34. The Dow has  
rebounded nearly 375 points, or 3.7 percent, since last Wednesday, 
when it reached 10,213.48, its lowest point since April 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 113.6 million shares, 
down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index was down 1.45 at 428.31  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.3 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.2 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.8 percent, and France's AC-40 was up 
0.8 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Try To Find Rhythm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) -- Good thing Phil Jackson is patient,  
because the Los Angeles Lakers haven't yet found a rhythm in the 
new triangle offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than a brief half-court scrimmage Wednesday night, the  
Lakers haven't really played any basketball three days into 
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to play, but we're not ready to let them play yet,''  
Jackson said after Thursday morning's practice. ``They're not up to 
that speed, they'll just form bad habits by playing right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So instead they drill while Jackson looks for signs that the  
players know what they're doing. He said the guards and wing 
players are showing flickers of recognition about where they should 
be on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trying to recognize and trying to anticipate and having five  
guys in sync is real important for us,'' he said. ``It was a hard 
practice and a long practice. They got fatigued out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team took Thursday night off and will resume two-a-days  
Friday. Their first public scrimmage is Sunday night on the UC 
Santa Barbara campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``We probably could've gone into a scrimmage situation, but with  
our focus being on the small things and the details of the game, we 
probably would've taken a step backward instead of continuing to 
stay on course,'' guard Derek Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson singled out Fisher as one of the most vocal in practice.  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now everybody's kind of tense because we don't really  
know what to expect,'' Fisher said. ``I'm feeling comfortable out 
there and having fun and sometimes just trying to get guys to 
loosen up and just enjoy being here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson has made no secret of his preference for bigger guards,  
which would seemingly make the 6-foot-1 Fisher and 6-foot Tyronn 
Lue nervous. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be able to provide better defensive pressure as far as  
full court is concerned than some of the other guys we have playing 
guard positions,'' Fisher said of himself and Lue. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than Kobe Bryant, Glen Rice and Shaquille O'Neal playing  
at least 30 minutes a game, Fisher doesn't think Jackson has 
decided who's going to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``There'll be times where I'll play 30-plus minutes, there'll be  
times where I might play 18 minutes,'' he said. ``It'll kind of be 
a game-to-game situation depending on matchups and how guys are 
playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher believes he's going to enjoy the new offense because the  
guards won't be relegated to only bringing the ball up the court 
and passing off. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of opens up more opportunities for me to shoot the  
basketball and create some other plays,'' he said. ``This offense 
is one where everybody is going to be handling the basketball, 
making passes, having open shots. It breeds a real team concept out 
on the floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's the offense, maybe it's Jackson's presence, but  
already Fisher sees better chemistry among his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it was that guys on our team didn't want to  
commit to being on the same page, but I don't think we ever really 
had a page to follow,'' he said. ``Our coaching staff has presented 
something for us to follow and everybody's following it right 
now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
