<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 12:30:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cincinnati Gun Lawsuit Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A judge's dismissal of Cincinnati's lawsuit  
against the firearms industry will be used to try and defeat 
similar lawsuits across the country, a lawyer for gun makers said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first dismissal of such a case, Hamilton County Common  
Pleas Judge Robert Ruehlman said the city's claims were vague and 
unsupported by legal precedent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It very clearly points out the weaknesses in the other cities'  
suits,'' said Jim Dorr, a Chicago lawyer for gun makers Sturm, 
Ruger &AMP; Co. Inc., of Southport, Conn., and Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., of 
Springfield, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorr said Cincinnati's claims are similar to those advanced in  
17 other lawsuits representing 27 city or county governments. 
``These lawsuits filed by the cities have been, in our opinion, 
nothing but smoke and mirrors with no legal foundation to them,'' 
he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati intends to appeal the decision within a few days,  
said Stanley M. Chesley, the city's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruehlman threw out the lawsuit without even allowing the city to  
see documents it wants to obtain from those who manufacture, 
distribute and advertise guns, Chesley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My view is simple: What does the industry have to hide?''  
Chesley said. ``Let's see the documents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati's suit -- against gun manufacturers, a distributor and  
three trade associations -- demanded reimbursement for the costs of 
providing police, emergency, court and prison services in 
connection with shootings in the city, whether those shootings were 
homicidal, suicidal or accidental. The suit did not request a 
specific amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The city also sought to force changes in the design,  
distribution and advertising of guns nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruehlman said he ruled on the basis of written filings and  
lawyers' arguments he heard on Sept. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said only the Legislature, not the courts, has the  
authority to regulate product design and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	He also rejected Cincinnati's allegations of design defects and  
failure to warn users of possible risks from use of guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``There can be liability for failure to warn only if the risk is  
not open and obvious or a matter of common knowledge,'' Ruehlman 
wrote in his five-page ruling. He said that ``the risks associated 
with the use of a firearm are open and obvious and matters of 
common knowledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city's claim of liability for defective firearm designs  
failed to meet a requirement under Ohio law of identifying specific 
products or specific injuries and their causes, the judge ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association praised the judge's decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a major victory for those who believe, as NRA members  
believe, that we must hold criminals accountable for their 
crimes,'' said James Baker, executive director of the NRA's 
Institute for Legislative Action. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants in Cincinnati's lawsuit are Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co.; Smith  
&AMP; Wesson; Beretta U.S.A. Corp.; Bryco Arms Inc.; Colt's 
Manufacturing Co. Inc.; H &AMP; R 1871 Inc.; Hi-Point Firearms; Lorcin 
Engineering Co. Inc.; North Americans Arms Inc.; Phoenix Arms; 
Taurus International Manufacturing Inc., Fabrica D'Armi, Pietro 
Beretta S.P.A. and B.L. Jennings Inc. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
