<DOCNO> APW19991007.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 05:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Leaves Rate Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England decided Thursday against  
changing its official lending rate, currently 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, announced following a monthly monetary committee  
meeting, had been anticipated by the markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Chambers of Commerce called the bank's decision  
``good news for British business,'' which has been hampered in 
export markets by the relatively strong pound. An additional 
increase in rates would likely cause the pound to strengthen 
further, making British goods costlier than products priced in 
other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank surprised many last month when it raised its base  
lending rate by 0.25 percentage point in an effort to dampen 
inflation. Its base lending rate is what it charges for loans to 
financial institutions and the rate is often used as a benchmark 
for changes in commercial and consumer lending rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry and labor unions warned that another rise could imperil  
thousands of manufacturing jobs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 11:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trump Forms Exploratory Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New York tycoon Donald Trump said today that  
he has formed an exploratory committee to help him determine 
whether he can win the White House as a Reform Party candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at the very strong possibility that we could win  
-- and not just the (third party) nomination,'' Trump told The 
Associated Press in a telephone interview from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In a further sign of Trump's seriousness, he is meeting tonight  
with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura -- the Reform Party's leading 
elected official. Ventura, a former wrestler who won the governor's 
office in a 1998 upset, is trying to find a candidate he can back 
in what is shaping to be a fractious nomination fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan is expected to bolt the Republican Party and seek a  
Reform Party nomination later this month. He is backed by another 
wing of the party, a loose alliance with ties to party founder Ross 
Perot. 
</P>
<P>
	Perot's top adviser and the current Reform Party chairman,  
Russell Verney, met with Buchanan this week in Texas to discuss the 
conservative's options. 
</P>
<P>
	Perot, himself, has not ruled out a possible Reform Party run.  
Former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker has indicated an interest in 
seeking the nomination of a splinter group, the American Reform 
Party, which could affect the dynamic of a third party campaign. 
There is even the potential that Ventura, himself, could run, 
despite earlier denials. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether he supports Trump for president, Ventura told  
reporters in New York, ``Ask me that question in the year 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura acknowledged that he was having dinner tonight with  
Trump. ``Do I like him for the Reform Party?'' he asked. ``It 
depends if he likes the Reform Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the topsy-turvy world of Reform Party politics Trump -- with  
his vast personal wealth -- would stand as good a chance as anybody 
of seizing the third party nomination. A CNN-Time poll taken in 
July suggested he would be a long-shot for the presidency. He had 7 
percent when matched against George W. Bush, governor of Texas, and 
Vice President Al Gore, the party front-runners in national polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said that unlike traditional exploratory committees --  
which are established primarily to raise money for a budding 
candidate -- his panel will be formed primarily to provide political 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good thing about this is I don't need the money,'' Trump  
said, signaling that he may finance his campaign himself. 
</P>
<P>
	A Trump adviser said the committee's efforts would be twofold:  
to determine Trump's presidential viability and to begin organizing 
for the internal struggle over the Reform Party nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to look at it and look at it very seriously. The  
polls have come out incredibly well,'' Trump said. ``Based on this, 
and the support of Jesse and other people, we're going to give it 
very serious consideration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said he planned to decide whether to seek the nomination  
by January or February. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said he would not run just to be a spoiler.  
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing that could interest me is if I could win. I'm  
not talking about the nomination, I'm talking about the whole 
megillah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said Wednesday in a ``Dateline NBC'' interview that he  
considers himself a ``great builder and conceptualizer'' and that 
those qualities would serve the country well if he were elected 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump, a registered Republican who says he identifies with  
former President Reagan, said the country ``is essentially in huge 
debt'' -- which he knows a thing or two about, after rebounding from 
the brink of bankruptcy in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he's socially liberal and fiscally conservative,  
supports major tax cuts, abortion rights and health care for all, 
but opposes gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	He also handicapped his prospective competition, saying Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush was ``really untested,'' that Vice President Al 
Gore ``has more ability than is being shown,'' and that Bill 
Bradley quit the Senate in 1996 because he was ``a loser in New 
Jersey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If elected, his first act would be to ``give the country  
spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing we have going and not insignificant ... is a  
good economy,'' Trump said. ``If that economy goes, we're going to 
be a very, very depressed place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The National Enquirer ... did a poll and said I'd win the  
election,'' Trump said in an interview on NBC's ``Today.'' Reminded 
that in a Newsweek poll, 2 percent said they were likely to vote 
for Trump and 73 percent said they were unlikely, he replied: ``If 
I had 2 percent how come they put me on their cover?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
