<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Supports Aviation Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A successful lobbying effort to restore  
funding for aviation safety research managed to anger one of its 
main beneficiaries -- the airline industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign included TV ads showing harrowing pictures of plane  
crashes -- not the kind of image the airlines like to project. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ads may have helped sway House and Senate negotiators  
working on next year's budget for the National Aeronautics and 
Space Administration; they agreed Thursday night to restore $900 
million that the House had proposed cutting from the NASA's budget. 
Overall, the bargainers boosted the agency's budget to $13.7 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The lobbying effort was mounted out of fear that any cuts would  
come would come from the aeronautics part of NASA, which conducts 
research into such areas as strengthening airplanes, coping with 
turbulence and developing new technologies to allow planes to land 
in bad weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The efforts were led by business leaders in Hampton, Va., who  
were concerned about jobs at the NASA Langley Research Center, 
which spends 70 percent of its budget on aviation research. But 
they didn't talk about employment but about possible dangers to the 
airline industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Congress doesn't support NASA today, you won't want to fly  
tomorrow,'' one advertisement proclaimed. Over scenes of airline 
crashes, a TV ad began, ``Air accidents will increase as air travel 
is expected to triple in the next two decades'' and ended with the 
narrator intoning, ``Tell Washington to stop risking your future 
safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We think those are scare tactics,'' said David Fuscus, a  
spokesman for the airlines' trade group, the Air Transport 
Association, which supported full funding for NASA but didn't lobby 
against the cuts. ``They're not accurate and they're in very poor 
taste. No matter what the cause that someone is working on, to 
scare people needlessly is really unacceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic consultant Jennifer Laszlo, who produced the ads,  
said they were accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	``American lives are at stake,'' she said. ``I'm not in the  
business of making pretty, feel-good advertising to sell seats on 
airplanes. I'm trying to defend the idea that somebody who buys a 
seat on one of those planes lands safely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Between $500,000 and $1 million was raised from businesses,  
residents and local governments for the lobbying campaign, which 
included bringing in Laszlo and Republican Frank Luntz to do 
polling and hiring a Washington lobbyist, Paul Hirsch. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirsch is a 20-year veteran of government and a former base  
closing commission staff member who later was hired to help the 
Hampton region keep one of its bases from being shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Herbert Bateman, R-Va., plastered the group's poll numbers  
-- 93 percent of respondents support air safety funding, 71 percent 
agree that the funding should continue even if it exceeds budget 
caps -- in big black type across the tops of letters he regularly 
sent to his colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important to the nation's interest,'' Bateman said.  
``Our airlines will not be able to grow as they are expected to 
grow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bateman also buttonholed Rep. James Walsh, the chairman of the  
House Appropriations subcommittee that handles NASA funding, as 
often as possible, even stopping by a fund-raising event for the 
New York Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	From the sidelines, officials at NASA Langley, applauded the  
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ads are reasonably accurate,'' spokesman Gary Price said.  
``They know in a lab like this, we do work in advanced technology 
that could help many of these problems.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
