<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell Still Not at Knicks Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell remained AWOL Thursday,  
and neither he nor his representatives contacted the New York 
Knicks with an explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the bottom line is, barring a family emergency, he  
should be here,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``And if he had a 
family emergency, he should have called to let us know what's going 
on. He hasn't, and when he gets here we'll talk and go from 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks went through two more practices Thursday, making it  
six missed practices for Sprewell during his puzzling 
disappearance. 
</P>
<P>
	The team expected him to surface at their training camp site at  
College of Charleston as early as Monday night, and his agent, 
Robert Gist, told them Wednesday that he'd arrive from his home in 
Milwaukee by Thursday morning at the latest. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Scott Layden and trainer Mike Saunders tried  
various methods of telephoning Sprewell, all to no avail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've reached out to him, yeah,'' Layden said. ``We haven't  
heard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy and Layden both want to hear what Sprewell was doing  
before they decide whether this merits a fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never had guys miss practice,'' Van Gundy said. ``I  
don't think I've ever had a guy not be at practice who was supposed 
to be. I don't want to jump to conclusions about the particulars, 
because I don't know any of them. When he gets here, we'll sit down 
and talk and decide what to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammates are also reserving judgment, but wonder whether  
Sprewell is handling this the right way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely would like to talk to Spree and see what he had  
to do, but, hey, I'm not in that situation,'' Larry Johnson said. 
``I'm not in Spree's shoes, so I don't know exactly what's going 
on, but we definitely would love to have our teammate here. 
</P>
<P>
	If Sprewell doesn't have a good excuse, Johnson said he would  
also address the matter as a tri-captain, friend and teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said the organization has been very supportive of  
Sprewell, but he has been frustrated by the lack of communication. 
</P>
<P>
	``He should be here. It's a team commitment to get here.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
