<DOCNO> APW19991007.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 06:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Deciding Miller's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- If the Baltimore Orioles don't want Ray Miller  
back as manager, they aren't telling anybody. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract that Miller signed on Nov. 11, 1997, contained a  
provision that stated the team would end its association with him 
if it did not pick up the option to retain him as manager within 72 
hours of the conclusion of the Orioles' 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, coming off his second straight losing season, met with  
owner Peter Angelos on Tuesday for a 90-minute talk. After that 
session, Miller said he granted an extension of the 72-hour window 
at the request of Angelos, who needed more time to reach a 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him to take your time and do what you think is best,''  
Miller said. ``He doesn't have to worry about the 72-hour thing. 
Whenever he wants, I don't care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But The Washington Post, quoting team sources, reported in  
today's editions that Miller's tenure effectively ended when the 
Orioles failed to exercise the option within the 72-hour window. 
The paper said the team was expected to begin the search for a new 
manager today. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no announcement of Miller's dismissal. General manager  
Frank Wren refused to come to the phone late Wednesday night, and 
an Orioles spokesman denied any knowledge of Miller being fired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles didn't part company with Miller's predecessor in the  
traditional fashion, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Davey Johnson sent a fax to Angelos saying he would resign if he  
didn't get an extension or a buyout of his final year. Angelos 
waved goodbye to Johnson and hired Miller to guide a team coming 
off two straight appearances in the AL championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	What followed were two straight losing seasons, including this  
year's 78-84 disaster, for a team that carried a $78.5 million 
payroll on opening day. The Orioles' payroll is the third-highest 
in the game behind the New York Yankees and Johnson's new team, the 
Los Angeles Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Miller's fate is sealed, Wren can't make a move to  
interview possible candidates for the job. Possible successors 
include former Milwaukee Brewers manager Phil Garner, Orioles 
director of player personnel Tom Trebelhorn and former Orioles 
player Don Baylor, now the Atlanta Braves' hitting coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Riggleman, fired by the Chicago Cubs on Monday, also is a  
possibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner and Riggleman would be available immediately. Baylor  
would need the Braves' permission to interview. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
