<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snoozing Mets Fans Miss Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Students, teachers and even New York Yankees  
were exhausted after watching -- or snoring through -- Game 1 of the 
Mets-Arizona series that concluded at 2:05 a.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	And that wasn't even as bad as Game 2, which ended 20 minutes  
later this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball's decision to televise as many games as  
possible meant that New Yorkers were up well past their bedtime to 
catch the first two games of the Mets series at Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so tired, I couldn't hold my eyes open,'' Yankees  
pitcher Andy Pettitte said Wednesday. ``As soon as he (Edgardo 
Alfonzo) hit the home run, I turned the TV off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pettitte got home just in time for the ninth inning Wednesday  
night after the Yankees-Rangers game ended at 11:49 p.m. EDT. The 
two games overlapped for 38 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was as fortunate as Pettitte to last until the  
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made it until the fifth inning and then nature took over,  
but I missed the ninth inning,'' said 17-year-old Mets fan Jeffrey 
Sable, a senior at Forest Hills High School in Queens. ``I just 
fell asleep and I couldn't help it. Today, I was taking a test and 
my eyes were closing. I think I did pretty bad because I couldn't 
stay awake. It's just not fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final out was recorded 2 hours, 53 minutes after it began.  
Many viewers fell asleep well before New York's Alfonzo provided 
the ninth inning dramatics with a grand slam to give the Mets an 
8-4 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's bad. It's wrong. Awful,'' said ESPN's Chris Berman, who  
worked the first two games of the Mets' NL playoff series at 
Arizona. ``Kids deserve a chance to see the teams. I'm disappointed 
as a fan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely a detriment for kids,'' said Grover Cleveland  
High School assistant principal Ira Pernick. ``It hurts their 
studies. But there was no drop in attendance here and the students 
seemed to be alert.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo said major  
league baseball asked him which of the three starting times he 
favored. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have preferred our usual time (6:30 p.m. local time),  
but that wasn't one of the choices. It was 1, 4 or 8. I said 8 
because of our workers and the parking downtown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 2,500 workers at Bank One Ballpark also have day  
jobs or go to school. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it wasn't my call,'' he said. ``It was the networks'  
decision. They just asked for my preference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it was baseball's decision and had nothing to do with  
the networks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try to show all four games whenever possible,'' major  
league baseball spokesman Rich Levin said. ``The fact that Arizona 
is a western team doesn't leave us with many options. We'd rather 
it not be this way, but we try to get all the games on and this is 
what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN would have preferred a starting time in which the entire  
country would be able to watch. However, it wasn't the first time 
the cable network televised a late, late game on the East coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Game 3 of the NL playoff series between Houston and San Diego  
last year was televised at 11 p.m. EDT and posted a 3.0 rating, not 
far off from the 3.3 playoff average at ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets-Diamondbacks game had a 2.7 rating. Combined with the  
3.7 for an afternoon playoff between Atlanta and Houston, it gave 
ESPN a 3.2 average for its first-day coverage, up 15 percent from 
the network's 2.8 for the first two games last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
