<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers Spread Across Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- A day after repelling a militia ambush,  
international peacekeepers spread out across rocky terrain today to 
prevent militiamen from entering East Timor to launch further 
attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been persistent reports that the militiamen have been  
massing just over the border in West Timor, where they fled after 
rampaging through East Timor in the wake of the territory's Aug. 30 
vote for independence from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Fears of further violence rose after suspected militiamen  
attacked a group of peacekeepers late Wednesday about nine miles 
from the frontier. Two Australian soldiers were slightly injured 
and two militiamen were killed in the first clash since the 
international peacekeepers arrived Sept. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, the Australian head of the  
multinational mission, said that although the peacekeepers had set 
up bases near the border, they had not completely blocked access 
from the Indonesian-controlled West Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say our forces are present in strength, but it's a  
long border and nobody is pretending that it is absolutely 
impermeable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cosgrove dismissed criticism that the peacekeepers were not  
spreading out fast enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our peacekeepers are moving extremely quickly ... in this  
harsh terrain to establish security for the people to come out of 
the hills,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeeping mission was bolstered today by the arrival of  
the USS Belleau Wood, an amphibious assault ship. The ship arrived 
off the East Timor capital, Dili, carrying 900 Marines and 900 
sailors for logistical support, Marines spokesman Maj. Rick Long 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not including the forces on the ship, several dozen American  
troops are in East Timor. Another 300 are providing logistics, 
intelligence and other support from Darwin, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	The force's deputy force commander, Maj. Gen. Songkitti  
Chakkabatr of Thailand, also arrived today with the vanguard of 
about 1,500 troops expected to arrive within a week. Those forces 
would bring the mission close to its authorized strength of 7,500 
troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The international force took control of East Timor after the  
pro-Indonesian militias, backed by elements of the Indonesian 
military, carried out a wave of violence, looting and arson 
following the independence vote. That vote still needs to be 
endorsed by the Indonesian parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Indonesians fear East Timor's breakaway will encourage  
separatists in other parts of the nation. An Indonesian general 
said today that the armed forces' top priority is keeping the 
country together. 
</P>
<P>
	The military is determined not to let Indonesia ``follow the  
same pattern of reform as the Soviet Union or Yugoslavia,'' 
Indonesian Lt. Gen. Agus Widjojo said at a seminar in Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's official Antara news agency blamed the foreign  
peacekeepers for Wednesday's clash. It quoted one man as claiming 
they opened fired on a group of refugees returning to their homes 
to pick up goods and food. 
</P>
<P>
	The peacekeepers angrily denied that, but Cosgrove has described  
some of the militiamen who were detained briefly and sent back to 
West Timor as ``poor folk who actually are scrounging for food.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's violence started after Australian troops shot out  
the tires of a truck full of militiamen that ran a roadblock in 
Suai, a militia stronghold about 70 miles southwest of Dili. Four 
passengers were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of militia members were disarmed and taken to the West  
Timor border. 
</P>
<P>
	As the peacekeepers drove back to Suai, they were ambushed,  
Cosgrove said. They returned fire, killing two men and forcing the 
rest to retreat. Two Australians were injured -- one shot at the 
base of his neck and the other shot in the leg and wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees from villages near Suai said the fighting militiamen  
had committed atrocities and forced residents into West Timor at 
gunpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of shooting. They came in trucks. We all  
ran,'' said Aniceto Xavier, a 31-year-old resident of Hatohudo. 
</P>
<P>
	Amnesty International said militiamen and Indonesian troops  
continued to target East Timorese refugees in West Timor. 
Kidnappings have been reported, and conditions in the refugee camps 
are deteriorating, with militias preventing aid workers from 
delivering food and medical supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The two wounded soldiers were flown to an Australian hospital  
for treatment today, defense sources said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
