<HEADLINE> Ex-Jackson St. Coach Carson Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Former Jackson State football coach James  
Carson, who was reassigned in May to the athletic department staff, 
died today at his home. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials confirmed the death, but did not have any  
details. A spokesman at Westhaven Funeral Home said funeral 
arrangements are incomplete. There was no immediate word on 
survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Carson asked to be relieved as coach duties after  
undergoing intestinal surgery a month earlier. Carson had missed 
all of spring practice. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Jackson State officials had declined to discuss his  
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Carson said he needed to have time to gain his strength back.  
</P>
<P>
	Carson's assistant head coach Robert Hughes was put in charge of  
the Tigers for this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Carson had a 54-25-1 career record at Jackson State, including  
Southwestern Athletic Conference championships in 1995-96. His 
teams made three trips to the NCAA Division I-AA playoffs. His best 
season was 1996 when the Tigers finished with a 10-2 record. 
</P>
<P>
	Carson had been a member of the Tiger coaching staff since 1977.  
</P>
<P>
	He was a 1963 graduate of Jackson State.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
