<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some New England Foliage Thrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Despite the summer drought that turned leaves brown, much of New  
England is awash in ambers, yellows and magentas -- and raking in 
the tourist dollars. But some are grumbling that the hues are 
duller than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	The heavy rains in September helped salvage the leaf-peeping  
season, when tourists trek to New England to ogle the fall foliage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The foliage is doing wonderful,'' raved Ally Lutz of the Maine  
Office of Tourism. ``The views are phenomenal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From Rhode Island to Maine, leaf watchers report that the color  
change is largely on schedule. Prime time for color change is 
typically the last two weeks in September and the first two in 
October, with activity starting in the north and working southward. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in August, there was fear that the drought wound ruin the  
autumn leaf show. Leaves on many trees turned brown and fell off, 
prompting fears there would be nothing left to change. 
</P>
<P>
	But after September's rains, including Tropical Storm Floyd, the  
remaining leaves started to turn their traditional reds, yellows 
and golds, said Ralph Scarpino of the Connecticut Forestry 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Art Steniford, owner of the Greenwood Motel in  
Greenville, Maine, said this year's foliage is ``bright but not 
like other years.'' And Kevin Adrien, manager of Leisure Life 
Family Resort in Greenville, complained that the leaves are ``kind 
of dull.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A bunch of baloney,'' countered Dick Hamilton, president of  
the White Mountains Attractions Association, a promotional 
organization in North Woodstock, N.H. ``I look out my window right 
now and see some vibrant reds and oranges. If that's dull, I'll eat 
my hat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inns and tour groups throughout the region reported capacity  
crowds, though many visitors had booked well in advance, before the 
leaf controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaves are big business in New England. New Hampshire officials  
say foliage sightseers contribute about $850 million to the state's 
$3.1 billion tourism industry. In Vermont, the foliage draws about 
4 million people -- more than a quarter of all yearly visitors -- in 
a roughly two-month period, spending about $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	During normal years, trees' production of chlorophyll -- the  
pigment that makes leaves green -- slows and then stops as nights 
get longer and temperatures drop. With their green ``mask'' gone, 
the leaves' other pigments are revealed. The process can be 
affected by any kind of stress, including dehydration. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 03:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: UPS Ends Some Gun Deliveries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- United Parcel Service has decided to stop  
delivering handguns through its ground service, sending gunmakers 
scrambling to find alternatives to the world's largest package 
distribution company, The Morning Call reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based UPS -- which handles the vast majority of firearms  
shipments -- is changing its policy beginning Monday to reduce the 
risk of guns being stolen en route. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to protect ourselves from employees stealing and  
criminals stealing,'' UPS spokesman Bob Godlewski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Handgun shipments have been stolen in the past, Godlewski said,  
although he would not say how many. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will continue to ship handguns by overnight air  
service, since such deliveries involve less risk than ground 
shipments that can take up to six days, Godlewski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight delivery, however, costs about $25 more per gun -- or  
about four times as much for a complete shipment, said Jim 
Chambers, executive director of the Sporting Arms and Ammunition 
Manufacturers' Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we're trying to come to grips with. We're looking  
for alternative methods,'' Chambers said. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS will continue to ship long guns, rifles and shotguns by  
ground. Godlewski said handguns are more of a target for criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Each business day, Atlanta-based UPS delivers 12 million  
packages via its trademark brown trucks and brown-uniformed 
employees. UPS handles up to 75 percent of guns sent from 
manufacturers to distributors and nearly all firearms shipped from 
distributors to dealers, Chambers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Postal Service also will not send handguns by ground  
shipment, said an employee at the service's nationwide Postal 
Answer Line. 
</P>
<P>
	A small gun dealer in Walnutport, Pa., said the UPS policy  
change would hurt his business. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to kill me,'' said Paul Keifer, owner of Keifer's  
Gun Shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Koehler, owner of Eagle Arms Sport Shop near Breinigsville,  
said he supported the change if it helps keep guns off the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``So it costs a little more,'' Koehler said. ``I think it's a  
non-issue. It's their policy. Maybe one day they'll say they won't 
ship any guns.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
