<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indictments Soon in China Trade Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department has decided to charge a  
U.S. aerospace company and a Chinese company with violating U.S. 
export controls after some machine tools were diverted for possible 
use on Chinese missiles, The Associated Press learned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Top Justice officials have approved offering the companies a  
plea bargain of reduced charges in return for guilty pleas. If a 
deal is not reached, the Justice Department will seek an 
indictment, it was learned. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies are McDonnell Douglas, now a subsidiary of the  
Boeing Co., and the China National Aero-Technology Import Export 
Corp., a state-owned Chinese aerospace firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involved McDonnell Douglas' sale in 1994 of surplus  
machine tools to the Chinese company for $5 million. The U.S 
government had licensed the tools to the Chinese company only for 
use on commercial aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	However, McDonnell Douglas learned shortly thereafter that the  
tools had been diverted to a facility that produces Chinese 
Silkworm missiles, and informed the U.S. government of the 
diversion. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors believe that the companies knew or should have known  
that the tools would be diverted before the diversion was reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Some officials, however, have argued that the case against the  
Chinese company is stronger than the one against McDonnell Douglas 
because the U.S. company reported the diversions to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Time magazine, which first reported the story on its Website,  
said the deadline given the companies was Oct. 21, but the exact 
date could not be confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry McCracken, a spokesman for Boeing, told Time, ``We  
continue to believe that McDonnell Douglas acted properly in this 
matter. We've maintained that this is how the system was supposed 
to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing acquired McDonnell Douglas in 1997.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
