<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Financier Indicted on 36 Counts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- As financier Martin R. Frankel sits in a  
prison cell in Hamburg, Germany, the charges against him back home 
in the United States are mounting. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel was indicted Thursday on 20 counts of wire fraud, 13  
counts of money laundering and one count each of securities fraud, 
racketeering and conspiracy by a federal grand jury in Bridgeport. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, 44, who was arrested in Germany Sept. 4, is accused of  
absconding with more than $200 million in insurance company assets 
he was supposed to have invested. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted of all charges, Frankel faces a maximum of 410  
years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel disappeared from his fortress-like Greenwich mansions in  
early May. Days later, firefighters responding to an automatic 
alarm found the homes littered with smoldering documents and a 
``to-do'' list upon which item No. 1 was ``Launder money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, a native of Toledo, Ohio, had been barred from  
securities trading years earlier by the Securities and Exchange 
Commission. He worked from Greenwich, a bedroom community of New 
York City, in a two-home compound equipped with numerous television 
sets, computers and the high-tech tools of international finance. 
</P>
<P>
	When it appeared his financial dealings were about to be  
exposed, investigators say, Frankel fled to Europe with a wad of 
cash and a cache of diamonds, living first in Italy and later in 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel is accused of running a ``racketeering enterprise''  
which bought up insurance companies. The indictment says Frankel 
then siphoned the insurers' cash reserves and used them to purchase 
mansions, cars, diamonds and gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel is awaiting extradition to the United States. Frankel  
has said he plans to fight extradition, although both American and 
German lawyers have recently quit the case after the U.S. 
government froze his assets and left Frankel struggling to pay his 
legal bills. 
</P>
<P>
	A public defender has been appointed in Hartford. He did not  
return a message seeking comment. Frankel's new lawyer in Germany 
also did not return a phone call seeking comment, which was left 
after business hours there. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators say Frankel's unlicensed brokerage siphoned at least  
$218 million from insurers in Arkansas, Mississippi, Missouri, 
Oklahoma and Tennessee. A lawsuit filed by some of the companies 
puts the loss at $915 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities in Mississippi have said they plan to ask a grand  
jury for indictments against Frankel and his associates for 
allegedly stealing more than $200 million from insurance companies 
in that state. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi Insurance Commissioner George Dale said he welcomes  
the Connecticut indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping this could lead to us being able to recover some of  
the millions of dollars we think belong to our re-insurance 
companies,'' Dale said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tennessee, authorities last month charged Frankel and  
unidentified associates with stealing more than $18 million from 
the Franklin American Life Insurance Co. District Attorney General 
Ron Davis said he was pleased by the Connecticut federal 
indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It couldn't happen to a nicer guy,'' Davis said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
