<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virus Claims 6th Victim in NY Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) -- A sixth person in the New York City  
metropolitan region has died from the West Nile-like virus, health 
officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 76-year-old woman, who lived in Nassau County just east of  
the city, died several days ago, said county Health Department 
spokeswoman Cynthia Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The mosquito-borne virus so far has infected 54 people in the  
metropolitan area, according to the state Department of Health. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, meanwhile, doctors were examining an encephalitis  
patient to see if he was suffering from the same strain that killed 
the six victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point there is no evidence that this case here is  
linked to that outbreak,'' said Dr. Elliot Frank of Jersey Shore 
Medical Center, where the man was in critical condition. ``The only 
thing unusual is that we happen to be a state next to a state 
that's having an outbreak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been no confirmed cases of West Nile-like virus in  
New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	The virus -- never before recorded in the Western Hemisphere -- is  
believed to have entered the United States in infected birds. 
Hundreds of dead birds have been found in recent weeks from 
Connecticut south to New Jersey and Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	In rare cases, the virus can cause neurological disorders and  
death. The elderly, young and those with weakened immune systems 
are most vulnerable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
