<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against all the other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0730 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0737 Wednesday. Later in midday trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0720. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,  
included 107.60 Japanese yen, up from 107.44; 1.4840 Swiss francs, 
up from 1.4811; 1.4698 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4690. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6524, down from $1.6545.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 107.61 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6518. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8231 German marks, up from 1.8216; 
6.1139 French francs, up from 6.1093; 2.0536 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0524; 1,804.37 Italian lire, up from 1,803.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $322.50 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$320.40 on Wednesday. In Zurich the bid price was $322.30, up from 
$319.00. Gold was unchanged in Hong Kong at $323.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.63 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.59. 
  	   	
</P>
