<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Tackle Ready for Giants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- The Arizona Cardinals sure could use some  
good news, and they finally got some. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Swann, the Arizona Cardinals' two-time Pro Bowl defensive  
tackle who's been out nearly a year while recovering from two 
operations on his arthritic right knee, is ready to play again. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have cleared him, and he plans to see action in  
long-yardage situations against the New York Giants on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The knee's doing great,'' Swann said after Thursday's  
practice. ``I passed all the tests, the endurance test on it and 
the sprint test, so we're going to go out and just have some fun 
this weekend with the Giants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5 Swann, who said he's lost 30 pounds since he last  
played at a slimmed-down 305 pounds. He said that initially he will 
go in on second- and third-and-long situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm needed, I'll probably go in for more,'' Swann said.  
``If not, we're going to take it slow and re-evaluate it after 
three weeks. If everything is fine by then, I'm cleared to go the 
rest of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said it's important to limit  
Swann's participation at first. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will use him in this ball game,'' McGinnis said, ``but when  
and how much will depend on what goes on the rest of the week. He 
won't play 70 snaps, that's for sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann has been severely criticized by some fans and local sports  
talk show hosts who thought he abandoned the team by not trying to 
come back for last year's playoff run following the first surgery. 
But Swann has said he did what he had to do to try to save his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I had to do something if I wanted to continue to play  
football, and my heart's still in the game,'' Swann said. ``I'm not 
done with the game yet. I've got probably another good six or seven 
years left in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann, plagued by constant pain that he compared with ``running  
around with a tack in your shoe,'' first underwent surgery by 
Cardinals team doctor Russell Chick shortly after the seventh game 
last season, which also was against the Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissatisfied with the outcome, he had a second, more extensive  
and unorthodox surgery performed by Dr. Richard Steadman, the noted 
knee specialist in Vail, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	What followed was a long rehabilitation process.  
</P>
<P>
	``I see a guy that's anxious to get back, didn't like the  
situation he was in and has worked extremely hard to get back,'' 
coach Vince Tobin said. ``It's been the popular thing to throw 
brickbats at Eric Swann, but I've seen a guy that's worked awfully 
hard in a very lonely, regimented routine to get back as quickly as 
he can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann's imminent return was welcome news to a team that limps  
into the Giants game with a 1-3 record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully he'll be lifting up those guards and centers on the  
other team and throwing them in the backfield,'' quarterback Jake 
Plummer said. ``It's great to have him back. He's worked so hard. 
I'm excited to see him play. He's such a force in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann said he knows opponents will target his knee in his first  
few games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they are. I've been doing that myself,'' he said with  
a smile. ``I've allowed my 2-year-old to jump up and down on it, 
and cut block me and everything else, so it feels great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Cardinals were awaiting word from defensive  
tackle Mark Smith, who went to Colorado for a second opinion from 
Steadman on what should be done about fluid on Smith's right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	If Smith has arthroscopic surgery, he could be out 3-4 weeks.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
