<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Oct. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	House OKs HMO Lawsuit Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today approved a sweeping bill meant  
to give patients a stronger hand in dealing with their health 
insurance companies, including a controversial new right to file 
lawsuits. The final vote was 275-151. Now the House bill must be 
reconciled with a considerably more limited version already 
approved by the Senate. The Senate bill has no new rights to sue 
and excludes many Americans from other patient protections. 
Earlier, the House rejected a GOP-backed patient protection bill 
that included new rights to sue, but only in federal court and only 
in limited circumstances. 

</P>
<P>
	$3.75B Fen-Phen Drug Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- American Home Products Corp. resolved one of  
the largest product liability cases ever today by agreeing to pay 
$3.75 billion to settle claims that its once-popular fen-phen diet 
drug combination caused dangerous heart valve problems. The 
settlement covers thousands of lawsuits filed nationwide, along 
with any of the roughly six million people who took the drugs even 
if they didn't sue. It will include money to pay those who say they 
were made ill by the drugs and for future medical monitoring for 
those who are still healthy. Individual benefits will range from 
$30 for prescription refunds to a maximum of $1.5 million per 
person for people with serious health problems. AHP shares were at 
48 3/4, up 3 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Industrials Close Down 51.29  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mixed today as investors took some  
profits from Wednesday's hefty jump in prices and looked nervously 
toward the government's employment report tomorrow. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 51.29 at 10,537.05. Broader stock 
indicators were mixed, with the Nasdaq composite index closing 
modestly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 7.76 at 
1,317.64, and the Nasdaq composite index rose 3.52 to 2,860.73. 

</P>
