<P>
	U.S. Consumers Keep Buying  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans maintained their shopping spree at the  
nation's stores and malls in September, hardly slowed by volatility 
in the stock market, stormy weather and rising interest rates. 
While sales reports today were generally strong, some merchants 
lost business because of Hurricane Floyd, which battered the East 
Coast last month. The storm also boosted the number of Americans 
filing new claims for employment benefits to the highest level in 
more than two months. Indicatons are that good retail sales will 
continue through the end of the year and into the Christmas season, 
according to Steve Paspal, senior retail analyst at Sovereign Asset 
Management, a subsidiary of John Hancock Funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Borrowing Rises in August  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' borrowing raced ahead in August,  
posting the largest monthly increase in seven months, led by strong 
demand for loans for everything from autos and boats to education 
and vacation. Consumers' credit outstanding, excluding mortgage 
debt, advanced at a 9.6 percent annual rate in August to a 
seasonally adjusted $1.367 trillion, the Federal Reserve said 
today. All told, consumers borrowed $10.8 billion more in August 
than during the month before. That was the biggest monthly increase 
since January when it rose by $15.3 billion The increase in the 
level of borrowing in August was much stronger than many analysts 
expected. They were forecasting a monthly gain of $6.5 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Financier Indicted on 36 Counts  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A federal grand jury has indicted rogue  
financier Martin R. Frankel on 36 counts of fraud and 
money-laundering, the U.S. attorney's office said today. If 
convicted of all charges, Frankel faces a maximum of 410 years in 
prison. Frankel, under arrest in Germany, is accused of absconding 
with more than $200 million in insurance company assets he was 
supposed to be investing. Frankel disappeared from his 
fortress-like Greenwich mansions in early May, shortly before 
firefighters responding to an automatic alarm found smoldering 
documents in a safe and a ``to-do'' list upon which item No. 1 was 
``Launder money.'' 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European shares closed higher today after the  
European Central Bank decided to leave its key interest rates 
unchanged. Bank President Wim Duisenberg said more evidence of 
inflation is needed to justify an interest rate rise. The Dow Jones 
Stoxx Index of 614 European companies rose 2.64 points to close at 
311.57. The best performing sector was telecommunications, up 2.3 
percent, with MCI WorldCom's bid for Sprint earlier this week 
fueling talk about consolidation across Europe. In London, telecom 
shares were the best performers in the FTSE 100 index of blue-chip 
shares, which closed with a gain of 1.7 percent, at 6,200.4. 
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index rose 1.2 percent to 5,419.31. 

</P>
<P>
	Macromedia To Acquire Andromedia  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Macromedia Inc., a provider of tools for  
building Web sites, said it is acquiring Andromedia Inc., maker of 
electronic commerce software for the Internet. The announcement was 
made in New York at the Fall Internet World '99 convention. 
Andromedia, based in San Francisco, makes software that analyzes 
data about Web site visitors. It also allows Web sites to be 
customized based on the data about the user. Terms of the deal were 
not announced. 

</P>
