<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Superintendent Named for Yosemite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- The new superintendent of  
Yosemite National Park arrived for introductions Thursday with a 
huge task already awaiting him: finding a way to please both 
environmentalists and carloads of tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	David Mihalic, introduced by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt,  
will be taking over Oct. 25 with a charge to finish a long-delayed 
management plan for the park by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan includes decisions on whether to widen a highway and  
allow more buses and cars into the center of the congested park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just a poor, shy country boy from Montana, and the world  
out here in California moves pretty quickly, so I'm just going to 
have to get used to it,'' Mihalic said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mihalic, 53, who is replacing Stanley Albright, 68, comes to  
Yosemite from Glacier National Park in Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt said the Montana park is second only to Yosemite when it  
comes to complex visitor and political problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the most difficult and complicated planning  
exercises in the National Park Service,'' Babbitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yosemite can trace many of its woes to its spectacular setting --  
too many people want to drive in to marvel at the granite cliffs 
and stunning waterfalls. As many as 7,000 cars squeeze into the 
park on any given day. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's room in this park for every American and their  
families,'' said Babbitt. ``There's not enough room in this park 
for everyone and their cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yosemite has also faced some darker problems this year with the  
disappearance of three female sightseers who were later found dead 
and the decapitation death of park naturalist Joie Ruth Armstrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Cary Stayner, 38, a part-time handyman at a motel just outside  
the park, has pleaded innocent in the Armstrong case and has not 
been charged in the other deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	At Glacier, Mihalic dealt with controversies over rebuilding a  
vital road, restoring historic buildings and banning personal 
watercraft and overflight tours. 
</P>
<P>
	Glacier's 1.4 million acres draw 1.8 million tourists a year.  
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, 3.8 million visitors crowded into Yosemite's  
748,000 acres in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before Albright arrived in October 1997, Congress approved  
$176 million to repair damage from a devastating 1997 flood that 
sent the Merced River spilling over its banks, damaging roads and 
buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Sierra Club sued over plans to widen a road along the  
river, and persuaded a federal judge this summer to order up a new 
river management plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Mihalic's past has won him supporters within the environmental  
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	His management plan at Glacier banned snowmobiles and Jet Skis  
and included language to ban air tours, said Rose Fennell of The 
Wilderness Society in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's definitely someone we can work with,'' said  
Fennell. ``He seems to have put resource conservation before 
recreational uses.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
