<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Contact' Is Exhilirating Fun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It has been so long since dance played an  
important part in musical theater that ``Contact,'' billed coyly as 
``a dance play,'' seems positively revolutionary. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only revolutionary but fun, exhilarating in a way that few  
musicals have been during the past several seasons. ``Fosse'' 
doesn't count, being solely about the master choreographer's way 
with movement, not character or story. 
</P>
<P>
	``Contact,'' which Lincoln Center Theater opened Thursday, makes  
you realize what audiences have been missing in terms of watching 
characters express their feelings through dance. 
</P>
<P>
	The concept for the show, playing at the compact Mitzi Newhouse  
Theater, couldn't be more simple. Credit Susan Stroman, director, 
choreographer and co-creator with author John Weidman, with 
devising three striking meditations on yearning -- one joyous, one 
poignant, one desperate. Dialogue is at a minimum and the emphasis 
is on dance, although the movement grows out of the people Stroman 
and Weidman have created. 
</P>
<P>
	The first and shortest piece on the triple bill is ``Swinging,''  
based on ``The Swing,'' a painting by 18th-century artist 
Jean-Honore Fragonard. A trio of players, a servant, an aristocrat 
and a girl on a swing, flirt and frolic to jazz violinist Stephane 
Grappelli's rendition of ``My Heart Stood Still.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This athletic menage a trois exudes a playful sensuality. Sean  
Martin Hingston and Scott Taylor as the amorous swains and 
Stephanie Michels, a saucy object of desire, scamper across the 
stage with alarming speed. And watch Hingston and Michels on that 
swing. Who knew that an old childhood pastime could be so erotic? 
</P>
<P>
	Gears switch dramatically in the second piece, ``Did You Move?''  
It is set in an Italian restaurant in Queens in 1954. The music 
mixes Dean Martin (``You're Nobody Till Somebody Loves You'') with 
classical compositions by Grieg, Tchaikovsky, Bizet and Puccini, 
among others. 
</P>
<P>
	An overbearing, brutish husband (Jason Antoon) and his mousy  
wife, played by the wonderful Karen Ziemba, have an uneasy dinner 
in the restaurant. He makes her meal miserable, ordering her not to 
move while he makes periodic trips to the buffet table. During 
those interludes, the wife finds an escape in reverie, including a 
dreamy romance with the headwaiter. 
</P>
<P>
	Ziemba is heartbreakingly effective as the mistreated mate. She  
is more than a fine dancer. The woman really acts. She has an open, 
trusting face and expressive eyes that make an audience root for 
her inner triumph over her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	After intermission, the title vignette takes over. It deals with  
a disillusioned Manhattan advertising executive, outwardly 
successful but emotionally dying inside. Boyd Gaines portrays the 
weary exec with appropriate anguish. 
</P>
<P>
	The man find his way to a swing club where he meets a woman in a  
yellow dress. She's played by the striking Deborah Yates. Yates, 
with the longest legs this side of Cyd Charisse, projects an 
elegant sexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Sex smolders right on the club floor, as couples dance to  
everything from Dion's ``Runaround Sue'' to Bobby Darin's version 
of ``Beyond the Sea'' to ``Sing, Sing, Sing,'' which, 
coincidentally, also is featured in ``Fosse'' and ``Dancin','' 
another Fosse show. Gaines must fight, meaning dance, to win the 
girl. 
</P>
<P>
	It's fascinating watching the actor, a nondancer, work with real  
pros. That's part of Stroman's concept. His character's halting 
connection with other human beings is finally achieved -- through 
dance. It doesn't matter that he doesn't possess their considerable 
technique. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroman knows that dance can express the most basic of emotions,  
and this ``Contact'' brings them strikingly to life. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
