<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Trooper Sues State Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A highway patrolman who opened fire on a  
van carrying four men is suing the State Police, claiming they knew 
better than to put him back on the beat after he was attacked by a 
motorist in an earlier incident. 
</P>
<P>
	The fear and trauma from the attack made him ``a risk to himself  
and to others,'' James Kenna said in his answer to a civil rights 
lawsuit filed by the van's driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenna also has filed his own injury lawsuit seeking unspecified  
damages from the State Police. 
</P>
<P>
	The Attorney General's office released a copy of the lawsuit  
Thursday. Office spokesman Roger Shatzkin and Kenna's lawyer, Jack 
Arseneault, would not comment. Kenna has routinely declined 
requests for interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	In the lawsuit, Kenna says he was traumatized March 18, 1998,  
when a man he had pulled over knocked him to the ground, jumped 
into his patrol car and nearly ran him over as he fled. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenna was sent to the State Police's Employee Assistance Program  
for psychological counseling, then returned to duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the severe psychological trauma he had suffered  
following the above incident, Kenna was recommended by these 
representatives as fit to return to duty,'' his lawsuit contends. 
</P>
<P>
	The staff ``knew or should have known that Kenna's condition  
created a risk of harm to himself or others,'' the suit states. 
</P>
<P>
	One month after the attack, on April 23, 1998, Kenna and Trooper  
John Hogan stopped the van driven by Keshon Moore. During the stop, 
three passengers, all minorities, were shot. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers said they fired because they thought the van was  
backing up to hit them. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were indicted last month on charges of attempted murder and  
are suspended without pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
