<DOCNO> APW19991007.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed May Revise Disclosure Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve, worried that its new  
disclosure policy is confusing financial markets, announced 
Thursday that Chairman Alan Greenspan had set up a working group to 
recommend improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed stressed that the working group, to be chaired by Fed  
Vice Chairman Roger Ferguson, did not signal a retreat from its new 
policy but was merely an effort to refine it to eliminate 
confusion. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the Fed began immediately announcing changes in its  
policy directive, which signals where interest rates may be headed 
in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel to examine that procedure will be made of Fed  
insiders: three board members and three regional bank presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Open Market Committee -- the officials who meet eight  
times a year to set interest rates -- has since 1994 announced 
immediately after their closed-door talks any actual changes made 
in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	But the panel also votes on a policy directive, which it sets at  
neutral or biased either toward raising rates or lowering rates. 
Those directives were always disclosed only after the next FOMC 
meeting, six to eight weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, the Fed changed its operating procedures to allow  
for the immediate disclosure of any ``significant'' changes in the 
policy directive. In May, for the first time, it announced it had 
changed the directive from neutral to one leaning toward an 
increase in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At the next meeting, June 30, the Fed followed through and  
raised interest rates for the first time in two years, pushing the 
federal funds rate up by a quarter-point to 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FOMC that day also moved its policy directive back to  
neutral, an announcement that triggered a big rally in stocks and 
bonds as investors believed it meant the central bank might stop 
with just one rate increase. Those hopes were dashed when the Fed 
raised rates for a second time at the Aug. 24 meeting. This week, 
the Fed left rates unchanged but said it had moved the policy 
directive back to one leaning toward raising rates, an announcement 
that triggered an abrupt sell-off in the bond market as investors 
began to fear a November rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists said investors have been reading too much into  
policy directives, given that a bias toward either raising rates or 
lowering them often doesn't translate into actual rate changes at 
later meetings. But they said the trend to more openness is a good 
thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Free market economists generally prefer openness and  
transparency because it produces small corrections along the way 
rather than one gigantic correction,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief 
economist at Wells Fargo in Minneapolis. ``I can't imagine any 
market participant who would want to go back to the old days when 
the Fed was communicating in sign language.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until Greenspan championed a push for more openness in 1994, the  
Fed did not announce changes in the federal funds rate, its key 
instrument for controlling the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Fed watchers were forced to divine the central bank's  
intentions on interest rates from watching its operations through 
the New York Fed in buying and selling government securities, a 
procedure that sometimes led to misreadings of Fed actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed minutes released Thursday said that Greenspan formed the  
working group because Fed officials were concerned that the 
directives were ``subject to differing interpretations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The minutes released Thursday showed that Robert McTeer,  
president of the Federal Reserve regional bank in Dallas, was the 
lone dissenter against both the June 30 and the Aug. 24 rate 
increases. They show he gave the same reason for both dissents: a 
view that inflation remained low and that productivity gains would 
continue to dampen the effect of higher wages on unit labor costs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:40:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Airlines Slashes Commissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines, the nation's largest air  
carrier, announced Thursday it is slashing the commission it pays 
travel agents for selling tickets from 8 percent to 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agents denounced United's move -- which takes effect early  
Friday and applies to both domestic and international tickets -- as 
being anti-consumer. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's rising at United is the price the consumer will  
ultimately pay for the airline ticket,'' said Joe Galloway, 
president of the American Society of Travel Agents in Alexandria, 
Va. United said it will pay agents a 5 percent commission for all 
tickets purchased in the United States for travel within the 
country, with a maximum payout of $50 for round-trip travel and $25 
for one-way travel. 
</P>
<P>
	For international travel, the maximum pay out will be $100 for  
round-trip travel and $50 for one-way travel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's announcement is part of our continuing efforts to  
examine all facets of our cost structure,'' United Airlines 
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Jim Goodwin said in a 
statement. ``We expect this action to result in savings of 
approximately $150 million annually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other airlines did not immediately respond to United's  
announcement. But in three of the previous commission cuts, United 
has led the way and all the other airlines eventually followed 
suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Led by United, the major airlines last November capped  
commission payments on all international flights at 8 percent or 
$100 a round trip. Delta went further, announcing it will pay only 
5 percent up to a maximum of $10 for a booking over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	United also led the move in 1997 to cut commission rates for  
domestic tickets to 8 percent from 10 percent, with a $50 cap for a 
round-trip fare. The move was quickly matched by other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agents sell about 80 percent of the airline tickets sold  
in the country, Galloway said. It is obvious United wants that to 
change, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``United is trying to force the cost of distribution onto the  
shoulders of consumers,'' he said. ``Consumers will be forced to 
pay more because they won't have adequate comparative information 
that travel agents alone provide or they will have to pay more 
because the travel agent will be forced to charge more or raise 
service fees for crucial services that consumers seek from them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galloway said there is no way to know what effect the cuts will  
have on individual travel agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	However, William Gallagher of Gallagher Travel Service Inc. in  
Chicago said it is likely that travel agents will charge fees for 
services they previously provided for free. 
</P>
<P>
	``For example, you call asking for the lowest fare from 'A' to  
'B,' that will cost you X number of dollars,'' he said. ``We 
haven't charged a fee in the past. There is no question we will 
have to now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to an ASTA survey taken last year, 64 percent of  
member agencies are charging some type of fee for services such as 
issuing refunds, canceling trips and sending faxes to customers. 
The average fee for a service is about $10. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher said the new commission level makes commercial travel  
planning unprofitable and means his agency will emphasize leisure 
travel. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted travel agents can get commissions from tour operators,  
rental car agencies and hotels. He said it is likely those segments 
of the travel industry will follow United's lead and cut 
commissions. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 00:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wrestler ``The Droz'' Hurt in Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- World Wrestling Federation star Darren  
Drozdov is recovering from surgery after being paralyzed below the 
waist from a neck fracture during a match. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident at the Nassau Coliseum on Tuesday is the second  
professional wrestling tragedy in five months. 
</P>
<P>
	The tattooed, body-pierced wrestler known as ``The Droz,''  
underwent three hours of surgery Wednesday to relieve pressure on 
his damaged neck, said orthopedic surgeon Dr. Laurence Mermelstein 
of the Nassau County Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's way too early to say whether or not he'll regain use of  
his legs,'' Mermelstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drozdov, 30, of Mays Landing, N.J., suffered two dislocated and  
fractured discs while wrestling against D'Lo Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the loss of feeling in his legs, Drozdov was in good  
spirits when he arrived at the hospital, Mermelstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgeons removed a piece of Drozdov's pelvis to replace the  
injured discs. They also attached a plate and screws to the area in 
an effort to stabilize his neck, the doctor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 270-pound wrestler was given the same steroid  
medication as New York Jets defensive end Dennis Byrd and Chinese 
gymnast Sang Lan when they suffered spinal cord injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd later regained use of his legs. Lan was paralyzed from the  
chest down in an accident -- also at the Nassau Coliseum -- during 
the 1998 Goodwill Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Drozdov's injury came just five months after the WWF suffered an  
in-ring fatality. 
</P>
<P>
	Wrestler Owen Hart, 34, known professionally as the Blue Blazer,  
died May 23 during a live pay-per-view event when he fell from the 
ceiling of the Kemper Arena in Kansas City, Mo. His family has 
since sued the WWF and its owner, Vince McMahon, for wrongful 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	The WWF had no immediate comment Wednesday on Drozdov's  
accident. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
