<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Set To Offer Farm Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Targeting an increasingly sour farm  
economy in a key political state, Democratic presidential candidate 
Bill Bradley is offering a $5.5 billion aid package that would 
restore direct payments to farmers when prices fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The emergency payments would be temporary and limited to avoid  
big checks going to absentee landlords, but the package would 
return a ``safety net'' to farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bradley also calls for sharply increasing the  
number of environmentally fragile acres taken out of production, 
increases in farm research programs and a ``rigorous review'' of 
concentration of ownership in the meat industry. 
</P>
<P>
	To accomplish that review, Bradley would shift responsibility  
for monitoring the industry from the Agriculture Department to the 
Department of Justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley plans to outline the proposals during a speech today on  
a farm near Des Moines. Details of the package were made available 
to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal will be unveiled at a time when the sour farm  
economy is getting increasing attention. Commodity prices have 
fallen to historic lows, and current farm policy phases out most 
traditional subsidy payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley calls for an ``income stabilization program'' that would  
provide temporary payments to farmers when prices fall. Payments 
would be triggered by a formula linking commodity process 
production costs for items such as fertilizer and seed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The payments would also be capped to ensure that the bulk of  
the benefits go to small, independent producers and their 
families,'' said background documents describing the package. It 
also would require farmers to actually work the land. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley calls for spending $5.5 billion on that effort, with  
some of the money redirected from other farm spending. The package 
sets new spending at $1.32 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wants to expand a program known as the Conservation  
Reserve Program, which pays farmers to take environmentally 
sensitive land out of production. His goal is to have 42 million 
acres idle at a cost of $580 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Another piece of the plan calls for payments to farmers to  
reward them for using environmentally friendly farming techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Bradley would spend $1.25 billion on conservation  
programs. That appeals to farmers, because of extra farm spending, 
and environmentalists worried about increasing chemical use and 
soil erosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shifting oversight of the industry to the Justice Department  
would cost $7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the plan calls for meatpackers to be forced to  
disclose what they pay for animals. Some critics argue that 
meatpackers cut special deals with giant producers to pay them 
better prices than smaller, family farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Another $60 million piece of the program would bolster farm  
research and create new rural economic development programs ``that 
help farmers develop their communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also pledged to support farm-owned cooperatives ``to give  
producers the opportunity to move closer to the consumer.'' That is 
part of an effort to encourage commodity processing, adding value 
to raw commodities and boosting farm income. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley does not mention ethanol in the package, an issue he  
previously has had difficulty with. Ethanol is very popular in Iowa 
because it's distilled from corn. Backers say an ethanol-gasoline 
blend is more environmentally friendly than other chemicals meant 
to reduce emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley opposed tax breaks for ethanol as a U.S. senator, but  
says he's changed his mind as a presidential candidate and now 
supports the breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	His speech opens a hectic political weekend in which he and his  
rival, Vice President Al Gore are to attend the Iowa Democratic 
Party's biggest annual fund-raiser Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls have shown Gore -- who has issued his own package of farm  
proposals -- with an edge in the state where precinct caucuses 
launch the nominating season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
