<DOCNO> APW19991007.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 08:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Klein Seeks Partner in Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Provocative American designer Calvin Klein is  
shopping for a buyer or partner for his New York-based fashion 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching this year's bidding wars over Gucci, Fendi and  
other designers, Calvin Klein decided to steal some of the 
spotlight and hired an investment bank to line up a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein wants to expand his $2.5 billion empire's line of  
accessories, menswear, active sportswear and home furnishings. The 
privately owned company also wants to open more retail stores -- a 
move that will relax the grip department stores have on the 
56-year-old designer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Calvin, by hooking up with a deep-pocketed partner, gets the  
infrastructure to grow the business in both venues -- retail stores 
and accessories,'' said Edward Nardoza, editor-in-chief of Women's 
Wear Daily, a trade publication which reported Calvin Klein's plans 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Klein issued a statement Wednesday saying it had hired  
Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. to explore ``strategic courses of action that 
the company may pursue in order to further develop and grow the 
business ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	Executives declined to comment further.  
</P>
<P>
	Some of the most prestigious names on the catwalks have changed  
hands this year, including Gucci, Valentino and Jil Sander. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, Gucci is jousting with Prada Holdings Ltd. and LVMH  
Moet-Hennessy Louis Vuitton for control of the Italian house of 
Fendi, which makes the hot-selling baguette handbag. 
</P>
<P>
	The bidding wars have escalated to couture prices. That should  
help Calvin Klein, which has one of the most widely recognized 
brands in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the feeding frenzy here, we have definitely gotten the  
sense these guys will be able to command a very nice price,'' said 
Faye Landes, an analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Klein, the designer, own 43 percent of his company. Barry  
Schwartz, the firm's chairman and chief executive, and Klein's 
childhood friend from the New York City borough of the Bronx, also 
owns 43 percent. The rest is held by family trusts. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the most likely buyers are European firms, such as LVMH,  
Prada, HdP, and Pinault-Printemps-Redoute. Other potential suitors 
include Warnaco, which owns the license for Calvin Klein jeans and 
underwear, and Unilever, the Dutch-Anglo consumer products giant 
that holds the license for Calvin Klein's Obsession and other 
fragrances. 
</P>
<P>
	The consolidation trend started with the department stores,  
which have snapped up competitors and closed extra stores to prop 
up profit margins. The department stores then used their bargaining 
power to drive hard bargains with vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	To survive, fashion houses have expanded overseas, found new  
niches and opened their own stores. But that takes money. 
</P>
<P>
	While several designers raised money in the early 1990s by  
selling stock to the public, their shares have run hot and cold, 
like sales of capri pants and bell bottoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Klein is not looking to go public, according to a person  
familiar with the company's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are always peaks and valleys in the fashion industry,''  
said Susan Silverstein, an analyst at Banc of America Securities. 
``But the more diversified a company is the less risky that fashion 
element becomes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Klein, like many designers today, wants to broaden its  
reach by putting its name on sheets and towels, running shoes, 
luggage and jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to see more consolidation and mergers and  
partnerships between brands and companies,'' Silverstein said. 
``It's what I call cross-dressing in the fashion industry.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991007.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 06:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
