<DOCNO> APW19991007.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Shares Close Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Wall Street's gains overnight boosted Japanese  
share prices Thursday. The dollar was higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 240.13  
points, or 1.34 percent, to close at 18,136.55 on Thursday. The 
average closed up 112.27 points, or 0.63 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei closed up for the sixth consecutive day.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 107.84 yen on the Tokyo foreign  
exchange market Thursday, up 0.48 yen from late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo stock market also gained on growing optimism about  
Japan's economic outlook, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is pretty strong. The outlook for the Japanese  
economy is bright,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, general manager of the 
stock division at Chuo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is struggling to emerge from its worst economic downturn  
in 50 years. Recent positive signs -- such as two straight quarters 
of economic growth -- have fueled optimism that the worst is over. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average gained 187.75  
points, or 1.8 percent, to close Wednesday's session at 10,588.34. 
Stocks rose on a rebounding bond market and optimism about 
corporate earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 12.51 points, or 0.83 percent, to 1,525.04. The 
TOPIX closed up 2.47 points, or 0.16 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the Nikkei's gains didn't stop investors  
from selling yen to buy dollars. Usually, investors buy yen when 
Japanese share prices rise, so they can buy into the rising market. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese investors, particularly pension and trust funds, bought  
dollars Thursday for investment in dollar-denominated assets, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overseas investors now realize that their purchases of yen for  
investing into Japanese stocks will, in the end, lead to a fall of 
the Nikkei because of a yen rise,'' said Minoru Shioiri, assistant 
manager of foreign exchange at Nippon Credit Bank. ``The link 
between dollar/yen rates and the Nikkei Average is now gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese authorities fear that too strong a yen could hamper the  
economic recovery. A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more 
expensive overseas and could hurt corporate earnings if sales 
suffer as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback also benefited from pro-dollar comments by  
government officials, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's vice finance minister for international affairs,  
Haruhiko Kuroda, said Thursday that recent yen strengthening has 
eased somewhat. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 115.48 yen at midday, up  
from 115.28 yen late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7200 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6950 percent. Its 
price fell 0.22 points to 99.82. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
