<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Imperils Truck Safety Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A spending bill awaiting President Clinton's  
signature would effectively bar the Transportation Department from 
imposing fines on truckers violating safety regulations, the 
department's general counsel told a House hearing today. 
</P>
<P>
	If the $50 billion fiscal 2000 transportation spending bill  
becomes law, said Nancy McFadden, safety officials ``will not be 
able to pursue a violation by initiating a civil penalty action or 
seeking an injunction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our enforcement efforts would be severely hampered by this  
legislation,'' she told the House ground transportation 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	A provision in the bill bars the Office of Motor Carriers and  
its parent agency, the Federal Highway Administration, from 
spending money to enforce certain truck safety regulations. If 
Clinton, as expected, signs the bill, the OMC spending ban could 
run counter to existing law giving the federal highway 
administrator sole authority to assess civil penalties for 
violations of motor safety regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lives of the driving public will be placed in serious  
jeopardy,'' with the bill, said Rep. Nick Rahall of West Virginia, 
ranking Democrat on the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible remedies to the problem, lawmakers said, are either to  
have the president veto the bill so it can be amended or pass new 
legislation redelegating penalty assessment authority. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an emergency, a serious problem and we've got to deal  
with it,'' said Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the 
Transportation Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	McFadden said even with the new law the department would still  
be able to issue rules, operate programs relating to motor carrier 
safety, conduct border inspections and conduct safety compliance 
reviews of bus and trucking companies. It would also be able to put 
out of service carriers that pose an immediate safety hazard. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the department is studying whether to move OMC  
staffers and their duties to a new agency or an existing office in 
the department. 
</P>
<P>
	OMC head Julie Anna Cirillo, in a memo to staff members Monday,  
said they would be transferred en masse to the new organizational 
unit while members of the enforcement teams will be reassigned to 
other duties. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision was inserted into the spending bill by OMC critics  
who want to move truck safety functions to a different agency. They 
contend the office has been too close to the trucking industry, 
impeding regulators' ability to address the problem of 
truck-related traffic accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 5,300 people are killed each year in accidents involving  
trucks, and the administration has pledged to cut that number in 
half. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
