<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Filed Against Papers Thief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New federal charges have been filed against a  
man convicted of stealing papers signed by Thomas Edison, Thomas 
Jefferson and others for allegedly trying to sell more documents to 
an antiques dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI complaint said Daniel Spiegelman of New York contacted a  
Greenwich, Conn., store last Friday and tried to sell stolen 
manuscripts and letters worth about $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Items signed by five presidents -- Jefferson, James Monroe,  
Andrew Jackson, James Polk and John Quincy Adams -- were offered 
along with scientific papers of Edison and a rare manuscript, all 
stolen from Columbia University, according to the complaint filed 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in Greenwich charged Spiegelman last week after the owner  
of Alexander Autographs Inc. in Greenwich said a man identifying 
himself as Andrew Osharksy had offered items that he recognized to 
be part of the stolen Columbia collection, authorities said. 
Prosecutors said Osharksy is an alias used by Spiegelman. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal charges against Spiegelman allege that he illegally  
transported stolen documents across state lines for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Fallick, a lawyer for Spiegelman, declined to comment  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Spiegelman was sentenced to five years in prison in July 1998  
after he was convicted of stealing $1.3 million worth of historical 
documents from Columbia University's Rare Collection Library in 
1994. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
