<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Employees at Paris Airports Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Many ground personnel at the two main Paris  
airports went on strike today to highlight their demands during 
talks under way with management over implementing a 35-hour 
workweek. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike did not concern pilots and flight attendants. It  
slowed air traffic and closed off one of two runways at Orly 
airport and one of three runways at Charles de Gaulle airport 
today, causing delays of up to one hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Both runways were operational by the afternoon, said Isabelle de  
Villaneuve, a spokeswoman for the Airports of Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how many employees participated in the strike,  
waged as employees and management are in talks about instituting 
the 35-hour workweek, a plan proposed by France's leftist 
government coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies have some flexibility in deciding how adopt the  
project. The Paris airports have proposed that employees take more 
time off during slow seasons, rather than spreading the downtime 
over each week, but some unions have expressed concern over this 
and other measures, Villaneuve said. 
</P>
<P>
	The employees have many, often seemingly minute demands, over  
retirement and flexibility, among others. They complain that 
management is not listening to their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	By Jan. 1, 2000, companies with more than 20 employees will be  
required by law to implement the 35-hour workweek. The government 
passed a law last year that encourages companies to sign on to the 
plan ahead of schedule by giving them tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's leftist government hopes that  
reducing working hours will force companies to hire more employees 
to maintain the same level of productivity, and help reduce 
unemployment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
