<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings 7, Thrashers 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Steve Yzerman scored his first goal of the season  
to ignite a three-goal first period Thursday night and the Detroit 
Red Wings went on to a 7-1 victory over the expansion Atlanta 
Thrashers. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second NHL game for the Thrashers, who lost in their  
debut on Saturday 4-1 to New Jersey at Philips Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Yzerman also had a pair of assists as the Red Wings won for the  
second time in three starts. 
</P>
<P>
	In the opening period, Yzerman scored Detroit's first goal and  
got an assist on the second one by Igor Larionov. Vyacheslav Kozlov 
scored the third goal with Larionov getting an assist on that one. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers averted a shutout when Petr Buzek beat Detroit  
goaltender Chris Osgood on a 30-foot slap shot 2:23 into the final 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, however, broke it by scoring three goals in 3:33  
for a 6-1 lead before a sellout crowd of 18,535. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Duchesne scored at the 5:23 mark, Yzerman assisting.  
Sergei Fedorov followed with another goal only 56 seconds later for 
a 5-1 lead. Tomas Holmstrom, who assisted on Fedorov's goal, 
knocked in a 15-foot slap shot after 8:56 and Doug Brown, with an 
assist from Holmstrom, made it 7-1 with a goal with 1:08 left. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings (2-1) peppered Thrashers goaltender Norm Maracle  
for a dozen shots in the opening period with Yzerman, who has led 
Detroit in scoring 10 times in his 16 NHL seasons, beating the 
former Red Wings goalie from in close after only 6:50. 
</P>
<P>
	Maracle, taken by the Thrashers in the June expansion draft, had  
played in 20 games for Detroit during the previous two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Larionov made it 2-0 at 11:56 by knocking one past Maracle from  
just to the side of the net with Yzerman and Larry Murphy getting 
assists. Kozlov closed out the first period scoring with a rebound 
goal after 15:38. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Wings forward Darren McCarty, ended his holdout earlier in  
the day by signing a three-year, $5.4 million deal. He was in 
uniform and played sparingly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
