<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Barely Changed / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bond markets barely moved Thursday as  
traders awaited a government report on employment as they looked 
for clues on the course of interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dipped 3/32  
point, or 94 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.18 from 6.17 percent 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders essentially sat still preparing for Friday's release of  
September's figures on employment and hourly wages, a key inflation 
indicator. 
</P>
<P>
	With labor markets already tight, another big increase in the  
number of jobholders can drive up wages, something that adds 
pressure on consumer prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say Friday's figures could provide a general sense of  
whether the Federal Reserve will increase interest rates for a 
third time this year when policy-makers next meet on Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting Tuesday, the Fed left rates unchanged, but said it  
was watching for signs of rekindled inflation and ready to increase 
rates to cool off the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were either unchanged or rose 1/32 point, while intermediate 
maturities ranged from no change to a decline of 1/32 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the yield on three-month Treasury was 4.83  
percent, as the discount rose 0.04 point from Thursday to 4.70 
percent. The six-month yield was 5.11 percent as the discount rose 
0.05 percentage point to 4.91 percent. The one-year yield rose to 
5.32 percent, and the discount rose 0.01 to 5.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay at maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.31 percent from 5.19 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 to 111 9/32. The average yield to 
maturity of the index was 5.95 percent, up from 5.94 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
