<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cincinnati Gun Lawsuit Cismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- An Ohio state judge today dismissed the city's  
lawsuit against gun manufacturers, a distributor and three trade 
associations on the grounds that it was vague and unsupported by 
legal precedent. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other cities across the country also have sued the  
firearms industry. Today's action was the first dismissal of such a 
suit, a lawyer for gun manufacturers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Dorr, a Chicago lawyer for gun makers Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co.  
Inc., of Southport, Conn., and Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., of 
Springfield, Mass., said he hopes to use the ruling by Hamilton 
County Common Pleas Judge Robert Ruehlman in seeking the dismissal 
of 17 similar lawsuits representing 27 city or county governments. 
</P>
<P>
	Those lawsuits are pending in state or federal courts around the  
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``These lawsuits filed by the cities have been, in our opinion,  
nothing but smoke and mirrors with no legal foundation to them,'' 
Dorr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruehlman became the first judge to dismiss any of the lawsuits,  
Dorr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati had demanded reimbursement for the costs of providing  
police, emergency, court and prison services in connection with 
shootings in the city, regardless of whether those shootings were 
homicidal, suicidal or accidental. 
</P>
<P>
	The city also sought damages for alleged reduction of property  
values and loss of taxpayer revenues, plus court orders that would 
force the defendants to change the way they design, distribute and 
advertise their products nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the Legislature, not the courts, has the authority to  
impose that type of regulation, the judge ruled. Ruehlman rejected 
other claims by Cincinnati as vague or not supported by laws or 
precedent in court cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley M. Chesley, Cincinnati's lawyer, said he expects to  
appeal within the next few days to the 1st Ohio District Court of 
Appeals in Cincinnati. The judge's ruling was premature because the 
city had not been allowed to review documents from the defendants, 
Chesley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants in Cincinnati's lawsuit are Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co.; Smith  
&AMP; Wesson; Beretta U.S.A. Corp.; Bryco Arms Inc.; Colt's 
Manufacturing Co. Inc.; H &AMP; R 1871 Inc.; Hi-Point Firearms; Lorcin 
Engineering Co. Inc.; North Americans Arms Inc.; Phoenix Arms; 
Taurus International Manufacturing Inc., Fabrica D'Armi, Pietro 
Beretta S.P.A. and B.L. Jennings Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati's claims included alleged design defects in firearms  
and alleged failure to warn users of possible risks from use of 
firearms. The judge rejected those. 
</P>
<P>
	``There can be liability for failure to warn only if the risk is  
not open and obvious or a matter of common knowledge. The court 
finds as a matter of law that the risks associated with the use of 
a firearm are open and obvious and matters of common knowledge,'' 
Ruehlman wrote in his five-page ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The city's claim of liability for defective firearm designs  
failed to meet a requirement under Ohio law of identifying specific 
products or specific injuries and their causes, the judge ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruehlman said he ruled on the basis of written filings and  
lawyers' arguments he heard on Sept. 27. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
