<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Teritories Dispute Y2K Findings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A U.S. report singling out Puerto  
Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands for not dealing with the Year 2000 
computer bug is too pessimistic, officials from both territories 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are at the average level,'' insisted Sen. Kenneth  
McClintock, who has led a two-year effort to prepare government 
computers in Puerto Rico. ``About half of the states are doing 
better than us and half are doing worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office reported Wednesday that Puerto  
Rico runs a ``high risk'' of errors in its Medicaid-backed health 
care system on Jan. 1, 2000. More than 1.6 million people on this 
island of 3.8 million people receive free medical care from the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nearby U.S. Virgin Islands, the GAO said computers  
running Medicaid, food assistance and child support programs were 
at high risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The Year 2000 bug is a glitch that causes older computers to  
mistake 2000 for 1900 because they use only ``00'' to designate the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in both U.S. territories said that in many cases, they  
started ``de-bugging'' their computers late because of budget 
constraints. But they believe they can catch up within a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have full confidence that the system will carry us through  
January,'' said Priscilla Berry-Quetel, director of Medicaid funds 
in the Virgin Islands Department of Health. ``If the system doesn't 
work, we will revert to a manual system, which we have done after 
hurricanes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Work on the Virgin Islands' food stamp program started late, in  
October 1998, because of contract problems, but also should be 
finished by November, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico's $1.25 billion health program finished rewriting  
its computer codes in July and began a final round of tests last 
week, said Orlando Colon, Y2K Officer for the Health Insurance 
Administration. The agency's contractor, Computer Aid Inc., should 
have the computers ready by November, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
