<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Mad Max' Brings His Act To Seattle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Gary Payton has been after the Seattle  
SuperSonics for years to sign his good friend, Vernon Maxwell. 
Well, ``Mad Max'' is finally here. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics -- and Maxwell himself -- say this is a more mature  
Maxwell than the player who's had problems with money, marijuana 
and fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't done anything the last six, seven years,'' Maxwell  
said after the Sonics' training camp practice Thursday. ``I feel 
like I've matured and the past is the past. I just look forward to 
the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maxwell, 34, has kept himself in tremendous shape in his 11  
seasons in the NBA. He's also kept himself in the news. 
</P>
<P>
	It should be an interesting season in Seattle, where Maxwell is  
playing for his seventh NBA franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics signed Maxwell to a three-year contract after falling  
short in their bid to get Mitch Richmond. Maxwell probably won't 
start, but he's likely to get a lot of minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``A great, pleasant surprise for us have been his leadership  
qualities,'' said team president and general manager Wally Walker, 
who brought Maxwell to the Sonics at the request of Payton. ``The 
guys respect him and he really goes out of the way to encourage the 
younger players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said coach Paul Westphal: ``From what I've seen so far, it's as  
easy as it gets. He's a veteran, he's a very encouraging teammate, 
he knows the game and he plays very hard. You don't have to tell 
Vernon much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hot-and-cold shooting guard has been known as ``Mad Max''  
for his behavior both on and off the court. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, Maxwell filed for bankruptcy protection in  
federal court in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	His bankruptcy petition indicated his affinity for fancy cars  
had left him strapped. His two biggest creditors were the lenders 
who financed a Ferrari and an auto leasing company in Philadelphia, 
where he played in 1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in 1998, Maxwell served a 90-day jail sentence for a 1995  
marijuana conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1995, he rushed into the stands in Portland and  
punched a fan, for which he was suspended 10 games and fined 
$20,000. No evidence was found to back Maxwell's claim that the 
35-year-old man used racial slurs and taunted his family. Maxwell 
subsequently settled out of court with the fan. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxwell arrives in Seattle with 10,198 points in 765 career  
games, including 51 in a game for the Houston Rockets against 
Cleveland in January 1991. In Sacramento last season, he helped the 
Kings make the playoffs, averaging 10.7 points in 46 games. In the 
Kings' first-round playoff loss to Utah, Maxwell scored 22 points 
in one game. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seattle, Payton hopes Maxwell can help him get back to the  
playoffs. The Sonics failed to get there in the lockout-abbreviated 
1998-99 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed somebody in the backcourt who is going to do the same  
things I do,'' Payton said. ``We're going to get in people's faces. 
We're not going to back down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton and Maxwell both play with a lot of emotion. They've been  
friends since Payton came into the league in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always wanted to play with a guy with the same kind of  
temperament as me,'' Maxwell said. ``I'm looking forward to it. I 
know him real well and he knows me real well. We've always hung out 
in the summertime together. We're a lot like brothers. I think in a 
lot of aspects in life we're alike, except the money. He makes a 
lot more money than I do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
