<DOCNO> APW19991007.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 00:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Challenges on Soft Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain is looking to his Republican  
presidential rivals for help in winning Senate passage of his 
legislation to ban unlimited ``soft money'' donations to the 
political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is scheduled to take up the issue next week.  
</P>
<P>
	McCain said in a speech Wednesday that he did not know whether  
he had the 60 votes that would be needed to end debate and bring 
the measure to a final vote. 
</P>
<P>
	He has sent letters to most of his competitors asking for their  
support, including a special appeal for help to the GOP 
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``If even half of the members of Congress who endorsed your  
candidacy were to honor your request, (the soft money ban) would 
pass with votes to spare,'' the Arizona senator wrote to Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The response from the Bush camp was cool.  
</P>
<P>
	``Like thousands of other Americans who write to us, we're glad  
he recognizes Governor Bush's leadership and ability to lead,'' 
Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said, declining to elaborate on 
whether Bush would support McCain's bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush believes individuals should be able to make unlimited  
donations to political parties but corporations and unions should 
not, ``because shareholders and union members don't have any say in 
how that money is spent,'' Tucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	The soft money ban offered by McCain and Sen. Russ Feingold,  
D-Wis., is a stripped-down version of campaign finance legislation 
killed in the Senate last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Soft money originally was used by political parties for  
party-building and get-out-the-vote efforts but is increasingly 
used for ``issue advertising'' designed to influence the outcome of 
an election. McCain says soft money has become a way for 
corporations and unions to get around bans on direct donations to 
candidates and for individuals to circumvent the $1,000 
contribution cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Warming up for next week's debate, McCain wrote to five GOP  
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need all the help we can get,'' he told the Committee for  
Economic Development, a business group that supports the bill. ``If 
they say they are for campaign finance reform, which they have 
stated publicly, I would hope that they would weigh in on the 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he did not send letters to Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, who  
opposes the plan, and Patrick Buchanan, who McCain said has 
``already left the Republican Party'' by questioning U.S. 
involvement in World War II. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
