<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Swings for New Jersey GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEWATER, N.J. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate  
George W. Bush joked that his reception at a local ballpark was ``a 
little warmer'' than one the Texas Rangers received in their 8-0 
lashing by the New York Yankees the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	About 750 New Jersey Republicans greeted Bush, a former managing  
partner of the Rangers and the GOP front-runner, at a 
$1,250-a-plate fund-raiser under a tent on the infield at Somerset 
Ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP officials expected to raise $800,000.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush praised state Assembly Republicans, pitched his credo of  
``compassionate conservatism'' and attempted to earn early points 
in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``All politics starts at the grass roots, as far as I'm  
concerned,'' he told the crowd. ``And New Jersey is an incredibly 
important state in the year 2000. I'm coming here to earn the 
support and respect of people all over your state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the governor of Texas, said New Jersey exemplifies his  
motto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe I'm looking at compassionate people who are  
conservative thinkers and I know your state is a better place for 
that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush cited Gov. Christie Whitman's effort to improve education  
standards and Republican efforts to reform welfare and cut taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman's withdrawal as a candidate for U.S. Senate next year  
immediately renewed speculation about her prospects as a possible 
vice presidential pick. Bush said it was ``far too early'' to talk 
about that, noting that he has not yet won his party's nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman has yet to endorse a candidate.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, Bush greeted well-wishers as he strolled  
around a New York City Italian food market and ate a 
pizza-and-pasta lunch with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George 
Pataki during a three-borough tour of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the market, Bush sampled food, chatted with vendors and  
called out ``Mucho gusto concerte!'' -- Spanish for ``nice to meet 
you'' -- to Marcia Hernandez, a Dominican immigrant picking up 
groceries to bring to a nearby senior center where she works. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yo tambien!'' (``Me too!'') she called back.  
</P>
<P>
	Pataki and Giuliani have a rocky personal relationship, but they  
put aside their differences to accompany Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``This Republican Party is unified,'' Bush said, standing with  
the pair during an earlier visit to a Queens job placement center 
for welfare recipients. ``Standing behind me are the pillars of the 
Republican Party in New York, people who put their minds to 
winning.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
