<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UPS Ending Some Gun Deliveries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service said today it will stop  
delivering handguns through its regular service, saying it was 
taking the step to help prevent thefts of weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Monday, Atlanta-based UPS -- which handles the vast  
majority of firearms shipments -- will ship handguns only through 
its Next Day Air service, which costs three to four times as much 
as ground service. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has become more than ever a tremendous issue of concern  
to our society,'' UPS spokesman Norman Black said. ``Society is 
concerned about these weapons falling into the wrong hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UPS' Next Day Air service is a separate, more controlled system  
where packages are handled by fewer people and stay in the system 
for only one night, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Chambers, executive director of the Sporting Arms and  
Ammunition Manufacturers' Institute, said overnight delivery costs 
about $25 more per gun, or about four times as much as ground 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we're trying to come to grips with. We're looking  
for alternative methods,'' Chambers told The Morning Call in 
Allentown, Pa., which reported the new UPS policy in a story 
published today. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will continue to ship long guns, rifles and shotguns  
by ground. Those guns are not as attractive to thieves as handguns, 
said another UPS spokesman, Robert Godlewski. 
</P>
<P>
	Godlewski acknowledged that shipping by air will be more  
expensive for gun manufacturers and dealers. But he said, ``We're 
going to err on the side of safety. If that costs more money, then 
that's the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each business day, Atlanta-based UPS delivers 12 million  
packages via its trademark brown trucks and brown-uniformed 
employees. UPS handles up to 75 percent of guns sent from 
manufacturers to distributors and nearly all firearms shipped from 
distributors to dealers, Chambers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Jannuzzo, vice president of Glock Inc., said the gun  
manufacturer will continue to ship with UPS, but the increase in 
cost will be passed on to dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too substantial to absorb,'' said Jannuzzo, who works at  
Glock's U.S. headquarters in Smyrna, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, federal investigators said 130 Glock guns being shipped  
via UPS were stolen from a series of shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it will cut out the theft problems, it will be a good  
thing,'' Jannuzzo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Black couldn't say how many guns have been stolen from the UPS  
ground system in the past. He knew of no cases where a gun stolen 
from UPS had been used in a crime and a lawsuit resulted. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, ``our attitude is that even one such instance is one too  
many, and we just had to find some way to improve the security 
around these shipments,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
