<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley To Offer $5.5B Farm Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill  
Bradley is putting together a $5.5 billion farm package designed to 
restore the rural ``safety net'' by calling for cash payments to 
farmers when commodity prices sag. 
</P>
<P>
	The package, which calls for $1.32 billion in new spending, also  
proposes sharply increasing the number of environmentally fragile 
acres taken out of production, increases in farm research programs 
and a ``rigorous review'' of concentration of ownership in the meat 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's staff huddled with Iowa State University economist  
Neil Harl late into the evening Wednesday, crafting the proposal, 
which Bradley will unveil Friday during a speech at a farm near Des 
Moines. Details were made available Thursday to The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, already  
has issued his own package of farm proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	At a time when commodity prices have fallen to historic lows and  
most traditional subsidy payments are being phased out, Bradley 
calls for an ``income stabilization program'' that would provide 
temporary payments to farmers when prices fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The payments would also be capped to ensure that the bulk of  
the benefits go to small, independent producers and their 
families,'' said background documents describing the package. It 
also would require that farmers actually work the land, avoiding 
big payments to absentee landlords. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley's package has an overall pricetag of $5.5 billion, but  
he said all but $1.32 billion would come from redirecting other 
farm spending. He would use the budget surplus to fund the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	He proposed expanding the Conservation Reserve Program so that  
farmers take 42 million acres of environmentally sensitive land out 
of production, at a cost of $580 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet another piece of his proposal would implement ``conservation  
security contracts'' which call for payments to farmers to reward 
them for using environmentally friendly farming techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Bradley would spend $1.25 billion on conservation  
programs. That appeals to farmers because of extra farm spending, 
and environmentalists worried about increasing chemical use and 
soil erosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley proposed spending $7 million as part of his effort to  
shift oversight of the livestock industry from the Agriculture 
Department to the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wants meatpackers to be forced to disclose the prices  
they pay for animals. Some critics argue that meatpackers cut 
special deals with giant producers to pay them better prices than 
smaller, family farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The package calls for spending $60 million on farm research and  
to put in place new rural economic development programs ``that help 
farmers develop their communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley does not mention ethanol in his farm package, and he's  
had difficulties with that issue in the past. Ethanol is very 
popular in Iowa because it's distilled from corn and blended with 
gasoline that backers say is more environmentally friendly. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley opposed tax breaks for ethanol as a senator, but says  
he's changed his mind and now backs the breaks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
