<HEADLINE> Japan Weighs $51B To Help Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Finance Ministry wants the government to  
spend an extra $51 billion this fiscal year to maintain the 
nation's economic recovery, published reports said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry officials made their proposal at a meeting with  
government policy makers. Members of Japan's three-party ruling 
coalition were planning to put forward their own recommendations 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	A ministry spokesman, speaking on customary condition of  
anonymity, said he was unable to confirm the proposal as it was not 
yet official. 
</P>
<P>
	A final proposal goes to Parliament for approval in November.  
Approval is likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposed outlays include $32 billion for public works projects  
and $19 billion to help small and medium-sized companies, the news 
reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be spent before Japan's fiscal year ends on  
March 31, 2000. It follows a first extra budget of about $5 billion 
approved in July as a way to create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese economy is just emerging from its worst downturn in  
decades, and the government has begun a massive spending campaign 
to keep the economy moving and get people to consume more. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of the three-way governing coalition said the  
ministry's proposed total is too small. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's got to be more,'' said Shizuka Kamei, the ruling Liberal  
Democratic Party's policy affairs chief. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two coalition members are the Liberal Party and the  
New Komeito. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
