<HEADLINE> Pan Am Coach Indicted for Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURG, Texas (AP) -- A grand jury indicted former University  
of Texas-Pan American basketball coach Delray Brooks on Thursday on 
a felony theft charge for alleged misuse of university money. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks was fired Aug. 23 because Pan American officials believed  
he deposited a check from Southwest Missouri State for $25,000 into 
his personal account and then made withdrawals from the account. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks has acknowledged that $25,000 was placed in his account,  
but has denied depositing it or telling someone else to do so. 
Brooks has an unpublished phone number and could not be reached for 
comment Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan American hired him in 1997 to restore the dignity of the  
men's basketball program after the school lost its NCAA 
certification in 1996. The certification was fully restored in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, whose salary was nearly $63,000 last season, had an 8-46  
record in his first two seasons as the Broncs' coach. 
</P>
<P>
	The school also chose not to renew the contracts of two  
assistant coaches, George Morgan and Patrick Harrington, for the 
1999-2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, the university hired Bob Hoffman, men's  
basketball coach at Oklahoma Baptist for nine seasons, as the new 
head coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, who played at Indiana and Providence, is a former  
assistant coach at Kentucky who helped the Wildcats to three Final 
Four appearances, including the 1996 national championship. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
