<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Unemployment Rate Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Unemployment in Australia edged up to  
7.4 percent last month, the government announced Thursday, but 
Prime Minister John Howard said job creation is still rising. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said the increase, from 7.2 percent in August,  
probably does not reflect any imminent weakness in the nation's 
economy, which grew by 4.1 percent in the year to the end of June. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's unemployment rate stood at 8 percent in September  
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given everything else that is happening in the economy, there  
is ample justification for an acceleration in employment growth 
from here,'' analyst Craig James of the Societe Generale bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard, who was in Port Moresby on a one-day visit to Papua New  
Guinea, said employment growth of 12,600 was recorded in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``The forward indicators are that jobs are still being generated  
at a very fast clip,'' he added. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
