<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magnate Gives $60M to Smithsonian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Billionaire aviation magnate Steven Udvar-Hazy  
has a tendency to do things in a big way, but his $60 million gift 
to the Smithsonian Institution -- the museum's largest gift ever -- 
is the biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Udvar-Hazy, a Hungarian immigrant who heads the world's largest  
aircraft leasing company, says he thought only five minutes before 
donating the money to help build a giant annex for the National Air 
and Space Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	The complex, which will cost $173 million to design and build,  
will house nearly 200 historic airplanes and spacecraft too big to 
display at the museum on the Mall downtown. When it opens in 
suburban Virginia in 2003, visitors will see, for instance, the 
69,000-pound B-29 ``Enola Gay'' that dropped the atomic bomb on 
Hiroshima, the space shuttle Enterprise and the speedy, 
needle-nosed Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, which is more than 107 feet 
long. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how to say it. We're not seeking publicity, but  
we like to do things in a major, big way,'' Udvar-Hazy said 
Thursday about his gift. ``That's just our style.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He flashed a mischievous grin under his reddish-brown mustache  
and added: ``It's a Hungarian, barbarian style.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Udvar-Hazy, 53, of Beverly Hills, Calif., looked anything but  
barbaric at a ceremony here to recognize his donation. Tanned and 
dressed in a double-breasted dark suit, stark white shirt, red tie 
and gold lapel pin in the shape of an airplane tail, Udvar-Hazy 
squinted into a shower of camera flashes and talked about the 
largest donation he's ever made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It properly mirrors my love for aviation,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Udvar-Hazy's gift virtually fell out of the sky, said  
Smithsonian Secretary I. Michael Heyman. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't really know him at all. He was referred to us by  
other folks. He fell in love with the idea after a fast visit,'' 
Heyman said. ``He goes places very rapidly and moves around very 
fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, maybe not on Thursday. Strong headwinds slowed his  
corporate jet flight to Washington, but once he arrived at the Air 
and Space Museum downtown, Udvar-Hazy -- a ``dynamic,'' 
``competitive'' man, according to his wife, Christine -- took center 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Udvar-Hazy got a standing ovation for remarks he made at a  
podium set up in front of the ``Spirit of St. Louis,'' the plane 
Charles Lindbergh flew for the first solo, nonstop flight across 
the Atlantic, and Chuck Yeager's ``Glamorous Glennis,'' a bright 
orange plane that first broke the sound barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke of growing up in Eastern Europe in the shadow of Soviet  
tanks. He talked of communist repression. Then he recalled a sunny 
spring day in 1953 when he went to an airshow just outside 
Budapest, Hungary. Udvar-Hazy, then age 7, was mesmerized by 
sunlight reflecting from the aluminum skin of a plane and vapor 
trails left in the sky by a MiG 15 Soviet fighter jet. 
</P>
<P>
	``He sees airplanes climbing into the air,'' said Udvar-Hazy,  
referring to himself in the third-person. ``There are soldiers and 
guards standing everywhere, but their importance is overshadowed by 
the sudden spirit of freedom, and the feeling that an airplane 
rising into the sky is the hope, the only way to reach into a 
bigger world, a world representing his future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a defining moment. Aviation had captured his imagination.  
He took his first flight the next year.At age 12, he and his family 
escaped Hungary, went to Sweden and later settled in New York City. 
While his friends played baseball, Udvar-Hazy watched takeoffs and 
landings at a nearby airport. While they read comic books, he 
studied airplane schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, he earned a bachelor's degree in economics from the  
University of California at Los Angeles and received his private 
pilot's license. Today, the father of four is president of 
International Lease Finance Corp., the leading commercial aircraft 
owner and lessor, which has a portfolio of more than 400 jet 
aircraft valued at more than $18 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very passionate about what he does,'' his wife said in an  
interview. ``He's the eternal optimist. If it's aviation, it's 24 
hours a day. If he's having fun, you've got to have fun to the 
final moment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
