<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Nixes Nazi Bill Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- The Polish parliament rejected opposition  
calls Thursday for a national referendum on a bill to compensate 
owners of property seized during Nazi and communist times. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sign of progress on the measure, which has been delayed  
since the country toppled communist rule in 1989, parliament sent 
it to a special committee. The committee must review the bill and 
return it to the lower chamber for consideration. It will also 
require approval of the Senate and President Aleksander 
Kwasniewski. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft was approved by a vote of 224 to 170.  
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, intended to deal with a painful legacy of  
Poland's past, has been delayed since the country toppled communist 
rule in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous governments argued that democratic and free-market  
reforms were more important priorities than satisfying Poles whose 
property was taken over by the Nazis during World War II or 
nationalized during the communist regime that followed. 
</P>
<P>
	The rightist-dominated Parliament, which began debating the bill  
Wednesday, rejected opposition demands to put it to a national vote 
and sharply limit the amount of compensation to be offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition leaders contend the measure will be too costly and  
undermine efforts to complete needed social and economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, prepared by the Solidarity-led government of Prime  
Minister Jerzy Buzek, would offer 50 percent compensation to 
people, including Jews, whose property was seized between 1939 and 
1962. 
</P>
<P>
	The government wants to pay compensation in bonds or return half  
of the seized property, if it still exists and has no new private 
owner. The law would not apply to national parks and monuments. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the communist regime seized farms and factories across  
the country, as well as all of central Warsaw, some predict that 
Poland could face as many as 170,000 claims from 2.5 million 
people, totaling $27 billion to $32 billion. That is about the 
equivalent of Poland's annual government budget. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
