<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mullin To Come Off Bench This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- Age is catching up to Chris  
Mullin. 
</P>
<P>
	A starter most of his 14-year NBA career and a five-time  
All-Star, Mullin will come off the bench this season as the Indiana 
Pacers go with youth. 
</P>
<P>
	Mullin, 36, a teammate with Bird on the 1992 U.S. Olympic  
``Dream Team,'' was acquired in a trade with Golden State in 1997 
and started at small forward for the Pacers the past two years. 
Coach Larry Bird hasn't decided who will start in Mullin's place, 
although the frontrunner appears to be Jalen Rose, the top scorer 
off the bench last season at 11.1 points a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Others competing for playing time at small forward include  
Austin Croshere, the Pacers' top draft pick in 1997, and Al 
Harrington, who was drafted out of high school in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the same Chris,'' Bird said. ``He hits his shots and he  
never makes a mistake. He's awesome. But he knows it's time for a 
change, and we're happy he's going along with it because we need to 
look at these younger players, too.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
