<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Fund Raising Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Local politicians are asking the IRS to  
investigate whether the Mormon Church is breaking the law by urging 
members to support a California initiative banning gay marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	The push by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints  
encouraging Mormons to donate time and money has helped give the 
March 2000 ballot measure a 4-1 cash advantage over its opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Initiative supporters have raised about $840,000 as of June 30,  
though it's unclear how much of that came from Mormon donors. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco supervisors see the church's involvement as an  
abuse of its tax-exempt status. IRS rules prohibit religious 
organizations from engaging in ``substantial'' political activity 
without endangering that status. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to have a fair and honest debate,'' Supervisor Mark  
Leno said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that can't happen if large sums of tax-deductible  
dollars are allowed to ``completely overrun the entire ballot 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Nonsense,'' said church spokesman Michael Otterson.  
</P>
<P>
	The Mormons aren't the only religious group supporting the  
initiative and tax laws apply equally to them all, Otterson said. 
</P>
<P>
	IRS spokesman Larry Wright said he could not comment on whether  
the agency has agreed to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mormon Church mounted similar campaigns last year in Hawaii  
and Alaska that helped pass measures banning gays and lesbians from 
marrying. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hawaii, the money funded television ads that ``preyed on the  
most insidious emotions,'' said David Smith, who oversaw the failed 
campaign to defeat the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, three Mormon Church presidents asked California church  
leaders in a letter to urge their members ``to do all you can by 
donating your means and time to assure a successful vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later that month, a second letter from a church elder, also on  
church letterhead, explained the donations should not be solicited 
on church grounds or during church meetings or using church 
stationery. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign manager Rob Stutzman said the only church money spent  
was $50 in postage to send the two letters, the same sort of 
expenditures made by Roman Catholic and Protestant churches. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Rothman, an attorney and certified public accountant at  
Loeb &AMP; Trouber in New York, said the church probably is in the 
clear. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mormons could run into trouble, he said, if church leaders  
advocate for or against a particular candidate, use a substantial 
portion of their tax-deductible funds for political activities, or 
ask that donations be made directly to the church to support the 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``A ballot issue would absolutely fall into the category of  
lobbying as opposed to political intervention,'' Rothman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
